 109 # goal is to be able to define the docs close to function, while still being
 110 # able to share
 111 _shared_docs: Dict[str, str] = dict()
 112 _shared_doc_kwargs = dict(
 113     axes="keywords for axes",
 114     klass="Series/DataFrame",
 115     axes_single_arg="int or labels for object",
 116     args_transpose="axes to permute (int or label for object)",
 117     optional_by="""
 118         by : str or list of str
 119             Name or list of names to sort by""",
 120 )

 123 def _single_replace(self, to_replace, method, inplace, limit):
 124     """
 125     Replaces values in a Series using the fill method specified when no
 126     replacement value is given in the replace method
 127     """
 128     if self.ndim != 1:
 129         raise TypeError(
 130             f"cannot replace {to_replace} with method {method} on a "
 131             f"{type(self).__name__}"
 132         )
 133 
 134     orig_dtype = self.dtype
 135     result = self if inplace else self.copy()
 136     fill_f = missing.get_fill_func(method)
 137 
 138     mask = missing.mask_missing(result.values, to_replace)
 139     values = fill_f(result.values, limit=limit, mask=mask)
 140 
 141     if values.dtype == orig_dtype and inplace:
 142         return
 143 
 144     result = pd.Series(values, index=self.index, dtype=self.dtype).__finalize__(self)
 145 
 146     if inplace:
 147         self._update_inplace(result)
 148         return
 149 
 150     return result

 153 bool_t = bool  # Need alias because NDFrame has def bool:

 155 
 156 class NDFrame(PandasObject, SelectionMixin, indexing.IndexingMixin):
 157     """
 158     N-dimensional analogue of DataFrame. Store multi-dimensional in a
 159     size-mutable, labeled data structure
 160 
 161     Parameters
 162     ----------
 163     data : BlockManager
 164     axes : list
 165     copy : bool, default False
 166     """
 167 
 168     _internal_names: List[str] = [
 169         "_mgr",
 170         "_cacher",
 171         "_item_cache",
 172         "_cache",
 173         "_is_copy",
 174         "_subtyp",
 175         "_name",
 176         "_index",
 177         "_default_kind",
 178         "_default_fill_value",
 179         "_metadata",
 180         "__array_struct__",
 181         "__array_interface__",
 182     ]
 183     _internal_names_set: Set[str] = set(_internal_names)
 184     _accessors: Set[str] = set()
 185     _deprecations: FrozenSet[str] = frozenset(["get_values"])
 186     _metadata: List[str] = []
 187     _is_copy = None
 188     _mgr: BlockManager
 189     _attrs: Dict[Optional[Hashable], Any]
 190     _typ: str
 191 
 192     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 193     # Constructors
 194 
 195     def __init__(
 196         self,
 197         data: BlockManager,
 198         copy: bool = False,
 199         attrs: Optional[Mapping[Optional[Hashable], Any]] = None,
 200     ):
 201         # copy kwarg is retained for mypy compat, is not used
 202 
 203         object.__setattr__(self, "_is_copy", None)
 204         object.__setattr__(self, "_mgr", data)
 205         object.__setattr__(self, "_item_cache", {})
 206         if attrs is None:
 207             attrs = {}
 208         else:
 209             attrs = dict(attrs)
 210         object.__setattr__(self, "_attrs", attrs)
 211 
 212     @classmethod
 213     def _init_mgr(cls, mgr, axes, dtype=None, copy: bool = False) -> BlockManager:
 214         """ passed a manager and a axes dict """
 215         for a, axe in axes.items():
 216             if axe is not None:
 217                 axe = ensure_index(axe)
 218                 bm_axis = cls._get_block_manager_axis(a)
 219                 mgr = mgr.reindex_axis(axe, axis=bm_axis, copy=False)
 220 
 221         # make a copy if explicitly requested
 222         if copy:
 223             mgr = mgr.copy()
 224         if dtype is not None:
 225             # avoid further copies if we can
 226             if len(mgr.blocks) > 1 or mgr.blocks[0].values.dtype != dtype:
 227                 mgr = mgr.astype(dtype=dtype)
 228         return mgr
 229 
 230     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 231 
 232     @property
 233     def attrs(self) -> Dict[Optional[Hashable], Any]:
 234         """
 235         Dictionary of global attributes on this object.
 236 
 237         .. warning::
 238 
 239            attrs is experimental and may change without warning.
 240         """
 241         if self._attrs is None:
 242             self._attrs = {}
 243         return self._attrs
 244 
 245     @attrs.setter
 246     def attrs(self, value: Mapping[Optional[Hashable], Any]) -> None:
 247         self._attrs = dict(value)
 248 
 249     @classmethod
 250     def _validate_dtype(cls, dtype):
 251         """ validate the passed dtype """
 252         if dtype is not None:
 253             dtype = pandas_dtype(dtype)
 254 
 255             # a compound dtype
 256             if dtype.kind == "V":
 257                 raise NotImplementedError(
 258                     "compound dtypes are not implemented "
 259                     f"in the {cls.__name__} constructor"
 260                 )
 261 
 262         return dtype
 263 
 264     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 265     # Construction
 266 
 267     @property
 268     def _constructor(self: FrameOrSeries) -> Type[FrameOrSeries]:
 269         """
 270         Used when a manipulation result has the same dimensions as the
 271         original.
 272         """
 273         raise AbstractMethodError(self)
 274 
 275     @property
 276     def _constructor_sliced(self):
 277         """
 278         Used when a manipulation result has one lower dimension(s) as the
 279         original, such as DataFrame single columns slicing.
 280         """
 281         raise AbstractMethodError(self)
 282 
 283     @property
 284     def _constructor_expanddim(self):
 285         """
 286         Used when a manipulation result has one higher dimension as the
 287         original, such as Series.to_frame()
 288         """
 289         raise NotImplementedError
 290 
 291     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 292     # Internals
 293 
 294     @property
 295     def _data(self):
 296         # GH#33054 retained because some downstream packages uses this,
 297         #  e.g. fastparquet
 298         return self._mgr
 299 
 300     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 301     # Axis
 302     _stat_axis_number = 0
 303     _stat_axis_name = "index"
 304     _ix = None
 305     _AXIS_ORDERS: List[str]
 306     _AXIS_TO_AXIS_NUMBER: Dict[Axis, int] = {0: 0, "index": 0, "rows": 0}
 307     _AXIS_REVERSED: bool
 308     _info_axis_number: int
 309     _info_axis_name: str
 310     _AXIS_LEN: int
 311 
 312     @property
 313     def _AXIS_NUMBERS(self) -> Dict[str, int]:
 314         """.. deprecated:: 1.1.0"""
 315         warnings.warn(
 316             "_AXIS_NUMBERS has been deprecated.", FutureWarning, stacklevel=3,
 317         )
 318         return {"index": 0}
 319 
 320     @property
 321     def _AXIS_NAMES(self) -> Dict[int, str]:
 322         """.. deprecated:: 1.1.0"""
 323         warnings.warn(
 324             "_AXIS_NAMES has been deprecated.", FutureWarning, stacklevel=3,
 325         )
 326         return {0: "index"}
 327 
 328     def _construct_axes_dict(self, axes=None, **kwargs):
 329         """Return an axes dictionary for myself."""
 330         d = {a: self._get_axis(a) for a in (axes or self._AXIS_ORDERS)}
 331         d.update(kwargs)
 332         return d
 333 
 334     @classmethod
 335     def _construct_axes_from_arguments(
 336         cls, args, kwargs, require_all: bool = False, sentinel=None
 337     ):
 338         """
 339         Construct and returns axes if supplied in args/kwargs.
 340 
 341         If require_all, raise if all axis arguments are not supplied
 342         return a tuple of (axes, kwargs).
 343 
 344         sentinel specifies the default parameter when an axis is not
 345         supplied; useful to distinguish when a user explicitly passes None
 346         in scenarios where None has special meaning.
 347         """
 348         # construct the args
 349         args = list(args)
 350         for a in cls._AXIS_ORDERS:
 351 
 352             # look for a argument by position
 353             if a not in kwargs:
 354                 try:
 355                     kwargs[a] = args.pop(0)
 356                 except IndexError as err:
 357                     if require_all:
 358                         raise TypeError(
 359                             "not enough/duplicate arguments specified!"
 360                         ) from err
 361 
 362         axes = {a: kwargs.pop(a, sentinel) for a in cls._AXIS_ORDERS}
 363         return axes, kwargs
 364 
 365     @classmethod
 366     def _get_axis_number(cls, axis: Axis) -> int:
 367         try:
 368             return cls._AXIS_TO_AXIS_NUMBER[axis]
 369         except KeyError:
 370             raise ValueError(f"No axis named {axis} for object type {cls.__name__}")
 371 
 372     @classmethod
 373     def _get_axis_name(cls, axis: Axis) -> str:
 374         axis_number = cls._get_axis_number(axis)
 375         return cls._AXIS_ORDERS[axis_number]
 376 
 377     def _get_axis(self, axis: Axis) -> Index:
 378         axis_number = self._get_axis_number(axis)
 379         assert axis_number in {0, 1}
 380         return self.index if axis_number == 0 else self.columns
 381 
 382     @classmethod
 383     def _get_block_manager_axis(cls, axis: Axis) -> int:
 384         """Map the axis to the block_manager axis."""
 385         axis = cls._get_axis_number(axis)
 386         if cls._AXIS_REVERSED:
 387             m = cls._AXIS_LEN - 1
 388             return m - axis
 389         return axis
 390 
 391     def _get_axis_resolvers(self, axis: str) -> Dict[str, ABCSeries]:
 392         # index or columns
 393         axis_index = getattr(self, axis)
 394         d = dict()
 395         prefix = axis[0]
 396 
 397         for i, name in enumerate(axis_index.names):
 398             if name is not None:
 399                 key = level = name
 400             else:
 401                 # prefix with 'i' or 'c' depending on the input axis
 402                 # e.g., you must do ilevel_0 for the 0th level of an unnamed
 403                 # multiiindex
 404                 key = f"{prefix}level_{i}"
 405                 level = i
 406 
 407             level_values = axis_index.get_level_values(level)
 408             s = level_values.to_series()
 409             s.index = axis_index
 410             d[key] = s
 411 
 412         # put the index/columns itself in the dict
 413         if isinstance(axis_index, MultiIndex):
 414             dindex = axis_index
 415         else:
 416             dindex = axis_index.to_series()
 417 
 418         d[axis] = dindex
 419         return d
 420 
 421     def _get_index_resolvers(self) -> Dict[str, ABCSeries]:
 422         from pandas.core.computation.parsing import clean_column_name
 423 
 424         d: Dict[str, ABCSeries] = {}
 425         for axis_name in self._AXIS_ORDERS:
 426             d.update(self._get_axis_resolvers(axis_name))
 427 
 428         return {clean_column_name(k): v for k, v in d.items() if not isinstance(k, int)}
 429 
 430     def _get_cleaned_column_resolvers(self) -> Dict[str, ABCSeries]:
 431         """
 432         Return the special character free column resolvers of a dataframe.
 433 
 434         Column names with special characters are 'cleaned up' so that they can
 435         be referred to by backtick quoting.
 436         Used in :meth:`DataFrame.eval`.
 437         """
 438         from pandas.core.computation.parsing import clean_column_name
 439 
 440         if isinstance(self, ABCSeries):
 441             return {clean_column_name(self.name): self}
 442 
 443         return {
 444             clean_column_name(k): v for k, v in self.items() if not isinstance(k, int)
 445         }
 446 
 447     @property
 448     def _info_axis(self) -> Index:
 449         return getattr(self, self._info_axis_name)
 450 
 451     @property
 452     def _stat_axis(self) -> Index:
 453         return getattr(self, self._stat_axis_name)
 454 
 455     @property
 456     def shape(self) -> Tuple[int, ...]:
 457         """
 458         Return a tuple of axis dimensions
 459         """
 460         return tuple(len(self._get_axis(a)) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS)
 461 
 462     @property
 463     def axes(self) -> List[Index]:
 464         """
 465         Return index label(s) of the internal NDFrame
 466         """
 467         # we do it this way because if we have reversed axes, then
 468         # the block manager shows then reversed
 469         return [self._get_axis(a) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS]
 470 
 471     @property
 472     def ndim(self) -> int:
 473         """
 474         Return an int representing the number of axes / array dimensions.
 475 
 476         Return 1 if Series. Otherwise return 2 if DataFrame.
 477 
 478         See Also
 479         --------
 480         ndarray.ndim : Number of array dimensions.
 481 
 482         Examples
 483         --------
 484         >>> s = pd.Series({'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 3})
 485         >>> s.ndim
 486         1
 487 
 488         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'col1': [1, 2], 'col2': [3, 4]})
 489         >>> df.ndim
 490         2
 491         """
 492         return self._mgr.ndim
 493 
 494     @property
 495     def size(self) -> int:
 496         """
 497         Return an int representing the number of elements in this object.
 498 
 499         Return the number of rows if Series. Otherwise return the number of
 500         rows times number of columns if DataFrame.
 501 
 502         See Also
 503         --------
 504         ndarray.size : Number of elements in the array.
 505 
 506         Examples
 507         --------
 508         >>> s = pd.Series({'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 3})
 509         >>> s.size
 510         3
 511 
 512         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'col1': [1, 2], 'col2': [3, 4]})
 513         >>> df.size
 514         4
 515         """
 516         return np.prod(self.shape)
 517 
 518     @property
 519     def _selected_obj(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
 520         """ internal compat with SelectionMixin """
 521         return self
 522 
 523     @property
 524     def _obj_with_exclusions(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
 525         """ internal compat with SelectionMixin """
 526         return self
 527 
 528     def set_axis(self, labels, axis: Axis = 0, inplace: bool = False):
 529         """
 530         Assign desired index to given axis.
 531 
 532         Indexes for%(extended_summary_sub)s row labels can be changed by assigning
 533         a list-like or Index.
 534 
 535         Parameters
 536         ----------
 537         labels : list-like, Index
 538             The values for the new index.
 539 
 540         axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default 0
 541             The axis to update. The value 0 identifies the rows%(axis_description_sub)s.
 542 
 543         inplace : bool, default False
 544             Whether to return a new %(klass)s instance.
 545 
 546         Returns
 547         -------
 548         renamed : %(klass)s or None
 549             An object of type %(klass)s if inplace=False, None otherwise.
 550 
 551         See Also
 552         --------
 553         %(klass)s.rename_axis : Alter the name of the index%(see_also_sub)s.
 554         """
 555         if inplace:
 556             setattr(self, self._get_axis_name(axis), labels)
 557         else:
 558             obj = self.copy()
 559             obj.set_axis(labels, axis=axis, inplace=True)
 560             return obj
 561 
 562     def _set_axis(self, axis: int, labels: Index) -> None:
 563         labels = ensure_index(labels)
 564         self._mgr.set_axis(axis, labels)
 565         self._clear_item_cache()
 566 
 567     def swapaxes(self: FrameOrSeries, axis1, axis2, copy=True) -> FrameOrSeries:
 568         """
 569         Interchange axes and swap values axes appropriately.
 570 
 571         Returns
 572         -------
 573         y : same as input
 574         """
 575         i = self._get_axis_number(axis1)
 576         j = self._get_axis_number(axis2)
 577 
 578         if i == j:
 579             if copy:
 580                 return self.copy()
 581             return self
 582 
 583         mapping = {i: j, j: i}
 584 
 585         new_axes = (self._get_axis(mapping.get(k, k)) for k in range(self._AXIS_LEN))
 586         new_values = self.values.swapaxes(i, j)
 587         if copy:
 588             new_values = new_values.copy()
 589 
 590         # ignore needed because of NDFrame constructor is different than
 591         # DataFrame/Series constructors.
 592         return self._constructor(new_values, *new_axes).__finalize__(  # type: ignore
 593             self, method="swapaxes"
 594         )
 595 
 596     def droplevel(self: FrameOrSeries, level, axis=0) -> FrameOrSeries:
 597         """
 598         Return DataFrame with requested index / column level(s) removed.
 599 
 600         .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
 601 
 602         Parameters
 603         ----------
 604         level : int, str, or list-like
 605             If a string is given, must be the name of a level
 606             If list-like, elements must be names or positional indexes
 607             of levels.
 608 
 609         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
 610             Axis along which the level(s) is removed:
 611 
 612             * 0 or 'index': remove level(s) in column.
 613             * 1 or 'columns': remove level(s) in row.
 614 
 615         Returns
 616         -------
 617         DataFrame
 618             DataFrame with requested index / column level(s) removed.
 619 
 620         Examples
 621         --------
 622         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([
 623         ...     [1, 2, 3, 4],
 624         ...     [5, 6, 7, 8],
 625         ...     [9, 10, 11, 12]
 626         ... ]).set_index([0, 1]).rename_axis(['a', 'b'])
 627 
 628         >>> df.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([
 629         ...     ('c', 'e'), ('d', 'f')
 630         ... ], names=['level_1', 'level_2'])
 631 
 632         >>> df
 633         level_1   c   d
 634         level_2   e   f
 635         a b
 636         1 2      3   4
 637         5 6      7   8
 638         9 10    11  12
 639 
 640         >>> df.droplevel('a')
 641         level_1   c   d
 642         level_2   e   f
 643         b
 644         2        3   4
 645         6        7   8
 646         10      11  12
 647 
 648         >>> df.droplevel('level_2', axis=1)
 649         level_1   c   d
 650         a b
 651         1 2      3   4
 652         5 6      7   8
 653         9 10    11  12
 654         """
 655         labels = self._get_axis(axis)
 656         new_labels = labels.droplevel(level)
 657         result = self.set_axis(new_labels, axis=axis, inplace=False)
 658         return result
 659 
 660     def pop(self: FrameOrSeries, item) -> FrameOrSeries:
 661         """
 662         Return item and drop from frame. Raise KeyError if not found.
 663 
 664         Parameters
 665         ----------
 666         item : str
 667             Label of column to be popped.
 668 
 669         Returns
 670         -------
 671         Series
 672 
 673         Examples
 674         --------
 675         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0),
 676         ...                    ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0),
 677         ...                    ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5),
 678         ...                    ('monkey', 'mammal', np.nan)],
 679         ...                   columns=('name', 'class', 'max_speed'))
 680         >>> df
 681              name   class  max_speed
 682         0  falcon    bird      389.0
 683         1  parrot    bird       24.0
 684         2    lion  mammal       80.5
 685         3  monkey  mammal        NaN
 686 
 687         >>> df.pop('class')
 688         0      bird
 689         1      bird
 690         2    mammal
 691         3    mammal
 692         Name: class, dtype: object
 693 
 694         >>> df
 695              name  max_speed
 696         0  falcon      389.0
 697         1  parrot       24.0
 698         2    lion       80.5
 699         3  monkey        NaN
 700         """
 701         result = self[item]
 702         del self[item]
 703         if self.ndim == 2:
 704             result._reset_cacher()
 705 
 706         return result
 707 
 708     def squeeze(self, axis=None):
 709         """
 710         Squeeze 1 dimensional axis objects into scalars.
 711 
 712         Series or DataFrames with a single element are squeezed to a scalar.
 713         DataFrames with a single column or a single row are squeezed to a
 714         Series. Otherwise the object is unchanged.
 715 
 716         This method is most useful when you don't know if your
 717         object is a Series or DataFrame, but you do know it has just a single
 718         column. In that case you can safely call `squeeze` to ensure you have a
 719         Series.
 720 
 721         Parameters
 722         ----------
 723         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None
 724             A specific axis to squeeze. By default, all length-1 axes are
 725             squeezed.
 726 
 727         Returns
 728         -------
 729         DataFrame, Series, or scalar
 730             The projection after squeezing `axis` or all the axes.
 731 
 732         See Also
 733         --------
 734         Series.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting scalars.
 735         DataFrame.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting Series.
 736         Series.to_frame : Inverse of DataFrame.squeeze for a
 737             single-column DataFrame.
 738 
 739         Examples
 740         --------
 741         >>> primes = pd.Series([2, 3, 5, 7])
 742 
 743         Slicing might produce a Series with a single value:
 744 
 745         >>> even_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 0]
 746         >>> even_primes
 747         0    2
 748         dtype: int64
 749 
 750         >>> even_primes.squeeze()
 751         2
 752 
 753         Squeezing objects with more than one value in every axis does nothing:
 754 
 755         >>> odd_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 1]
 756         >>> odd_primes
 757         1    3
 758         2    5
 759         3    7
 760         dtype: int64
 761 
 762         >>> odd_primes.squeeze()
 763         1    3
 764         2    5
 765         3    7
 766         dtype: int64
 767 
 768         Squeezing is even more effective when used with DataFrames.
 769 
 770         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2], [3, 4]], columns=['a', 'b'])
 771         >>> df
 772            a  b
 773         0  1  2
 774         1  3  4
 775 
 776         Slicing a single column will produce a DataFrame with the columns
 777         having only one value:
 778 
 779         >>> df_a = df[['a']]
 780         >>> df_a
 781            a
 782         0  1
 783         1  3
 784 
 785         So the columns can be squeezed down, resulting in a Series:
 786 
 787         >>> df_a.squeeze('columns')
 788         0    1
 789         1    3
 790         Name: a, dtype: int64
 791 
 792         Slicing a single row from a single column will produce a single
 793         scalar DataFrame:
 794 
 795         >>> df_0a = df.loc[df.index < 1, ['a']]
 796         >>> df_0a
 797            a
 798         0  1
 799 
 800         Squeezing the rows produces a single scalar Series:
 801 
 802         >>> df_0a.squeeze('rows')
 803         a    1
 804         Name: 0, dtype: int64
 805 
 806         Squeezing all axes will project directly into a scalar:
 807 
 808         >>> df_0a.squeeze()
 809         1
 810         """
 811         axis = range(self._AXIS_LEN) if axis is None else (self._get_axis_number(axis),)
 812         return self.iloc[
 813             tuple(
 814                 0 if i in axis and len(a) == 1 else slice(None)
 815                 for i, a in enumerate(self.axes)
 816             )
 817         ]
 818 
 819     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 820     # Rename
 821 
 822     def rename(
 823         self: FrameOrSeries,
 824         mapper: Optional[Renamer] = None,
 825         *,
 826         index: Optional[Renamer] = None,
 827         columns: Optional[Renamer] = None,
 828         axis: Optional[Axis] = None,
 829         copy: bool = True,
 830         inplace: bool = False,
 831         level: Optional[Level] = None,
 832         errors: str = "ignore",
 833     ) -> Optional[FrameOrSeries]:
 834         """
 835         Alter axes input function or functions. Function / dict values must be
 836         unique (1-to-1). Labels not contained in a dict / Series will be left
 837         as-is. Extra labels listed don't throw an error. Alternatively, change
 838         ``Series.name`` with a scalar value (Series only).
 839 
 840         Parameters
 841         ----------
 842         %(axes)s : scalar, list-like, dict-like or function, optional
 843             Scalar or list-like will alter the ``Series.name`` attribute,
 844             and raise on DataFrame.
 845             dict-like or functions are transformations to apply to
 846             that axis' values
 847         copy : bool, default True
 848             Also copy underlying data.
 849         inplace : bool, default False
 850             Whether to return a new %(klass)s. If True then value of copy is
 851             ignored.
 852         level : int or level name, default None
 853             In case of a MultiIndex, only rename labels in the specified
 854             level.
 855         errors : {'ignore', 'raise'}, default 'ignore'
 856             If 'raise', raise a `KeyError` when a dict-like `mapper`, `index`,
 857             or `columns` contains labels that are not present in the Index
 858             being transformed.
 859             If 'ignore', existing keys will be renamed and extra keys will be
 860             ignored.
 861 
 862         Returns
 863         -------
 864         renamed : %(klass)s (new object)
 865 
 866         Raises
 867         ------
 868         KeyError
 869             If any of the labels is not found in the selected axis and
 870             "errors='raise'".
 871 
 872         See Also
 873         --------
 874         NDFrame.rename_axis
 875 
 876         Examples
 877         --------
 878         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3])
 879         >>> s
 880         0    1
 881         1    2
 882         2    3
 883         dtype: int64
 884         >>> s.rename("my_name") # scalar, changes Series.name
 885         0    1
 886         1    2
 887         2    3
 888         Name: my_name, dtype: int64
 889         >>> s.rename(lambda x: x ** 2)  # function, changes labels
 890         0    1
 891         1    2
 892         4    3
 893         dtype: int64
 894         >>> s.rename({1: 3, 2: 5})  # mapping, changes labels
 895         0    1
 896         3    2
 897         5    3
 898         dtype: int64
 899 
 900         Since ``DataFrame`` doesn't have a ``.name`` attribute,
 901         only mapping-type arguments are allowed.
 902 
 903         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2, 3], "B": [4, 5, 6]})
 904         >>> df.rename(2)
 905         Traceback (most recent call last):
 906         ...
 907         TypeError: 'int' object is not callable
 908 
 909         ``DataFrame.rename`` supports two calling conventions
 910 
 911         * ``(index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, ...)``
 912         * ``(mapper, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)``
 913 
 914         We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your
 915         intent.
 916 
 917         >>> df.rename(index=str, columns={"A": "a", "B": "c"})
 918            a  c
 919         0  1  4
 920         1  2  5
 921         2  3  6
 922 
 923         >>> df.rename(index=str, columns={"A": "a", "C": "c"})
 924            a  B
 925         0  1  4
 926         1  2  5
 927         2  3  6
 928 
 929         Using axis-style parameters
 930 
 931         >>> df.rename(str.lower, axis='columns')
 932            a  b
 933         0  1  4
 934         1  2  5
 935         2  3  6
 936 
 937         >>> df.rename({1: 2, 2: 4}, axis='index')
 938            A  B
 939         0  1  4
 940         2  2  5
 941         4  3  6
 942 
 943         See the :ref:`user guide <basics.rename>` for more.
 944         """
 945         if mapper is None and index is None and columns is None:
 946             raise TypeError("must pass an index to rename")
 947 
 948         if index is not None or columns is not None:
 949             if axis is not None:
 950                 raise TypeError(
 951                     "Cannot specify both 'axis' and any of 'index' or 'columns'"
 952                 )
 953             elif mapper is not None:
 954                 raise TypeError(
 955                     "Cannot specify both 'mapper' and any of 'index' or 'columns'"
 956                 )
 957         else:
 958             # use the mapper argument
 959             if axis and self._get_axis_number(axis) == 1:
 960                 columns = mapper
 961             else:
 962                 index = mapper
 963 
 964         result = self if inplace else self.copy(deep=copy)
 965 
 966         for axis_no, replacements in enumerate((index, columns)):
 967             if replacements is None:
 968                 continue
 969 
 970             ax = self._get_axis(axis_no)
 971             f = com.get_rename_function(replacements)
 972 
 973             if level is not None:
 974                 level = ax._get_level_number(level)
 975 
 976             # GH 13473
 977             if not callable(replacements):
 978                 indexer = ax.get_indexer_for(replacements)
 979                 if errors == "raise" and len(indexer[indexer == -1]):
 980                     missing_labels = [
 981                         label
 982                         for index, label in enumerate(replacements)
 983                         if indexer[index] == -1
 984                     ]
 985                     raise KeyError(f"{missing_labels} not found in axis")
 986 
 987             new_index = ax._transform_index(f, level)
 988             result.set_axis(new_index, axis=axis_no, inplace=True)
 989             result._clear_item_cache()
 990 
 991         if inplace:
 992             self._update_inplace(result)
 993             return None
 994         else:
 995             return result.__finalize__(self, method="rename")
 996 
 997     @rewrite_axis_style_signature("mapper", [("copy", True), ("inplace", False)])
 998     def rename_axis(self, mapper=lib.no_default, **kwargs):
 999         """
1000         Set the name of the axis for the index or columns.
1001 
1002         Parameters
1003         ----------
1004         mapper : scalar, list-like, optional
1005             Value to set the axis name attribute.
1006         index, columns : scalar, list-like, dict-like or function, optional
1007             A scalar, list-like, dict-like or functions transformations to
1008             apply to that axis' values.
1009             Note that the ``columns`` parameter is not allowed if the
1010             object is a Series. This parameter only apply for DataFrame
1011             type objects.
1012 
1013             Use either ``mapper`` and ``axis`` to
1014             specify the axis to target with ``mapper``, or ``index``
1015             and/or ``columns``.
1016 
1017             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0
1018 
1019         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
1020             The axis to rename.
1021         copy : bool, default True
1022             Also copy underlying data.
1023         inplace : bool, default False
1024             Modifies the object directly, instead of creating a new Series
1025             or DataFrame.
1026 
1027         Returns
1028         -------
1029         Series, DataFrame, or None
1030             The same type as the caller or None if `inplace` is True.
1031 
1032         See Also
1033         --------
1034         Series.rename : Alter Series index labels or name.
1035         DataFrame.rename : Alter DataFrame index labels or name.
1036         Index.rename : Set new names on index.
1037 
1038         Notes
1039         -----
1040         ``DataFrame.rename_axis`` supports two calling conventions
1041 
1042         * ``(index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, ...)``
1043         * ``(mapper, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)``
1044 
1045         The first calling convention will only modify the names of
1046         the index and/or the names of the Index object that is the columns.
1047         In this case, the parameter ``copy`` is ignored.
1048 
1049         The second calling convention will modify the names of the
1050         the corresponding index if mapper is a list or a scalar.
1051         However, if mapper is dict-like or a function, it will use the
1052         deprecated behavior of modifying the axis *labels*.
1053 
1054         We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your
1055         intent.
1056 
1057         Examples
1058         --------
1059         **Series**
1060 
1061         >>> s = pd.Series(["dog", "cat", "monkey"])
1062         >>> s
1063         0       dog
1064         1       cat
1065         2    monkey
1066         dtype: object
1067         >>> s.rename_axis("animal")
1068         animal
1069         0    dog
1070         1    cat
1071         2    monkey
1072         dtype: object
1073 
1074         **DataFrame**
1075 
1076         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"num_legs": [4, 4, 2],
1077         ...                    "num_arms": [0, 0, 2]},
1078         ...                   ["dog", "cat", "monkey"])
1079         >>> df
1080                 num_legs  num_arms
1081         dog            4         0
1082         cat            4         0
1083         monkey         2         2
1084         >>> df = df.rename_axis("animal")
1085         >>> df
1086                 num_legs  num_arms
1087         animal
1088         dog            4         0
1089         cat            4         0
1090         monkey         2         2
1091         >>> df = df.rename_axis("limbs", axis="columns")
1092         >>> df
1093         limbs   num_legs  num_arms
1094         animal
1095         dog            4         0
1096         cat            4         0
1097         monkey         2         2
1098 
1099         **MultiIndex**
1100 
1101         >>> df.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([['mammal'],
1102         ...                                        ['dog', 'cat', 'monkey']],
1103         ...                                       names=['type', 'name'])
1104         >>> df
1105         limbs          num_legs  num_arms
1106         type   name
1107         mammal dog            4         0
1108                cat            4         0
1109                monkey         2         2
1110 
1111         >>> df.rename_axis(index={'type': 'class'})
1112         limbs          num_legs  num_arms
1113         class  name
1114         mammal dog            4         0
1115                cat            4         0
1116                monkey         2         2
1117 
1118         >>> df.rename_axis(columns=str.upper)
1119         LIMBS          num_legs  num_arms
1120         type   name
1121         mammal dog            4         0
1122                cat            4         0
1123                monkey         2         2
1124         """
1125         axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments(
1126             (), kwargs, sentinel=lib.no_default
1127         )
1128         copy = kwargs.pop("copy", True)
1129         inplace = kwargs.pop("inplace", False)
1130         axis = kwargs.pop("axis", 0)
1131         if axis is not None:
1132             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
1133 
1134         if kwargs:
1135             raise TypeError(
1136                 "rename_axis() got an unexpected keyword "
1137                 f'argument "{list(kwargs.keys())[0]}"'
1138             )
1139 
1140         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
1141 
1142         if mapper is not lib.no_default:
1143             # Use v0.23 behavior if a scalar or list
1144             non_mapper = is_scalar(mapper) or (
1145                 is_list_like(mapper) and not is_dict_like(mapper)
1146             )
1147             if non_mapper:
1148                 return self._set_axis_name(mapper, axis=axis, inplace=inplace)
1149             else:
1150                 raise ValueError("Use `.rename` to alter labels with a mapper.")
1151         else:
1152             # Use new behavior.  Means that index and/or columns
1153             # is specified
1154             result = self if inplace else self.copy(deep=copy)
1155 
1156             for axis in range(self._AXIS_LEN):
1157                 v = axes.get(self._get_axis_name(axis))
1158                 if v is lib.no_default:
1159                     continue
1160                 non_mapper = is_scalar(v) or (is_list_like(v) and not is_dict_like(v))
1161                 if non_mapper:
1162                     newnames = v
1163                 else:
1164                     f = com.get_rename_function(v)
1165                     curnames = self._get_axis(axis).names
1166                     newnames = [f(name) for name in curnames]
1167                 result._set_axis_name(newnames, axis=axis, inplace=True)
1168             if not inplace:
1169                 return result
1170 
1171     def _set_axis_name(self, name, axis=0, inplace=False):
1172         """
1173         Set the name(s) of the axis.
1174 
1175         Parameters
1176         ----------
1177         name : str or list of str
1178             Name(s) to set.
1179         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
1180             The axis to set the label. The value 0 or 'index' specifies index,
1181             and the value 1 or 'columns' specifies columns.
1182         inplace : bool, default False
1183             If `True`, do operation inplace and return None.
1184 
1185         Returns
1186         -------
1187         Series, DataFrame, or None
1188             The same type as the caller or `None` if `inplace` is `True`.
1189 
1190         See Also
1191         --------
1192         DataFrame.rename : Alter the axis labels of :class:`DataFrame`.
1193         Series.rename : Alter the index labels or set the index name
1194             of :class:`Series`.
1195         Index.rename : Set the name of :class:`Index` or :class:`MultiIndex`.
1196 
1197         Examples
1198         --------
1199         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"num_legs": [4, 4, 2]},
1200         ...                   ["dog", "cat", "monkey"])
1201         >>> df
1202                 num_legs
1203         dog            4
1204         cat            4
1205         monkey         2
1206         >>> df._set_axis_name("animal")
1207                 num_legs
1208         animal
1209         dog            4
1210         cat            4
1211         monkey         2
1212         >>> df.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product(
1213         ...                [["mammal"], ['dog', 'cat', 'monkey']])
1214         >>> df._set_axis_name(["type", "name"])
1215                        num_legs
1216         type   name
1217         mammal dog        4
1218                cat        4
1219                monkey     2
1220         """
1221         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
1222         idx = self._get_axis(axis).set_names(name)
1223 
1224         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
1225         renamed = self if inplace else self.copy()
1226         renamed.set_axis(idx, axis=axis, inplace=True)
1227         if not inplace:
1228             return renamed
1229 
1230     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
1231     # Comparison Methods
1232 
1233     def _indexed_same(self, other) -> bool:
1234         return all(
1235             self._get_axis(a).equals(other._get_axis(a)) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS
1236         )
1237 
1238     def equals(self, other):
1239         """
1240         Test whether two objects contain the same elements.
1241 
1242         This function allows two Series or DataFrames to be compared against
1243         each other to see if they have the same shape and elements. NaNs in
1244         the same location are considered equal. The column headers do not
1245         need to have the same type, but the elements within the columns must
1246         be the same dtype.
1247 
1248         Parameters
1249         ----------
1250         other : Series or DataFrame
1251             The other Series or DataFrame to be compared with the first.
1252 
1253         Returns
1254         -------
1255         bool
1256             True if all elements are the same in both objects, False
1257             otherwise.
1258 
1259         See Also
1260         --------
1261         Series.eq : Compare two Series objects of the same length
1262             and return a Series where each element is True if the element
1263             in each Series is equal, False otherwise.
1264         DataFrame.eq : Compare two DataFrame objects of the same shape and
1265             return a DataFrame where each element is True if the respective
1266             element in each DataFrame is equal, False otherwise.
1267         testing.assert_series_equal : Raises an AssertionError if left and
1268             right are not equal. Provides an easy interface to ignore
1269             inequality in dtypes, indexes and precision among others.
1270         testing.assert_frame_equal : Like assert_series_equal, but targets
1271             DataFrames.
1272         numpy.array_equal : Return True if two arrays have the same shape
1273             and elements, False otherwise.
1274 
1275         Notes
1276         -----
1277         This function requires that the elements have the same dtype as their
1278         respective elements in the other Series or DataFrame. However, the
1279         column labels do not need to have the same type, as long as they are
1280         still considered equal.
1281 
1282         Examples
1283         --------
1284         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({1: [10], 2: [20]})
1285         >>> df
1286             1   2
1287         0  10  20
1288 
1289         DataFrames df and exactly_equal have the same types and values for
1290         their elements and column labels, which will return True.
1291 
1292         >>> exactly_equal = pd.DataFrame({1: [10], 2: [20]})
1293         >>> exactly_equal
1294             1   2
1295         0  10  20
1296         >>> df.equals(exactly_equal)
1297         True
1298 
1299         DataFrames df and different_column_type have the same element
1300         types and values, but have different types for the column labels,
1301         which will still return True.
1302 
1303         >>> different_column_type = pd.DataFrame({1.0: [10], 2.0: [20]})
1304         >>> different_column_type
1305            1.0  2.0
1306         0   10   20
1307         >>> df.equals(different_column_type)
1308         True
1309 
1310         DataFrames df and different_data_type have different types for the
1311         same values for their elements, and will return False even though
1312         their column labels are the same values and types.
1313 
1314         >>> different_data_type = pd.DataFrame({1: [10.0], 2: [20.0]})
1315         >>> different_data_type
1316               1     2
1317         0  10.0  20.0
1318         >>> df.equals(different_data_type)
1319         False
1320         """
1321         if not isinstance(other, self._constructor):
1322             return False
1323         return self._mgr.equals(other._mgr)
1324 
1325     # -------------------------------------------------------------------------
1326     # Unary Methods
1327 
1328     def __neg__(self):
1329         values = self._values
1330         if is_bool_dtype(values):
1331             arr = operator.inv(values)
1332         elif (
1333             is_numeric_dtype(values)
1334             or is_timedelta64_dtype(values)
1335             or is_object_dtype(values)
1336         ):
1337             arr = operator.neg(values)
1338         else:
1339             raise TypeError(f"Unary negative expects numeric dtype, not {values.dtype}")
1340         return self.__array_wrap__(arr)
1341 
1342     def __pos__(self):
1343         values = self._values
1344         if is_bool_dtype(values):
1345             arr = values
1346         elif (
1347             is_numeric_dtype(values)
1348             or is_timedelta64_dtype(values)
1349             or is_object_dtype(values)
1350         ):
1351             arr = operator.pos(values)
1352         else:
1353             raise TypeError(f"Unary plus expects numeric dtype, not {values.dtype}")
1354         return self.__array_wrap__(arr)
1355 
1356     def __invert__(self):
1357         if not self.size:
1358             # inv fails with 0 len
1359             return self
1360 
1361         new_data = self._mgr.apply(operator.invert)
1362         result = self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self, method="__invert__")
1363         return result
1364 
1365     def __nonzero__(self):
1366         raise ValueError(
1367             f"The truth value of a {type(self).__name__} is ambiguous. "
1368             "Use a.empty, a.bool(), a.item(), a.any() or a.all()."
1369         )
1370 
1371     __bool__ = __nonzero__
1372 
1373     def bool(self):
1374         """
1375         Return the bool of a single element PandasObject.
1376 
1377         This must be a boolean scalar value, either True or False.  Raise a
1378         ValueError if the PandasObject does not have exactly 1 element, or that
1379         element is not boolean
1380 
1381         Returns
1382         -------
1383         bool
1384             Same single boolean value converted to bool type.
1385         """
1386         v = self.squeeze()
1387         if isinstance(v, (bool, np.bool_)):
1388             return bool(v)
1389         elif is_scalar(v):
1390             raise ValueError(
1391                 "bool cannot act on a non-boolean single element "
1392                 f"{type(self).__name__}"
1393             )
1394 
1395         self.__nonzero__()
1396 
1397     def __abs__(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
1398         return self.abs()
1399 
1400     def __round__(self: FrameOrSeries, decimals: int = 0) -> FrameOrSeries:
1401         return self.round(decimals)
1402 
1403     # -------------------------------------------------------------------------
1404     # Label or Level Combination Helpers
1405     #
1406     # A collection of helper methods for DataFrame/Series operations that
1407     # accept a combination of column/index labels and levels.  All such
1408     # operations should utilize/extend these methods when possible so that we
1409     # have consistent precedence and validation logic throughout the library.
1410 
1411     def _is_level_reference(self, key, axis=0):
1412         """
1413         Test whether a key is a level reference for a given axis.
1414 
1415         To be considered a level reference, `key` must be a string that:
1416           - (axis=0): Matches the name of an index level and does NOT match
1417             a column label.
1418           - (axis=1): Matches the name of a column level and does NOT match
1419             an index label.
1420 
1421         Parameters
1422         ----------
1423         key : str
1424             Potential level name for the given axis
1425         axis : int, default 0
1426             Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns)
1427 
1428         Returns
1429         -------
1430         is_level : bool
1431         """
1432         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
1433 
1434         return (
1435             key is not None
1436             and is_hashable(key)
1437             and key in self.axes[axis].names
1438             and not self._is_label_reference(key, axis=axis)
1439         )
1440 
1441     def _is_label_reference(self, key, axis=0) -> bool_t:
1442         """
1443         Test whether a key is a label reference for a given axis.
1444 
1445         To be considered a label reference, `key` must be a string that:
1446           - (axis=0): Matches a column label
1447           - (axis=1): Matches an index label
1448 
1449         Parameters
1450         ----------
1451         key: str
1452             Potential label name
1453         axis: int, default 0
1454             Axis perpendicular to the axis that labels are associated with
1455             (0 means search for column labels, 1 means search for index labels)
1456 
1457         Returns
1458         -------
1459         is_label: bool
1460         """
1461         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
1462         other_axes = (ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis)
1463 
1464         return (
1465             key is not None
1466             and is_hashable(key)
1467             and any(key in self.axes[ax] for ax in other_axes)
1468         )
1469 
1470     def _is_label_or_level_reference(self, key: str, axis: int = 0) -> bool_t:
1471         """
1472         Test whether a key is a label or level reference for a given axis.
1473 
1474         To be considered either a label or a level reference, `key` must be a
1475         string that:
1476           - (axis=0): Matches a column label or an index level
1477           - (axis=1): Matches an index label or a column level
1478 
1479         Parameters
1480         ----------
1481         key: str
1482             Potential label or level name
1483         axis: int, default 0
1484             Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns)
1485 
1486         Returns
1487         -------
1488         is_label_or_level: bool
1489         """
1490         return self._is_level_reference(key, axis=axis) or self._is_label_reference(
1491             key, axis=axis
1492         )
1493 
1494     def _check_label_or_level_ambiguity(self, key, axis: int = 0) -> None:
1495         """
1496         Check whether `key` is ambiguous.
1497 
1498         By ambiguous, we mean that it matches both a level of the input
1499         `axis` and a label of the other axis.
1500 
1501         Parameters
1502         ----------
1503         key: str or object
1504             Label or level name.
1505         axis: int, default 0
1506             Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns).
1507 
1508         Raises
1509         ------
1510         ValueError: `key` is ambiguous
1511         """
1512         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
1513         other_axes = (ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis)
1514 
1515         if (
1516             key is not None
1517             and is_hashable(key)
1518             and key in self.axes[axis].names
1519             and any(key in self.axes[ax] for ax in other_axes)
1520         ):
1521 
1522             # Build an informative and grammatical warning
1523             level_article, level_type = (
1524                 ("an", "index") if axis == 0 else ("a", "column")
1525             )
1526 
1527             label_article, label_type = (
1528                 ("a", "column") if axis == 0 else ("an", "index")
1529             )
1530 
1531             msg = (
1532                 f"'{key}' is both {level_article} {level_type} level and "
1533                 f"{label_article} {label_type} label, which is ambiguous."
1534             )
1535             raise ValueError(msg)
1536 
1537     def _get_label_or_level_values(self, key: str, axis: int = 0) -> np.ndarray:
1538         """
1539         Return a 1-D array of values associated with `key`, a label or level
1540         from the given `axis`.
1541 
1542         Retrieval logic:
1543           - (axis=0): Return column values if `key` matches a column label.
1544             Otherwise return index level values if `key` matches an index
1545             level.
1546           - (axis=1): Return row values if `key` matches an index label.
1547             Otherwise return column level values if 'key' matches a column
1548             level
1549 
1550         Parameters
1551         ----------
1552         key: str
1553             Label or level name.
1554         axis: int, default 0
1555             Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns)
1556 
1557         Returns
1558         -------
1559         values: np.ndarray
1560 
1561         Raises
1562         ------
1563         KeyError
1564             if `key` matches neither a label nor a level
1565         ValueError
1566             if `key` matches multiple labels
1567         FutureWarning
1568             if `key` is ambiguous. This will become an ambiguity error in a
1569             future version
1570         """
1571         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
1572         other_axes = [ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis]
1573 
1574         if self._is_label_reference(key, axis=axis):
1575             self._check_label_or_level_ambiguity(key, axis=axis)
1576             values = self.xs(key, axis=other_axes[0])._values
1577         elif self._is_level_reference(key, axis=axis):
1578             values = self.axes[axis].get_level_values(key)._values
1579         else:
1580             raise KeyError(key)
1581 
1582         # Check for duplicates
1583         if values.ndim > 1:
1584 
1585             if other_axes and isinstance(self._get_axis(other_axes[0]), MultiIndex):
1586                 multi_message = (
1587                     "\n"
1588                     "For a multi-index, the label must be a "
1589                     "tuple with elements corresponding to each level."
1590                 )
1591             else:
1592                 multi_message = ""
1593 
1594             label_axis_name = "column" if axis == 0 else "index"
1595             raise ValueError(
1596                 (
1597                     f"The {label_axis_name} label '{key}' "
1598                     f"is not unique.{multi_message}"
1599                 )
1600             )
1601 
1602         return values
1603 
1604     def _drop_labels_or_levels(self, keys, axis: int = 0):
1605         """
1606         Drop labels and/or levels for the given `axis`.
1607 
1608         For each key in `keys`:
1609           - (axis=0): If key matches a column label then drop the column.
1610             Otherwise if key matches an index level then drop the level.
1611           - (axis=1): If key matches an index label then drop the row.
1612             Otherwise if key matches a column level then drop the level.
1613 
1614         Parameters
1615         ----------
1616         keys: str or list of str
1617             labels or levels to drop
1618         axis: int, default 0
1619             Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns)
1620 
1621         Returns
1622         -------
1623         dropped: DataFrame
1624 
1625         Raises
1626         ------
1627         ValueError
1628             if any `keys` match neither a label nor a level
1629         """
1630         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
1631 
1632         # Validate keys
1633         keys = com.maybe_make_list(keys)
1634         invalid_keys = [
1635             k for k in keys if not self._is_label_or_level_reference(k, axis=axis)
1636         ]
1637 
1638         if invalid_keys:
1639             raise ValueError(
1640                 (
1641                     "The following keys are not valid labels or "
1642                     f"levels for axis {axis}: {invalid_keys}"
1643                 )
1644             )
1645 
1646         # Compute levels and labels to drop
1647         levels_to_drop = [k for k in keys if self._is_level_reference(k, axis=axis)]
1648 
1649         labels_to_drop = [k for k in keys if not self._is_level_reference(k, axis=axis)]
1650 
1651         # Perform copy upfront and then use inplace operations below.
1652         # This ensures that we always perform exactly one copy.
1653         # ``copy`` and/or ``inplace`` options could be added in the future.
1654         dropped = self.copy()
1655 
1656         if axis == 0:
1657             # Handle dropping index levels
1658             if levels_to_drop:
1659                 dropped.reset_index(levels_to_drop, drop=True, inplace=True)
1660 
1661             # Handle dropping columns labels
1662             if labels_to_drop:
1663                 dropped.drop(labels_to_drop, axis=1, inplace=True)
1664         else:
1665             # Handle dropping column levels
1666             if levels_to_drop:
1667                 if isinstance(dropped.columns, MultiIndex):
1668                     # Drop the specified levels from the MultiIndex
1669                     dropped.columns = dropped.columns.droplevel(levels_to_drop)
1670                 else:
1671                     # Drop the last level of Index by replacing with
1672                     # a RangeIndex
1673                     dropped.columns = RangeIndex(dropped.columns.size)
1674 
1675             # Handle dropping index labels
1676             if labels_to_drop:
1677                 dropped.drop(labels_to_drop, axis=0, inplace=True)
1678 
1679         return dropped
1680

1687             f"thus they cannot be hashed"
1688         )

1703         """
1704         Get the 'info axis' (see Indexing for more).
1705 
1706         This is index for Series, columns for DataFrame.
1707 
1708         Returns
1709         -------
1710         Index
1711             Info axis.

1715     def items(self):
1716         """
1717         Iterate over (label, values) on info axis
1718 
1719         This is index for Series and columns for DataFrame.
1720 
1721         Returns
1722         -------
1723         Generator
1724         """
1725         for h in self._info_axis:
1726             yield h, self[h]
1727 
1728     @doc(items)

1730         return self.items()
1731 
1732     def __len__(self) -> int:
1733         """Returns length of info axis"""
1734         return len(self._info_axis)

1737         """True if the key is in the info axis"""

1740     @property
1741     def empty(self) -> bool_t:
1742         """
1743         Indicator whether DataFrame is empty.
1744 
1745         True if DataFrame is entirely empty (no items), meaning any of the
1746         axes are of length 0.
1747 
1748         Returns
1749         -------
1750         bool
1751             If DataFrame is empty, return True, if not return False.
1752 
1753         See Also
1754         --------
1755         Series.dropna : Return series without null values.
1756         DataFrame.dropna : Return DataFrame with labels on given axis omitted
1757             where (all or any) data are missing.
1758 
1759         Notes
1760         -----
1761         If DataFrame contains only NaNs, it is still not considered empty. See
1762         the example below.
1763 
1764         Examples
1765         --------
1766         An example of an actual empty DataFrame. Notice the index is empty:
1767 
1768         >>> df_empty = pd.DataFrame({'A' : []})
1769         >>> df_empty
1770         Empty DataFrame
1771         Columns: [A]
1772         Index: []
1773         >>> df_empty.empty
1774         True
1775 
1776         If we only have NaNs in our DataFrame, it is not considered empty! We
1777         will need to drop the NaNs to make the DataFrame empty:
1778 
1779         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A' : [np.nan]})
1780         >>> df
1781             A
1782         0 NaN
1783         >>> df.empty
1784         False
1785         >>> df.dropna().empty
1786         True
1787         """
1788         return any(len(self._get_axis(a)) == 0 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS)
1789

1791     # Array Interface
1792 
1793     # This is also set in IndexOpsMixin
1794     # GH#23114 Ensure ndarray.__op__(DataFrame) returns NotImplemented
1795     __array_priority__ = 1000
1796 
1797     def __array__(self, dtype=None) -> np.ndarray:
1798         return np.asarray(self._values, dtype=dtype)
1799 
1800     def __array_wrap__(self, result, context=None):
1801         result = lib.item_from_zerodim(result)
1802         if is_scalar(result):
1803             # e.g. we get here with np.ptp(series)
1804             # ptp also requires the item_from_zerodim
1805             return result
1806         d = self._construct_axes_dict(self._AXIS_ORDERS, copy=False)
1807         return self._constructor(result, **d).__finalize__(
1808             self, method="__array_wrap__"
1809         )
1810 
1811     # ideally we would define this to avoid the getattr checks, but
1812     # is slower
1813     # @property
1814     # def __array_interface__(self):
1815     #    """ provide numpy array interface method """
1816     #    values = self.values
1817     #    return dict(typestr=values.dtype.str,shape=values.shape,data=values)

1819     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
1820     # Picklability
1821 
1822     def __getstate__(self) -> Dict[str, Any]:
1823         meta = {k: getattr(self, k, None) for k in self._metadata}
1824         return dict(
1825             _mgr=self._mgr,
1826             _typ=self._typ,
1827             _metadata=self._metadata,
1828             attrs=self.attrs,
1829             **meta,
1830         )
1831 
1832     def __setstate__(self, state):
1833 
1834         if isinstance(state, BlockManager):
1835             self._mgr = state
1836         elif isinstance(state, dict):
1837             if "_data" in state and "_mgr" not in state:
1838                 # compat for older pickles
1839                 state["_mgr"] = state.pop("_data")
1840             typ = state.get("_typ")
1841             if typ is not None:
1842                 attrs = state.get("_attrs", {})
1843                 object.__setattr__(self, "_attrs", attrs)
1844 
1845                 # set in the order of internal names
1846                 # to avoid definitional recursion
1847                 # e.g. say fill_value needing _mgr to be
1848                 # defined
1849                 meta = set(self._internal_names + self._metadata)
1850                 for k in list(meta):
1851                     if k in state:
1852                         v = state[k]
1853                         object.__setattr__(self, k, v)
1854 
1855                 for k, v in state.items():
1856                     if k not in meta:
1857                         object.__setattr__(self, k, v)
1858 
1859             else:
1860                 raise NotImplementedError("Pre-0.12 pickles are no longer supported")
1861         elif len(state) == 2:
1862             raise NotImplementedError("Pre-0.12 pickles are no longer supported")
1863 
1864         self._item_cache = {}
1865 
1866     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
1867     # Rendering Methods
1868 
1869     def __repr__(self) -> str:
1870         # string representation based upon iterating over self
1871         # (since, by definition, `PandasContainers` are iterable)
1872         prepr = f"[{','.join(map(pprint_thing, self))}]"
1873         return f"{type(self).__name__}({prepr})"
1874 
1875     def _repr_latex_(self):
1876         """
1877         Returns a LaTeX representation for a particular object.
1878         Mainly for use with nbconvert (jupyter notebook conversion to pdf).
1879         """
1880         if config.get_option("display.latex.repr"):
1881             return self.to_latex()
1882         else:
1883             return None
1884 
1885     def _repr_data_resource_(self):
1886         """
1887         Not a real Jupyter special repr method, but we use the same
1888         naming convention.
1889         """
1890         if config.get_option("display.html.table_schema"):
1891             data = self.head(config.get_option("display.max_rows"))
1892             payload = json.loads(
1893                 data.to_json(orient="table"), object_pairs_hook=collections.OrderedDict
1894             )
1895             return payload

1900     _shared_docs[
1901         "to_markdown"
1902     ] = """
1903     Print %(klass)s in Markdown-friendly format.
1904 
1905     .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
1906 
1907     Parameters
1908     ----------
1909     buf : str, Path or StringIO-like, optional, default None
1910         Buffer to write to. If None, the output is returned as a string.
1911     mode : str, optional
1912         Mode in which file is opened.
1913     **kwargs
1914         These parameters will be passed to `tabulate \
1915             <https://pypi.org/project/tabulate>`_.
1916 
1917     Returns
1918     -------
1919     str
1920         %(klass)s in Markdown-friendly format.
