1923     @doc(klass="object")
1924     def to_excel(
1925         self,
1926         excel_writer,
1927         sheet_name="Sheet1",
1928         na_rep="",
1929         float_format=None,
1930         columns=None,
1931         header=True,
1932         index=True,
1933         index_label=None,
1934         startrow=0,
1935         startcol=0,
1936         engine=None,
1937         merge_cells=True,
1938         encoding=None,
1939         inf_rep="inf",
1940         verbose=True,
1941         freeze_panes=None,
1942     ) -> None:
1943         """
1944         Write {klass} to an Excel sheet.
1945 
1946         To write a single {klass} to an Excel .xlsx file it is only necessary to
1947         specify a target file name. To write to multiple sheets it is necessary to
1948         create an `ExcelWriter` object with a target file name, and specify a sheet
1949         in the file to write to.
1950 
1951         Multiple sheets may be written to by specifying unique `sheet_name`.
1952         With all data written to the file it is necessary to save the changes.
1953         Note that creating an `ExcelWriter` object with a file name that already
1954         exists will result in the contents of the existing file being erased.
1955 
1956         Parameters
1957         ----------
1958         excel_writer : str or ExcelWriter object
1959             File path or existing ExcelWriter.
1960         sheet_name : str, default 'Sheet1'
1961             Name of sheet which will contain DataFrame.
1962         na_rep : str, default ''
1963             Missing data representation.
1964         float_format : str, optional
1965             Format string for floating point numbers. For example
1966             ``float_format="%.2f"`` will format 0.1234 to 0.12.
1967         columns : sequence or list of str, optional
1968             Columns to write.
1969         header : bool or list of str, default True
1970             Write out the column names. If a list of string is given it is
1971             assumed to be aliases for the column names.
1972         index : bool, default True
1973             Write row names (index).
1974         index_label : str or sequence, optional
1975             Column label for index column(s) if desired. If not specified, and
1976             `header` and `index` are True, then the index names are used. A
1977             sequence should be given if the DataFrame uses MultiIndex.
1978         startrow : int, default 0
1979             Upper left cell row to dump data frame.
1980         startcol : int, default 0
1981             Upper left cell column to dump data frame.
1982         engine : str, optional
1983             Write engine to use, 'openpyxl' or 'xlsxwriter'. You can also set this
1984             via the options ``io.excel.xlsx.writer``, ``io.excel.xls.writer``, and
1985             ``io.excel.xlsm.writer``.
1986         merge_cells : bool, default True
1987             Write MultiIndex and Hierarchical Rows as merged cells.
1988         encoding : str, optional
1989             Encoding of the resulting excel file. Only necessary for xlwt,
1990             other writers support unicode natively.
1991         inf_rep : str, default 'inf'
1992             Representation for infinity (there is no native representation for
1993             infinity in Excel).
1994         verbose : bool, default True
1995             Display more information in the error logs.
1996         freeze_panes : tuple of int (length 2), optional
1997             Specifies the one-based bottommost row and rightmost column that
1998             is to be frozen.
1999 
2000         See Also
2001         --------
2002         to_csv : Write DataFrame to a comma-separated values (csv) file.
2003         ExcelWriter : Class for writing DataFrame objects into excel sheets.
2004         read_excel : Read an Excel file into a pandas DataFrame.
2005         read_csv : Read a comma-separated values (csv) file into DataFrame.
2006 
2007         Notes
2008         -----
2009         For compatibility with :meth:`~DataFrame.to_csv`,
2010         to_excel serializes lists and dicts to strings before writing.
2011 
2012         Once a workbook has been saved it is not possible write further data
2013         without rewriting the whole workbook.
2014 
2015         Examples
2016         --------
2017 
2018         Create, write to and save a workbook:
2019 
2020         >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame([['a', 'b'], ['c', 'd']],
2021         ...                    index=['row 1', 'row 2'],
2022         ...                    columns=['col 1', 'col 2'])
2023         >>> df1.to_excel("output.xlsx")  # doctest: +SKIP
2024 
2025         To specify the sheet name:
2026 
2027         >>> df1.to_excel("output.xlsx",
2028         ...              sheet_name='Sheet_name_1')  # doctest: +SKIP
2029 
2030         If you wish to write to more than one sheet in the workbook, it is
2031         necessary to specify an ExcelWriter object:
2032 
2033         >>> df2 = df1.copy()
2034         >>> with pd.ExcelWriter('output.xlsx') as writer:  # doctest: +SKIP
2035         ...     df1.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_1')
2036         ...     df2.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_2')
2037 
2038         ExcelWriter can also be used to append to an existing Excel file:
2039 
2040         >>> with pd.ExcelWriter('output.xlsx',
2041         ...                     mode='a') as writer:  # doctest: +SKIP
2042         ...     df.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_3')
2043 
2044         To set the library that is used to write the Excel file,
2045         you can pass the `engine` keyword (the default engine is
2046         automatically chosen depending on the file extension):
2047 
2048         >>> df1.to_excel('output1.xlsx', engine='xlsxwriter')  # doctest: +SKIP
2049         """
2050 
2051         df = self if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) else self.to_frame()
2052 
2053         from pandas.io.formats.excel import ExcelFormatter
2054 
2055         formatter = ExcelFormatter(
2056             df,
2057             na_rep=na_rep,
2058             cols=columns,
2059             header=header,
2060             float_format=float_format,
2061             index=index,
2062             index_label=index_label,
2063             merge_cells=merge_cells,
2064             inf_rep=inf_rep,
2065         )
2066         formatter.write(
2067             excel_writer,
2068             sheet_name=sheet_name,
2069             startrow=startrow,
2070             startcol=startcol,
2071             freeze_panes=freeze_panes,
2072             engine=engine,
2073         )
2074 
2075     def to_json(
2076         self,
2077         path_or_buf: Optional[FilePathOrBuffer] = None,
2078         orient: Optional[str] = None,
2079         date_format: Optional[str] = None,
2080         double_precision: int = 10,
2081         force_ascii: bool_t = True,
2082         date_unit: str = "ms",
2083         default_handler: Optional[Callable[[Any], JSONSerializable]] = None,
2084         lines: bool_t = False,
2085         compression: Optional[str] = "infer",
2086         index: bool_t = True,
2087         indent: Optional[int] = None,
2088     ) -> Optional[str]:
2089         """
2090         Convert the object to a JSON string.
2091 
2092         Note NaN's and None will be converted to null and datetime objects
2093         will be converted to UNIX timestamps.
2094 
2095         Parameters
2096         ----------
2097         path_or_buf : str or file handle, optional
2098             File path or object. If not specified, the result is returned as
2099             a string.
2100         orient : str
2101             Indication of expected JSON string format.
2102 
2103             * Series:
2104 
2105                 - default is 'index'
2106                 - allowed values are: {'split','records','index','table'}.
2107 
2108             * DataFrame:
2109 
2110                 - default is 'columns'
2111                 - allowed values are: {'split', 'records', 'index', 'columns',
2112                   'values', 'table'}.
2113 
2114             * The format of the JSON string:
2115 
2116                 - 'split' : dict like {'index' -> [index], 'columns' -> [columns],
2117                   'data' -> [values]}
2118                 - 'records' : list like [{column -> value}, ... , {column -> value}]
2119                 - 'index' : dict like {index -> {column -> value}}
2120                 - 'columns' : dict like {column -> {index -> value}}
2121                 - 'values' : just the values array
2122                 - 'table' : dict like {'schema': {schema}, 'data': {data}}
2123 
2124                 Describing the data, where data component is like ``orient='records'``.
2125 
2126             .. versionchanged:: 0.20.0
2127 
2128         date_format : {None, 'epoch', 'iso'}
2129             Type of date conversion. 'epoch' = epoch milliseconds,
2130             'iso' = ISO8601. The default depends on the `orient`. For
2131             ``orient='table'``, the default is 'iso'. For all other orients,
2132             the default is 'epoch'.
2133         double_precision : int, default 10
2134             The number of decimal places to use when encoding
2135             floating point values.
2136         force_ascii : bool, default True
2137             Force encoded string to be ASCII.
2138         date_unit : str, default 'ms' (milliseconds)
2139             The time unit to encode to, governs timestamp and ISO8601
2140             precision.  One of 's', 'ms', 'us', 'ns' for second, millisecond,
2141             microsecond, and nanosecond respectively.
2142         default_handler : callable, default None
2143             Handler to call if object cannot otherwise be converted to a
2144             suitable format for JSON. Should receive a single argument which is
2145             the object to convert and return a serialisable object.
2146         lines : bool, default False
2147             If 'orient' is 'records' write out line delimited json format. Will
2148             throw ValueError if incorrect 'orient' since others are not list
2149             like.
2150 
2151         compression : {'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}
2152 
2153             A string representing the compression to use in the output file,
2154             only used when the first argument is a filename. By default, the
2155             compression is inferred from the filename.
2156 
2157             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0
2158                'infer' option added and set to default
2159         index : bool, default True
2160             Whether to include the index values in the JSON string. Not
2161             including the index (``index=False``) is only supported when
2162             orient is 'split' or 'table'.
2163 
2164             .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
2165 
2166         indent : int, optional
2167            Length of whitespace used to indent each record.
2168 
2169            .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
2170 
2171         Returns
2172         -------
2173         None or str
2174             If path_or_buf is None, returns the resulting json format as a
2175             string. Otherwise returns None.
2176 
2177         See Also
2178         --------
2179         read_json : Convert a JSON string to pandas object.
2180 
2181         Notes
2182         -----
2183         The behavior of ``indent=0`` varies from the stdlib, which does not
2184         indent the output but does insert newlines. Currently, ``indent=0``
2185         and the default ``indent=None`` are equivalent in pandas, though this
2186         may change in a future release.
2187 
2188         Examples
2189         --------
2190         >>> import json
2191         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(
2192         ...     [["a", "b"], ["c", "d"]],
2193         ...     index=["row 1", "row 2"],
2194         ...     columns=["col 1", "col 2"],
2195         ... )
2196 
2197         >>> result = df.to_json(orient="split")
2198         >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2199         >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4)  # doctest: +SKIP
2200         {
2201             "columns": [
2202                 "col 1",
2203                 "col 2"
2204             ],
2205             "index": [
2206                 "row 1",
2207                 "row 2"
2208             ],
2209             "data": [
2210                 [
2211                     "a",
2212                     "b"
2213                 ],
2214                 [
2215                     "c",
2216                     "d"
2217                 ]
2218             ]
2219         }
2220 
2221         Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'records'`` formatted JSON.
2222         Note that index labels are not preserved with this encoding.
2223 
2224         >>> result = df.to_json(orient="records")
2225         >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2226         >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4)  # doctest: +SKIP
2227         [
2228             {
2229                 "col 1": "a",
2230                 "col 2": "b"
2231             },
2232             {
2233                 "col 1": "c",
2234                 "col 2": "d"
2235             }
2236         ]
2237 
2238         Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'index'`` formatted JSON:
2239 
2240         >>> result = df.to_json(orient="index")
2241         >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2242         >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4)  # doctest: +SKIP
2243         {
2244             "row 1": {
2245                 "col 1": "a",
2246                 "col 2": "b"
2247             },
2248             "row 2": {
2249                 "col 1": "c",
2250                 "col 2": "d"
2251             }
2252         }
2253 
2254         Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'columns'`` formatted JSON:
2255 
2256         >>> result = df.to_json(orient="columns")
2257         >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2258         >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4)  # doctest: +SKIP
2259         {
2260             "col 1": {
2261                 "row 1": "a",
2262                 "row 2": "c"
2263             },
2264             "col 2": {
2265                 "row 1": "b",
2266                 "row 2": "d"
2267             }
2268         }
2269 
2270         Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'values'`` formatted JSON:
2271 
2272         >>> result = df.to_json(orient="values")
2273         >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2274         >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4)  # doctest: +SKIP
2275         [
2276             [
2277                 "a",
2278                 "b"
2279             ],
2280             [
2281                 "c",
2282                 "d"
2283             ]
2284         ]
2285 
2286         Encoding with Table Schema:
2287 
2288         >>> result = df.to_json(orient="table")
2289         >>> parsed = json.loads(result)
2290         >>> json.dumps(parsed, indent=4)  # doctest: +SKIP
2291         {
2292             "schema": {
2293                 "fields": [
2294                     {
2295                         "name": "index",
2296                         "type": "string"
2297                     },
2298                     {
2299                         "name": "col 1",
2300                         "type": "string"
2301                     },
2302                     {
2303                         "name": "col 2",
2304                         "type": "string"
2305                     }
2306                 ],
2307                 "primaryKey": [
2308                     "index"
2309                 ],
2310                 "pandas_version": "0.20.0"
2311             },
2312             "data": [
2313                 {
2314                     "index": "row 1",
2315                     "col 1": "a",
2316                     "col 2": "b"
2317                 },
2318                 {
2319                     "index": "row 2",
2320                     "col 1": "c",
2321                     "col 2": "d"
2322                 }
2323             ]
2324         }
2325         """
2326         from pandas.io import json
2327 
2328         if date_format is None and orient == "table":
2329             date_format = "iso"
2330         elif date_format is None:
2331             date_format = "epoch"
2332 
2333         config.is_nonnegative_int(indent)
2334         indent = indent or 0
2335 
2336         return json.to_json(
2337             path_or_buf=path_or_buf,
2338             obj=self,
2339             orient=orient,
2340             date_format=date_format,
2341             double_precision=double_precision,
2342             force_ascii=force_ascii,
2343             date_unit=date_unit,
2344             default_handler=default_handler,
2345             lines=lines,
2346             compression=compression,
2347             index=index,
2348             indent=indent,
2349         )
2350 
2351     def to_hdf(
2352         self,
2353         path_or_buf,
2354         key: str,
2355         mode: str = "a",
2356         complevel: Optional[int] = None,
2357         complib: Optional[str] = None,
2358         append: bool_t = False,
2359         format: Optional[str] = None,
2360         index: bool_t = True,
2361         min_itemsize: Optional[Union[int, Dict[str, int]]] = None,
2362         nan_rep=None,
2363         dropna: Optional[bool_t] = None,
2364         data_columns: Optional[Union[bool_t, List[str]]] = None,
2365         errors: str = "strict",
2366         encoding: str = "UTF-8",
2367     ) -> None:
2368         """
2369         Write the contained data to an HDF5 file using HDFStore.
2370 
2371         Hierarchical Data Format (HDF) is self-describing, allowing an
2372         application to interpret the structure and contents of a file with
2373         no outside information. One HDF file can hold a mix of related objects
2374         which can be accessed as a group or as individual objects.
2375 
2376         In order to add another DataFrame or Series to an existing HDF file
2377         please use append mode and a different a key.
2378 
2379         For more information see the :ref:`user guide <io.hdf5>`.
2380 
2381         Parameters
2382         ----------
2383         path_or_buf : str or pandas.HDFStore
2384             File path or HDFStore object.
2385         key : str
2386             Identifier for the group in the store.
2387         mode : {'a', 'w', 'r+'}, default 'a'
2388             Mode to open file:
2389 
2390             - 'w': write, a new file is created (an existing file with
2391               the same name would be deleted).
2392             - 'a': append, an existing file is opened for reading and
2393               writing, and if the file does not exist it is created.
2394             - 'r+': similar to 'a', but the file must already exist.
2395         complevel : {0-9}, optional
2396             Specifies a compression level for data.
2397             A value of 0 disables compression.
2398         complib : {'zlib', 'lzo', 'bzip2', 'blosc'}, default 'zlib'
2399             Specifies the compression library to be used.
2400             As of v0.20.2 these additional compressors for Blosc are supported
2401             (default if no compressor specified: 'blosc:blosclz'):
2402             {'blosc:blosclz', 'blosc:lz4', 'blosc:lz4hc', 'blosc:snappy',
2403             'blosc:zlib', 'blosc:zstd'}.
2404             Specifying a compression library which is not available issues
2405             a ValueError.
2406         append : bool, default False
2407             For Table formats, append the input data to the existing.
2408         format : {'fixed', 'table', None}, default 'fixed'
2409             Possible values:
2410 
2411             - 'fixed': Fixed format. Fast writing/reading. Not-appendable,
2412               nor searchable.
2413             - 'table': Table format. Write as a PyTables Table structure
2414               which may perform worse but allow more flexible operations
2415               like searching / selecting subsets of the data.
2416             - If None, pd.get_option('io.hdf.default_format') is checked,
2417               followed by fallback to "fixed"
2418         errors : str, default 'strict'
2419             Specifies how encoding and decoding errors are to be handled.
2420             See the errors argument for :func:`open` for a full list
2421             of options.
2422         encoding : str, default "UTF-8"
2423         min_itemsize : dict or int, optional
2424             Map column names to minimum string sizes for columns.
2425         nan_rep : Any, optional
2426             How to represent null values as str.
2427             Not allowed with append=True.
2428         data_columns : list of columns or True, optional
2429             List of columns to create as indexed data columns for on-disk
2430             queries, or True to use all columns. By default only the axes
2431             of the object are indexed. See :ref:`io.hdf5-query-data-columns`.
2432             Applicable only to format='table'.
2433 
2434         See Also
2435         --------
2436         DataFrame.read_hdf : Read from HDF file.
2437         DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format.
2438         DataFrame.to_sql : Write to a sql table.
2439         DataFrame.to_feather : Write out feather-format for DataFrames.
2440         DataFrame.to_csv : Write out to a csv file.
2441 
2442         Examples
2443         --------
2444         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3], 'B': [4, 5, 6]},
2445         ...                   index=['a', 'b', 'c'])
2446         >>> df.to_hdf('data.h5', key='df', mode='w')
2447 
2448         We can add another object to the same file:
2449 
2450         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4])
2451         >>> s.to_hdf('data.h5', key='s')
2452 
2453         Reading from HDF file:
2454 
2455         >>> pd.read_hdf('data.h5', 'df')
2456         A  B
2457         a  1  4
2458         b  2  5
2459         c  3  6
2460         >>> pd.read_hdf('data.h5', 's')
2461         0    1
2462         1    2
2463         2    3
2464         3    4
2465         dtype: int64
2466 
2467         Deleting file with data:
2468 
2469         >>> import os
2470         >>> os.remove('data.h5')
2471         """
2472         from pandas.io import pytables
2473 
2474         pytables.to_hdf(
2475             path_or_buf,
2476             key,
2477             self,
2478             mode=mode,
2479             complevel=complevel,
2480             complib=complib,
2481             append=append,
2482             format=format,
2483             index=index,
2484             min_itemsize=min_itemsize,
2485             nan_rep=nan_rep,
2486             dropna=dropna,
2487             data_columns=data_columns,
2488             errors=errors,
2489             encoding=encoding,
2490         )
2491 
2492     def to_sql(
2493         self,
2494         name: str,
2495         con,
2496         schema=None,
2497         if_exists: str = "fail",
2498         index: bool_t = True,
2499         index_label=None,
2500         chunksize=None,
2501         dtype=None,
2502         method=None,
2503     ) -> None:
2504         """
2505         Write records stored in a DataFrame to a SQL database.
2506 
2507         Databases supported by SQLAlchemy [1]_ are supported. Tables can be
2508         newly created, appended to, or overwritten.
2509 
2510         Parameters
2511         ----------
2512         name : str
2513             Name of SQL table.
2514         con : sqlalchemy.engine.Engine or sqlite3.Connection
2515             Using SQLAlchemy makes it possible to use any DB supported by that
2516             library. Legacy support is provided for sqlite3.Connection objects. The user
2517             is responsible for engine disposal and connection closure for the SQLAlchemy
2518             connectable See `here \
2519                 <https://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/13/core/connections.html>`_.
2520 
2521         schema : str, optional
2522             Specify the schema (if database flavor supports this). If None, use
2523             default schema.
2524         if_exists : {'fail', 'replace', 'append'}, default 'fail'
2525             How to behave if the table already exists.
2526 
2527             * fail: Raise a ValueError.
2528             * replace: Drop the table before inserting new values.
2529             * append: Insert new values to the existing table.
2530 
2531         index : bool, default True
2532             Write DataFrame index as a column. Uses `index_label` as the column
2533             name in the table.
2534         index_label : str or sequence, default None
2535             Column label for index column(s). If None is given (default) and
2536             `index` is True, then the index names are used.
2537             A sequence should be given if the DataFrame uses MultiIndex.
2538         chunksize : int, optional
2539             Specify the number of rows in each batch to be written at a time.
2540             By default, all rows will be written at once.
2541         dtype : dict or scalar, optional
2542             Specifying the datatype for columns. If a dictionary is used, the
2543             keys should be the column names and the values should be the
2544             SQLAlchemy types or strings for the sqlite3 legacy mode. If a
2545             scalar is provided, it will be applied to all columns.
2546         method : {None, 'multi', callable}, optional
2547             Controls the SQL insertion clause used:
2548 
2549             * None : Uses standard SQL ``INSERT`` clause (one per row).
2550             * 'multi': Pass multiple values in a single ``INSERT`` clause.
2551             * callable with signature ``(pd_table, conn, keys, data_iter)``.
2552 
2553             Details and a sample callable implementation can be found in the
2554             section :ref:`insert method <io.sql.method>`.
2555 
2556             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2557 
2558         Raises
2559         ------
2560         ValueError
2561             When the table already exists and `if_exists` is 'fail' (the
2562             default).
2563 
2564         See Also
2565         --------
2566         read_sql : Read a DataFrame from a table.
2567 
2568         Notes
2569         -----
2570         Timezone aware datetime columns will be written as
2571         ``Timestamp with timezone`` type with SQLAlchemy if supported by the
2572         database. Otherwise, the datetimes will be stored as timezone unaware
2573         timestamps local to the original timezone.
2574 
2575         .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
2576 
2577         References
2578         ----------
2579         .. [1] https://docs.sqlalchemy.org
2580         .. [2] https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0249/
2581 
2582         Examples
2583         --------
2584         Create an in-memory SQLite database.
2585 
2586         >>> from sqlalchemy import create_engine
2587         >>> engine = create_engine('sqlite://', echo=False)
2588 
2589         Create a table from scratch with 3 rows.
2590 
2591         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'name' : ['User 1', 'User 2', 'User 3']})
2592         >>> df
2593              name
2594         0  User 1
2595         1  User 2
2596         2  User 3
2597 
2598         >>> df.to_sql('users', con=engine)
2599         >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall()
2600         [(0, 'User 1'), (1, 'User 2'), (2, 'User 3')]
2601 
2602         >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'name' : ['User 4', 'User 5']})
2603         >>> df1.to_sql('users', con=engine, if_exists='append')
2604         >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall()
2605         [(0, 'User 1'), (1, 'User 2'), (2, 'User 3'),
2606          (0, 'User 4'), (1, 'User 5')]
2607 
2608         Overwrite the table with just ``df1``.
2609 
2610         >>> df1.to_sql('users', con=engine, if_exists='replace',
2611         ...            index_label='id')
2612         >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall()
2613         [(0, 'User 4'), (1, 'User 5')]
2614 
2615         Specify the dtype (especially useful for integers with missing values).
2616         Notice that while pandas is forced to store the data as floating point,
2617         the database supports nullable integers. When fetching the data with
2618         Python, we get back integer scalars.
2619 
2620         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, None, 2]})
2621         >>> df
2622              A
2623         0  1.0
2624         1  NaN
2625         2  2.0
2626 
2627         >>> from sqlalchemy.types import Integer
2628         >>> df.to_sql('integers', con=engine, index=False,
2629         ...           dtype={"A": Integer()})
2630 
2631         >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM integers").fetchall()
2632         [(1,), (None,), (2,)]
2633         """
2634         from pandas.io import sql
2635 
2636         sql.to_sql(
2637             self,
2638             name,
2639             con,
2640             schema=schema,
2641             if_exists=if_exists,
2642             index=index,
2643             index_label=index_label,
2644             chunksize=chunksize,
2645             dtype=dtype,
2646             method=method,
2647         )
2648 
2649     def to_pickle(
2650         self,
2651         path,
2652         compression: Optional[str] = "infer",
2653         protocol: int = pickle.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL,
2654     ) -> None:
2655         """
2656         Pickle (serialize) object to file.
2657 
2658         Parameters
2659         ----------
2660         path : str
2661             File path where the pickled object will be stored.
2662         compression : {'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}, \
2663         default 'infer'
2664             A string representing the compression to use in the output file. By
2665             default, infers from the file extension in specified path.
2666         protocol : int
2667             Int which indicates which protocol should be used by the pickler,
2668             default HIGHEST_PROTOCOL (see [1]_ paragraph 12.1.2). The possible
2669             values are 0, 1, 2, 3, 4. A negative value for the protocol
2670             parameter is equivalent to setting its value to HIGHEST_PROTOCOL.
2671 
2672             .. [1] https://docs.python.org/3/library/pickle.html.
2673 
2674         See Also
2675         --------
2676         read_pickle : Load pickled pandas object (or any object) from file.
2677         DataFrame.to_hdf : Write DataFrame to an HDF5 file.
2678         DataFrame.to_sql : Write DataFrame to a SQL database.
2679         DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format.
2680 
2681         Examples
2682         --------
2683         >>> original_df = pd.DataFrame({"foo": range(5), "bar": range(5, 10)})
2684         >>> original_df
2685            foo  bar
2686         0    0    5
2687         1    1    6
2688         2    2    7
2689         3    3    8
2690         4    4    9
2691         >>> original_df.to_pickle("./dummy.pkl")
2692 
2693         >>> unpickled_df = pd.read_pickle("./dummy.pkl")
2694         >>> unpickled_df
2695            foo  bar
2696         0    0    5
2697         1    1    6
2698         2    2    7
2699         3    3    8
2700         4    4    9
2701 
2702         >>> import os
2703         >>> os.remove("./dummy.pkl")
2704         """
2705         from pandas.io.pickle import to_pickle
2706 
2707         to_pickle(self, path, compression=compression, protocol=protocol)

2709     def to_clipboard(
2710         self, excel: bool_t = True, sep: Optional[str] = None, **kwargs
2711     ) -> None:
2712         r"""
2713         Copy object to the system clipboard.
2714 
2715         Write a text representation of object to the system clipboard.
2716         This can be pasted into Excel, for example.
2717 
2718         Parameters
2719         ----------
2720         excel : bool, default True
2721             Produce output in a csv format for easy pasting into excel.
2722 
2723             - True, use the provided separator for csv pasting.
2724             - False, write a string representation of the object to the clipboard.
2725 
2726         sep : str, default ``'\t'``
2727             Field delimiter.
2728         **kwargs
2729             These parameters will be passed to DataFrame.to_csv.
2730 
2731         See Also
2732         --------
2733         DataFrame.to_csv : Write a DataFrame to a comma-separated values
2734             (csv) file.
2735         read_clipboard : Read text from clipboard and pass to read_table.
2736 
2737         Notes
2738         -----
2739         Requirements for your platform.
2740 
2741           - Linux : `xclip`, or `xsel` (with `PyQt4` modules)
2742           - Windows : none
2743           - OS X : none
2744 
2745         Examples
2746         --------
2747         Copy the contents of a DataFrame to the clipboard.
2748 
2749         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]], columns=['A', 'B', 'C'])
2750 
2751         >>> df.to_clipboard(sep=',')  # doctest: +SKIP
2752         ... # Wrote the following to the system clipboard:
2753         ... # ,A,B,C
2754         ... # 0,1,2,3
2755         ... # 1,4,5,6
2756 
2757         We can omit the index by passing the keyword `index` and setting
2758         it to false.
2759 
2760         >>> df.to_clipboard(sep=',', index=False)  # doctest: +SKIP
2761         ... # Wrote the following to the system clipboard:
2762         ... # A,B,C
2763         ... # 1,2,3
2764         ... # 4,5,6
2765         """
2766         from pandas.io import clipboards
2767 
2768         clipboards.to_clipboard(self, excel=excel, sep=sep, **kwargs)

2770     def to_xarray(self):
2771         """
2772         Return an xarray object from the pandas object.
2773 
2774         Returns
2775         -------
2776         xarray.DataArray or xarray.Dataset
2777             Data in the pandas structure converted to Dataset if the object is
2778             a DataFrame, or a DataArray if the object is a Series.
2779 
2780         See Also
2781         --------
2782         DataFrame.to_hdf : Write DataFrame to an HDF5 file.
2783         DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format.
2784 
2785         Notes
2786         -----
2787         See the `xarray docs <https://xarray.pydata.org/en/stable/>`__
2788 
2789         Examples
2790         --------
2791         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0, 2),
2792         ...                    ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0, 2),
2793         ...                    ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5, 4),
2794         ...                    ('monkey', 'mammal', np.nan, 4)],
2795         ...                   columns=['name', 'class', 'max_speed',
2796         ...                            'num_legs'])
2797         >>> df
2798              name   class  max_speed  num_legs
2799         0  falcon    bird      389.0         2
2800         1  parrot    bird       24.0         2
2801         2    lion  mammal       80.5         4
2802         3  monkey  mammal        NaN         4
2803 
2804         >>> df.to_xarray()
2805         <xarray.Dataset>
2806         Dimensions:    (index: 4)
2807         Coordinates:
2808           * index      (index) int64 0 1 2 3
2809         Data variables:
2810             name       (index) object 'falcon' 'parrot' 'lion' 'monkey'
2811             class      (index) object 'bird' 'bird' 'mammal' 'mammal'
2812             max_speed  (index) float64 389.0 24.0 80.5 nan
2813             num_legs   (index) int64 2 2 4 4
2814 
2815         >>> df['max_speed'].to_xarray()
2816         <xarray.DataArray 'max_speed' (index: 4)>
2817         array([389. ,  24. ,  80.5,   nan])
2818         Coordinates:
2819           * index    (index) int64 0 1 2 3
2820 
2821         >>> dates = pd.to_datetime(['2018-01-01', '2018-01-01',
2822         ...                         '2018-01-02', '2018-01-02'])
2823         >>> df_multiindex = pd.DataFrame({'date': dates,
2824         ...                               'animal': ['falcon', 'parrot',
2825         ...                                          'falcon', 'parrot'],
2826         ...                               'speed': [350, 18, 361, 15]})
2827         >>> df_multiindex = df_multiindex.set_index(['date', 'animal'])
2828 
2829         >>> df_multiindex
2830                            speed
2831         date       animal
2832         2018-01-01 falcon    350
2833                    parrot     18
2834         2018-01-02 falcon    361
2835                    parrot     15
2836 
2837         >>> df_multiindex.to_xarray()
2838         <xarray.Dataset>
2839         Dimensions:  (animal: 2, date: 2)
2840         Coordinates:
2841           * date     (date) datetime64[ns] 2018-01-01 2018-01-02
2842           * animal   (animal) object 'falcon' 'parrot'
2843         Data variables:
2844             speed    (date, animal) int64 350 18 361 15
2845         """
2846         xarray = import_optional_dependency("xarray")
2847 
2848         if self.ndim == 1:
2849             return xarray.DataArray.from_series(self)
2850         else:
2851             return xarray.Dataset.from_dataframe(self)

2853     @Substitution(returns=fmt.return_docstring)
2854     def to_latex(
2855         self,
2856         buf=None,
2857         columns=None,
2858         col_space=None,
2859         header=True,
2860         index=True,
2861         na_rep="NaN",
2862         formatters=None,
2863         float_format=None,
2864         sparsify=None,
2865         index_names=True,
2866         bold_rows=False,
2867         column_format=None,
2868         longtable=None,
2869         escape=None,
2870         encoding=None,
2871         decimal=".",
2872         multicolumn=None,
2873         multicolumn_format=None,
2874         multirow=None,
2875         caption=None,
2876         label=None,
2877     ):
2878         r"""
2879         Render object to a LaTeX tabular, longtable, or nested table/tabular.
2880 
2881         Requires ``\usepackage{booktabs}``.  The output can be copy/pasted
2882         into a main LaTeX document or read from an external file
2883         with ``\input{table.tex}``.
2884 
2885         .. versionchanged:: 0.20.2
2886            Added to Series.
2887 
2888         .. versionchanged:: 1.0.0
2889            Added caption and label arguments.
2890 
2891         Parameters
2892         ----------
2893         buf : str, Path or StringIO-like, optional, default None
2894             Buffer to write to. If None, the output is returned as a string.
2895         columns : list of label, optional
2896             The subset of columns to write. Writes all columns by default.
2897         col_space : int, optional
2898             The minimum width of each column.
2899         header : bool or list of str, default True
2900             Write out the column names. If a list of strings is given,
2901             it is assumed to be aliases for the column names.
2902         index : bool, default True
2903             Write row names (index).
2904         na_rep : str, default 'NaN'
2905             Missing data representation.
2906         formatters : list of functions or dict of {str: function}, optional
2907             Formatter functions to apply to columns' elements by position or
2908             name. The result of each function must be a unicode string.
2909             List must be of length equal to the number of columns.
2910         float_format : one-parameter function or str, optional, default None
2911             Formatter for floating point numbers. For example
2912             ``float_format="%%.2f"`` and ``float_format="{:0.2f}".format`` will
2913             both result in 0.1234 being formatted as 0.12.
2914         sparsify : bool, optional
2915             Set to False for a DataFrame with a hierarchical index to print
2916             every multiindex key at each row. By default, the value will be
2917             read from the config module.
2918         index_names : bool, default True
2919             Prints the names of the indexes.
2920         bold_rows : bool, default False
2921             Make the row labels bold in the output.
2922         column_format : str, optional
2923             The columns format as specified in `LaTeX table format
2924             <https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/LaTeX/Tables>`__ e.g. 'rcl' for 3
2925             columns. By default, 'l' will be used for all columns except
2926             columns of numbers, which default to 'r'.
2927         longtable : bool, optional
2928             By default, the value will be read from the pandas config
2929             module. Use a longtable environment instead of tabular. Requires
2930             adding a \usepackage{longtable} to your LaTeX preamble.
2931         escape : bool, optional
2932             By default, the value will be read from the pandas config
2933             module. When set to False prevents from escaping latex special
2934             characters in column names.
2935         encoding : str, optional
2936             A string representing the encoding to use in the output file,
2937             defaults to 'utf-8'.
2938         decimal : str, default '.'
2939             Character recognized as decimal separator, e.g. ',' in Europe.
2940         multicolumn : bool, default True
2941             Use \multicolumn to enhance MultiIndex columns.
2942             The default will be read from the config module.
2943         multicolumn_format : str, default 'l'
2944             The alignment for multicolumns, similar to `column_format`
2945             The default will be read from the config module.
2946         multirow : bool, default False
2947             Use \multirow to enhance MultiIndex rows. Requires adding a
2948             \usepackage{multirow} to your LaTeX preamble. Will print
2949             centered labels (instead of top-aligned) across the contained
2950             rows, separating groups via clines. The default will be read
2951             from the pandas config module.
2952         caption : str, optional
2953             The LaTeX caption to be placed inside ``\caption{}`` in the output.
2954 
2955             .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
2956 
2957         label : str, optional
2958             The LaTeX label to be placed inside ``\label{}`` in the output.
2959             This is used with ``\ref{}`` in the main ``.tex`` file.
2960 
2961             .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
2962         %(returns)s
2963         See Also
2964         --------
2965         DataFrame.to_string : Render a DataFrame to a console-friendly
2966             tabular output.
2967         DataFrame.to_html : Render a DataFrame as an HTML table.
2968 
2969         Examples
2970         --------
2971         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'name': ['Raphael', 'Donatello'],
2972         ...                    'mask': ['red', 'purple'],
2973         ...                    'weapon': ['sai', 'bo staff']})
2974         >>> print(df.to_latex(index=False))  # doctest: +NORMALIZE_WHITESPACE
2975         \begin{tabular}{lll}
2976          \toprule
2977                name &    mask &    weapon \\
2978          \midrule
2979             Raphael &     red &       sai \\
2980           Donatello &  purple &  bo staff \\
2981         \bottomrule
2982         \end{tabular}
2983         """
2984         # Get defaults from the pandas config
2985         if self.ndim == 1:
2986             self = self.to_frame()
2987         if longtable is None:
2988             longtable = config.get_option("display.latex.longtable")
2989         if escape is None:
2990             escape = config.get_option("display.latex.escape")
2991         if multicolumn is None:
2992             multicolumn = config.get_option("display.latex.multicolumn")
2993         if multicolumn_format is None:
2994             multicolumn_format = config.get_option("display.latex.multicolumn_format")
2995         if multirow is None:
2996             multirow = config.get_option("display.latex.multirow")
2997 
2998         formatter = DataFrameFormatter(
2999             self,
3000             columns=columns,
3001             col_space=col_space,
3002             na_rep=na_rep,
3003             header=header,
3004             index=index,
3005             formatters=formatters,
3006             float_format=float_format,
3007             bold_rows=bold_rows,
3008             sparsify=sparsify,
3009             index_names=index_names,
3010             escape=escape,
3011             decimal=decimal,
3012         )
3013         return formatter.to_latex(
3014             buf=buf,
3015             column_format=column_format,
3016             longtable=longtable,
3017             encoding=encoding,
3018             multicolumn=multicolumn,
3019             multicolumn_format=multicolumn_format,
3020             multirow=multirow,
3021             caption=caption,
3022             label=label,
3023         )
3024 
3025     def to_csv(
3026         self,
3027         path_or_buf: Optional[FilePathOrBuffer] = None,
3028         sep: str = ",",
3029         na_rep: str = "",
3030         float_format: Optional[str] = None,
3031         columns: Optional[Sequence[Label]] = None,
3032         header: Union[bool_t, List[str]] = True,
3033         index: bool_t = True,
3034         index_label: Optional[Union[bool_t, str, Sequence[Label]]] = None,
3035         mode: str = "w",
3036         encoding: Optional[str] = None,
3037         compression: Optional[Union[str, Mapping[str, str]]] = "infer",
3038         quoting: Optional[int] = None,
3039         quotechar: str = '"',
3040         line_terminator: Optional[str] = None,
3041         chunksize: Optional[int] = None,
3042         date_format: Optional[str] = None,
3043         doublequote: bool_t = True,
3044         escapechar: Optional[str] = None,
3045         decimal: Optional[str] = ".",
3046         errors: str = "strict",
3047     ) -> Optional[str]:
3048         r"""
3049         Write object to a comma-separated values (csv) file.
3050 
3051         .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0
3052             The order of arguments for Series was changed.
3053 
3054         Parameters
3055         ----------
3056         path_or_buf : str or file handle, default None
3057             File path or object, if None is provided the result is returned as
3058             a string.  If a file object is passed it should be opened with
3059             `newline=''`, disabling universal newlines.
3060 
3061             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0
3062 
3063                Was previously named "path" for Series.
3064 
3065         sep : str, default ','
3066             String of length 1. Field delimiter for the output file.
3067         na_rep : str, default ''
3068             Missing data representation.
3069         float_format : str, default None
3070             Format string for floating point numbers.
3071         columns : sequence, optional
3072             Columns to write.
3073         header : bool or list of str, default True
3074             Write out the column names. If a list of strings is given it is
3075             assumed to be aliases for the column names.
3076 
3077             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0
3078 
3079                Previously defaulted to False for Series.
3080 
3081         index : bool, default True
3082             Write row names (index).
3083         index_label : str or sequence, or False, default None
3084             Column label for index column(s) if desired. If None is given, and
3085             `header` and `index` are True, then the index names are used. A
3086             sequence should be given if the object uses MultiIndex. If
3087             False do not print fields for index names. Use index_label=False
3088             for easier importing in R.
3089         mode : str
3090             Python write mode, default 'w'.
3091         encoding : str, optional
3092             A string representing the encoding to use in the output file,
3093             defaults to 'utf-8'.
3094         compression : str or dict, default 'infer'
3095             If str, represents compression mode. If dict, value at 'method' is
3096             the compression mode. Compression mode may be any of the following
3097             possible values: {'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}. If
3098             compression mode is 'infer' and `path_or_buf` is path-like, then
3099             detect compression mode from the following extensions: '.gz',
3100             '.bz2', '.zip' or '.xz'. (otherwise no compression). If dict given
3101             and mode is one of {'zip', 'gzip', 'bz2'}, or inferred as
3102             one of the above, other entries passed as
3103             additional compression options.
3104 
3105             .. versionchanged:: 1.0.0
3106 
3107                May now be a dict with key 'method' as compression mode
3108                and other entries as additional compression options if
3109                compression mode is 'zip'.
3110 
3111             .. versionchanged:: 1.1.0
3112 
3113                Passing compression options as keys in dict is
3114                supported for compression modes 'gzip' and 'bz2'
3115                as well as 'zip'.
3116 
3117         quoting : optional constant from csv module
3118             Defaults to csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL. If you have set a `float_format`
3119             then floats are converted to strings and thus csv.QUOTE_NONNUMERIC
3120             will treat them as non-numeric.
3121         quotechar : str, default '\"'
3122             String of length 1. Character used to quote fields.
3123         line_terminator : str, optional
3124             The newline character or character sequence to use in the output
3125             file. Defaults to `os.linesep`, which depends on the OS in which
3126             this method is called ('\n' for linux, '\r\n' for Windows, i.e.).
3127 
3128             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0
3129         chunksize : int or None
3130             Rows to write at a time.
3131         date_format : str, default None
3132             Format string for datetime objects.
3133         doublequote : bool, default True
3134             Control quoting of `quotechar` inside a field.
3135         escapechar : str, default None
3136             String of length 1. Character used to escape `sep` and `quotechar`
3137             when appropriate.
3138         decimal : str, default '.'
3139             Character recognized as decimal separator. E.g. use ',' for
3140             European data.
3141         errors : str, default 'strict'
3142             Specifies how encoding and decoding errors are to be handled.
3143             See the errors argument for :func:`open` for a full list
3144             of options.
3145 
3146             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
3147 
3148         Returns
3149         -------
3150         None or str
3151             If path_or_buf is None, returns the resulting csv format as a
3152             string. Otherwise returns None.
3153 
3154         See Also
3155         --------
3156         read_csv : Load a CSV file into a DataFrame.
3157         to_excel : Write DataFrame to an Excel file.
3158 
3159         Examples
3160         --------
3161         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'name': ['Raphael', 'Donatello'],
3162         ...                    'mask': ['red', 'purple'],
3163         ...                    'weapon': ['sai', 'bo staff']})
3164         >>> df.to_csv(index=False)
3165         'name,mask,weapon\nRaphael,red,sai\nDonatello,purple,bo staff\n'
3166 
3167         Create 'out.zip' containing 'out.csv'
3168 
3169         >>> compression_opts = dict(method='zip',
3170         ...                         archive_name='out.csv')  # doctest: +SKIP
3171         >>> df.to_csv('out.zip', index=False,
3172         ...           compression=compression_opts)  # doctest: +SKIP
3173         """
3174         df = self if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) else self.to_frame()
3175 
3176         from pandas.io.formats.csvs import CSVFormatter
3177 
3178         formatter = CSVFormatter(
3179             df,
3180             path_or_buf,
3181             line_terminator=line_terminator,
3182             sep=sep,
3183             encoding=encoding,
3184             errors=errors,
3185             compression=compression,
3186             quoting=quoting,
3187             na_rep=na_rep,
3188             float_format=float_format,
3189             cols=columns,
3190             header=header,
3191             index=index,
3192             index_label=index_label,
3193             mode=mode,
3194             chunksize=chunksize,
3195             quotechar=quotechar,
3196             date_format=date_format,
3197             doublequote=doublequote,
3198             escapechar=escapechar,
3199             decimal=decimal,
3200         )
3201         formatter.save()
3202 
3203         if path_or_buf is None:
3204             return formatter.path_or_buf.getvalue()
3205 
3206         return None

3208     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
3209     # Lookup Caching
3210 
3211     def _set_as_cached(self, item, cacher) -> None:
3212         """
3213         Set the _cacher attribute on the calling object with a weakref to
3214         cacher.
3215         """
3216         self._cacher = (item, weakref.ref(cacher))
3217 
3218     def _reset_cacher(self) -> None:
3219         """
3220         Reset the cacher.
3221         """
3222         if hasattr(self, "_cacher"):
3223             del self._cacher
3224 
3225     def _maybe_cache_changed(self, item, value) -> None:
3226         """
3227         The object has called back to us saying maybe it has changed.
3228         """
3229         loc = self._info_axis.get_loc(item)
3230         self._mgr.iset(loc, value)
3231 
3232     @property
3233     def _is_cached(self) -> bool_t:
3234         """Return boolean indicating if self is cached or not."""
3235         return getattr(self, "_cacher", None) is not None
3236 
3237     def _get_cacher(self):
3238         """return my cacher or None"""
3239         cacher = getattr(self, "_cacher", None)
3240         if cacher is not None:
3241             cacher = cacher[1]()
3242         return cacher
3243 
3244     def _maybe_update_cacher(
3245         self, clear: bool_t = False, verify_is_copy: bool_t = True
3246     ) -> None:
3247         """
3248         See if we need to update our parent cacher if clear, then clear our
3249         cache.
3250 
3251         Parameters
3252         ----------
3253         clear : bool, default False
3254             Clear the item cache.
3255         verify_is_copy : bool, default True
3256             Provide is_copy checks.
3257         """
3258         cacher = getattr(self, "_cacher", None)
3259         if cacher is not None:
3260             ref = cacher[1]()
3261 
3262             # we are trying to reference a dead referant, hence
3263             # a copy
3264             if ref is None:
3265                 del self._cacher
3266             else:
3267                 if len(self) == len(ref):
3268                     # otherwise, either self or ref has swapped in new arrays
3269                     ref._maybe_cache_changed(cacher[0], self)
3270 
3271         if verify_is_copy:
3272             self._check_setitem_copy(stacklevel=5, t="referant")
3273 
3274         if clear:
3275             self._clear_item_cache()
3276 
3277     def _clear_item_cache(self) -> None:
3278         self._item_cache.clear()
3279 
3280     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
3281     # Indexing Methods
3282 
3283     def take(
3284         self: FrameOrSeries, indices, axis=0, is_copy: Optional[bool_t] = None, **kwargs
3285     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
3286         """
3287         Return the elements in the given *positional* indices along an axis.
3288 
3289         This means that we are not indexing according to actual values in
3290         the index attribute of the object. We are indexing according to the
3291         actual position of the element in the object.
3292 
3293         Parameters
3294         ----------
3295         indices : array-like
3296             An array of ints indicating which positions to take.
3297         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default 0
3298             The axis on which to select elements. ``0`` means that we are
3299             selecting rows, ``1`` means that we are selecting columns.
3300         is_copy : bool
3301             Before pandas 1.0, ``is_copy=False`` can be specified to ensure
3302             that the return value is an actual copy. Starting with pandas 1.0,
3303             ``take`` always returns a copy, and the keyword is therefore
3304             deprecated.
3305 
3306             .. deprecated:: 1.0.0
3307         **kwargs
3308             For compatibility with :meth:`numpy.take`. Has no effect on the
3309             output.
3310 
3311         Returns
3312         -------
3313         taken : same type as caller
3314             An array-like containing the elements taken from the object.
3315 
3316         See Also
3317         --------
3318         DataFrame.loc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by labels.
3319         DataFrame.iloc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by positions.
3320         numpy.take : Take elements from an array along an axis.
3321 
3322         Examples
3323         --------
3324         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0),
3325         ...                    ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0),
3326         ...                    ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5),
3327         ...                    ('monkey', 'mammal', np.nan)],
3328         ...                   columns=['name', 'class', 'max_speed'],
3329         ...                   index=[0, 2, 3, 1])
3330         >>> df
3331              name   class  max_speed
3332         0  falcon    bird      389.0
3333         2  parrot    bird       24.0
3334         3    lion  mammal       80.5
3335         1  monkey  mammal        NaN
3336 
3337         Take elements at positions 0 and 3 along the axis 0 (default).
3338 
3339         Note how the actual indices selected (0 and 1) do not correspond to
3340         our selected indices 0 and 3. That's because we are selecting the 0th
3341         and 3rd rows, not rows whose indices equal 0 and 3.
3342 
3343         >>> df.take([0, 3])
3344              name   class  max_speed
3345         0  falcon    bird      389.0
3346         1  monkey  mammal        NaN
3347 
3348         Take elements at indices 1 and 2 along the axis 1 (column selection).
3349 
3350         >>> df.take([1, 2], axis=1)
3351             class  max_speed
3352         0    bird      389.0
3353         2    bird       24.0
3354         3  mammal       80.5
3355         1  mammal        NaN
3356 
3357         We may take elements using negative integers for positive indices,
3358         starting from the end of the object, just like with Python lists.
3359 
3360         >>> df.take([-1, -2])
3361              name   class  max_speed
3362         1  monkey  mammal        NaN
3363         3    lion  mammal       80.5
3364         """
3365         if is_copy is not None:
3366             warnings.warn(
3367                 "is_copy is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. "
3368                 "'take' always returns a copy, so there is no need to specify this.",
3369                 FutureWarning,
3370                 stacklevel=2,
3371             )
3372 
3373         nv.validate_take(tuple(), kwargs)
3374 
3375         new_data = self._mgr.take(
3376             indices, axis=self._get_block_manager_axis(axis), verify=True
3377         )
3378         return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self, method="take")
3379 
3380     def _take_with_is_copy(self: FrameOrSeries, indices, axis=0) -> FrameOrSeries:
3381         """
3382         Internal version of the `take` method that sets the `_is_copy`
3383         attribute to keep track of the parent dataframe (using in indexing
3384         for the SettingWithCopyWarning).
3385 
3386         See the docstring of `take` for full explanation of the parameters.
3387         """
3388         result = self.take(indices=indices, axis=axis)
3389         # Maybe set copy if we didn't actually change the index.
3390         if not result._get_axis(axis).equals(self._get_axis(axis)):
3391             result._set_is_copy(self)
3392         return result
3393 
3394     def xs(self, key, axis=0, level=None, drop_level: bool_t = True):
3395         """
3396         Return cross-section from the Series/DataFrame.
3397 
3398         This method takes a `key` argument to select data at a particular
3399         level of a MultiIndex.
3400 
3401         Parameters
3402         ----------
3403         key : label or tuple of label
3404             Label contained in the index, or partially in a MultiIndex.
3405         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
3406             Axis to retrieve cross-section on.
3407         level : object, defaults to first n levels (n=1 or len(key))
3408             In case of a key partially contained in a MultiIndex, indicate
3409             which levels are used. Levels can be referred by label or position.
3410         drop_level : bool, default True
3411             If False, returns object with same levels as self.
3412 
3413         Returns
3414         -------
3415         Series or DataFrame
3416             Cross-section from the original Series or DataFrame
3417             corresponding to the selected index levels.
3418 
3419         See Also
3420         --------
3421         DataFrame.loc : Access a group of rows and columns
3422             by label(s) or a boolean array.
3423         DataFrame.iloc : Purely integer-location based indexing
3424             for selection by position.
3425 
3426         Notes
3427         -----
3428         `xs` can not be used to set values.
3429 
3430         MultiIndex Slicers is a generic way to get/set values on
3431         any level or levels.
3432         It is a superset of `xs` functionality, see
3433         :ref:`MultiIndex Slicers <advanced.mi_slicers>`.
3434 
3435         Examples
3436         --------
3437         >>> d = {'num_legs': [4, 4, 2, 2],
3438         ...      'num_wings': [0, 0, 2, 2],
3439         ...      'class': ['mammal', 'mammal', 'mammal', 'bird'],
3440         ...      'animal': ['cat', 'dog', 'bat', 'penguin'],
3441         ...      'locomotion': ['walks', 'walks', 'flies', 'walks']}
3442         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data=d)
3443         >>> df = df.set_index(['class', 'animal', 'locomotion'])
3444         >>> df
3445                                    num_legs  num_wings
3446         class  animal  locomotion
3447         mammal cat     walks              4          0
3448                dog     walks              4          0
3449                bat     flies              2          2
3450         bird   penguin walks              2          2
3451 
3452         Get values at specified index
3453 
3454         >>> df.xs('mammal')
3455                            num_legs  num_wings
3456         animal locomotion
3457         cat    walks              4          0
3458         dog    walks              4          0
3459         bat    flies              2          2
3460 
3461         Get values at several indexes
3462 
3463         >>> df.xs(('mammal', 'dog'))
3464                     num_legs  num_wings
3465         locomotion
3466         walks              4          0
3467 
3468         Get values at specified index and level
3469 
3470         >>> df.xs('cat', level=1)
3471                            num_legs  num_wings
3472         class  locomotion
3473         mammal walks              4          0
3474 
3475         Get values at several indexes and levels
3476 
3477         >>> df.xs(('bird', 'walks'),
3478         ...       level=[0, 'locomotion'])
3479                  num_legs  num_wings
3480         animal
3481         penguin         2          2
3482 
3483         Get values at specified column and axis
3484 
3485         >>> df.xs('num_wings', axis=1)
3486         class   animal   locomotion
3487         mammal  cat      walks         0
3488                 dog      walks         0
3489                 bat      flies         2
3490         bird    penguin  walks         2
3491         Name: num_wings, dtype: int64
3492         """
3493         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
3494         labels = self._get_axis(axis)
3495         if level is not None:
3496             if not isinstance(labels, MultiIndex):
3497                 raise TypeError("Index must be a MultiIndex")
3498             loc, new_ax = labels.get_loc_level(key, level=level, drop_level=drop_level)
3499 
3500             # create the tuple of the indexer
3501             _indexer = [slice(None)] * self.ndim
3502             _indexer[axis] = loc
3503             indexer = tuple(_indexer)
3504 
3505             result = self.iloc[indexer]
3506             setattr(result, result._get_axis_name(axis), new_ax)
3507             return result
3508 
3509         if axis == 1:
3510             return self[key]
3511 
3512         index = self.index
3513         if isinstance(index, MultiIndex):
3514             loc, new_index = self.index.get_loc_level(key, drop_level=drop_level)
3515         else:
3516             loc = self.index.get_loc(key)
3517 
3518             if isinstance(loc, np.ndarray):
3519                 if loc.dtype == np.bool_:
3520                     (inds,) = loc.nonzero()
3521                     return self._take_with_is_copy(inds, axis=axis)
3522                 else:
3523                     return self._take_with_is_copy(loc, axis=axis)
3524 
3525             if not is_scalar(loc):
3526                 new_index = self.index[loc]
3527 
3528         if is_scalar(loc):
3529             # In this case loc should be an integer
3530             if self.ndim == 1:
3531                 # if we encounter an array-like and we only have 1 dim
3532                 # that means that their are list/ndarrays inside the Series!
3533                 # so just return them (GH 6394)
3534                 return self._values[loc]
3535 
3536             new_values = self._mgr.fast_xs(loc)
3537 
3538             result = self._constructor_sliced(
3539                 new_values,
3540                 index=self.columns,
3541                 name=self.index[loc],
3542                 dtype=new_values.dtype,
3543             )
3544 
3545         else:
3546             result = self.iloc[loc]
3547             result.index = new_index
3548 
3549         # this could be a view
3550         # but only in a single-dtyped view sliceable case
3551         result._set_is_copy(self, copy=not result._is_view)
3552         return result
3553 
3554     def __getitem__(self, item):
3555         raise AbstractMethodError(self)
3556 
3557     def _get_item_cache(self, item):
3558         """Return the cached item, item represents a label indexer."""
3559         cache = self._item_cache
3560         res = cache.get(item)
3561         if res is None:
3562             # All places that call _get_item_cache have unique columns,
3563             #  pending resolution of GH#33047
3564 
3565             loc = self.columns.get_loc(item)
3566             values = self._mgr.iget(loc)
3567             res = self._box_col_values(values, loc)
3568 
3569             cache[item] = res
3570             res._set_as_cached(item, self)
3571 
3572             # for a chain
3573             res._is_copy = self._is_copy
3574         return res
3575 
3576     def _slice(self: FrameOrSeries, slobj: slice, axis=0) -> FrameOrSeries:
3577         """
3578         Construct a slice of this container.
3579 
3580         Slicing with this method is *always* positional.
3581         """
3582         assert isinstance(slobj, slice), type(slobj)
3583         axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis)
3584         result = self._constructor(self._mgr.get_slice(slobj, axis=axis))
3585         result = result.__finalize__(self)
3586 
3587         # this could be a view
3588         # but only in a single-dtyped view sliceable case
3589         is_copy = axis != 0 or result._is_view
3590         result._set_is_copy(self, copy=is_copy)
3591         return result

3593     def _iset_item(self, loc: int, value) -> None:

3597     def _set_item(self, key, value) -> None:
3598         try:
3599             loc = self._info_axis.get_loc(key)
3600         except KeyError:
3601             # This item wasn't present, just insert at end
3602             self._mgr.insert(len(self._info_axis), key, value)
3603             return
3604 
3605         NDFrame._iset_item(self, loc, value)
