3607     def _set_is_copy(self, ref, copy: bool_t = True) -> None:
3608         if not copy:
3609             self._is_copy = None
3610         else:
3611             assert ref is not None
3612             self._is_copy = weakref.ref(ref)
3613 
3614     def _check_is_chained_assignment_possible(self) -> bool_t:
3615         """
3616         Check if we are a view, have a cacher, and are of mixed type.
3617         If so, then force a setitem_copy check.
3618 
3619         Should be called just near setting a value
3620 
3621         Will return a boolean if it we are a view and are cached, but a
3622         single-dtype meaning that the cacher should be updated following
3623         setting.
3624         """
3625         if self._is_view and self._is_cached:
3626             ref = self._get_cacher()
3627             if ref is not None and ref._is_mixed_type:
3628                 self._check_setitem_copy(stacklevel=4, t="referant", force=True)
3629             return True
3630         elif self._is_copy:
3631             self._check_setitem_copy(stacklevel=4, t="referant")
3632         return False
3633 
3634     def _check_setitem_copy(self, stacklevel=4, t="setting", force=False):
3635         """
3636 
3637         Parameters
3638         ----------
3639         stacklevel : int, default 4
3640            the level to show of the stack when the error is output
3641         t : str, the type of setting error
3642         force : bool, default False
3643            If True, then force showing an error.
3644 
3645         validate if we are doing a setitem on a chained copy.
3646 
3647         If you call this function, be sure to set the stacklevel such that the
3648         user will see the error *at the level of setting*
3649 
3650         It is technically possible to figure out that we are setting on
3651         a copy even WITH a multi-dtyped pandas object. In other words, some
3652         blocks may be views while other are not. Currently _is_view will ALWAYS
3653         return False for multi-blocks to avoid having to handle this case.
3654 
3655         df = DataFrame(np.arange(0,9), columns=['count'])
3656         df['group'] = 'b'
3657 
3658         # This technically need not raise SettingWithCopy if both are view
3659         # (which is not # generally guaranteed but is usually True.  However,
3660         # this is in general not a good practice and we recommend using .loc.
3661         df.iloc[0:5]['group'] = 'a'
3662 
3663         """
3664         # return early if the check is not needed
3665         if not (force or self._is_copy):
3666             return
3667 
3668         value = config.get_option("mode.chained_assignment")
3669         if value is None:
3670             return
3671 
3672         # see if the copy is not actually referred; if so, then dissolve
3673         # the copy weakref
3674         if self._is_copy is not None and not isinstance(self._is_copy, str):
3675             r = self._is_copy()
3676             if not gc.get_referents(r) or r.shape == self.shape:
3677                 self._is_copy = None
3678                 return
3679 
3680         # a custom message
3681         if isinstance(self._is_copy, str):
3682             t = self._is_copy
3683 
3684         elif t == "referant":
3685             t = (
3686                 "\n"
3687                 "A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a "
3688                 "DataFrame\n\n"
3689                 "See the caveats in the documentation: "
3690                 "https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/"
3691                 "indexing.html#returning-a-view-versus-a-copy"
3692             )
3693 
3694         else:
3695             t = (
3696                 "\n"
3697                 "A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a "
3698                 "DataFrame.\n"
3699                 "Try using .loc[row_indexer,col_indexer] = value "
3700                 "instead\n\nSee the caveats in the documentation: "
3701                 "https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/"
3702                 "indexing.html#returning-a-view-versus-a-copy"
3703             )
3704 
3705         if value == "raise":
3706             raise com.SettingWithCopyError(t)
3707         elif value == "warn":
3708             warnings.warn(t, com.SettingWithCopyWarning, stacklevel=stacklevel)
3709 
3710     def __delitem__(self, key) -> None:
3711         """
3712         Delete item
3713         """
3714         deleted = False
3715 
3716         maybe_shortcut = False
3717         if self.ndim == 2 and isinstance(self.columns, MultiIndex):
3718             try:
3719                 maybe_shortcut = key not in self.columns._engine
3720             except TypeError:
3721                 pass
3722 
3723         if maybe_shortcut:
3724             # Allow shorthand to delete all columns whose first len(key)
3725             # elements match key:
3726             if not isinstance(key, tuple):
3727                 key = (key,)
3728             for col in self.columns:
3729                 if isinstance(col, tuple) and col[: len(key)] == key:
3730                     del self[col]
3731                     deleted = True
3732         if not deleted:
3733             # If the above loop ran and didn't delete anything because
3734             # there was no match, this call should raise the appropriate
3735             # exception:
3736             loc = self.axes[-1].get_loc(key)
3737             self._mgr.idelete(loc)
3738 
3739         # delete from the caches
3740         try:
3741             del self._item_cache[key]
3742         except KeyError:
3743             pass
3744 
3745     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
3746     # Unsorted
3747 
3748     def get(self, key, default=None):
3749         """
3750         Get item from object for given key (ex: DataFrame column).
3751 
3752         Returns default value if not found.
3753 
3754         Parameters
3755         ----------
3756         key : object
3757 
3758         Returns
3759         -------
3760         value : same type as items contained in object
3761         """
3762         try:
3763             return self[key]
3764         except (KeyError, ValueError, IndexError):
3765             return default
3766 
3767     @property
3768     def _is_view(self) -> bool_t:
3769         """Return boolean indicating if self is view of another array """
3770         return self._mgr.is_view
3771 
3772     def reindex_like(
3773         self: FrameOrSeries,
3774         other,
3775         method: Optional[str] = None,
3776         copy: bool_t = True,
3777         limit=None,
3778         tolerance=None,
3779     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
3780         """
3781         Return an object with matching indices as other object.
3782 
3783         Conform the object to the same index on all axes. Optional
3784         filling logic, placing NaN in locations having no value
3785         in the previous index. A new object is produced unless the
3786         new index is equivalent to the current one and copy=False.
3787 
3788         Parameters
3789         ----------
3790         other : Object of the same data type
3791             Its row and column indices are used to define the new indices
3792             of this object.
3793         method : {None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'}
3794             Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame.
3795             Please note: this is only applicable to DataFrames/Series with a
3796             monotonically increasing/decreasing index.
3797 
3798             * None (default): don't fill gaps
3799             * pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next
3800               valid
3801             * backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap
3802             * nearest: use nearest valid observations to fill gap.
3803 
3804         copy : bool, default True
3805             Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same.
3806         limit : int, default None
3807             Maximum number of consecutive labels to fill for inexact matches.
3808         tolerance : optional
3809             Maximum distance between original and new labels for inexact
3810             matches. The values of the index at the matching locations most
3811             satisfy the equation ``abs(index[indexer] - target) <= tolerance``.
3812 
3813             Tolerance may be a scalar value, which applies the same tolerance
3814             to all values, or list-like, which applies variable tolerance per
3815             element. List-like includes list, tuple, array, Series, and must be
3816             the same size as the index and its dtype must exactly match the
3817             index's type.
3818 
3819         Returns
3820         -------
3821         Series or DataFrame
3822             Same type as caller, but with changed indices on each axis.
3823 
3824         See Also
3825         --------
3826         DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels.
3827         DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns.
3828         DataFrame.reindex : Change to new indices or expand indices.
3829 
3830         Notes
3831         -----
3832         Same as calling
3833         ``.reindex(index=other.index, columns=other.columns,...)``.
3834 
3835         Examples
3836         --------
3837         >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame([[24.3, 75.7, 'high'],
3838         ...                     [31, 87.8, 'high'],
3839         ...                     [22, 71.6, 'medium'],
3840         ...                     [35, 95, 'medium']],
3841         ...                    columns=['temp_celsius', 'temp_fahrenheit',
3842         ...                             'windspeed'],
3843         ...                    index=pd.date_range(start='2014-02-12',
3844         ...                                        end='2014-02-15', freq='D'))
3845 
3846         >>> df1
3847                     temp_celsius  temp_fahrenheit windspeed
3848         2014-02-12          24.3             75.7      high
3849         2014-02-13          31.0             87.8      high
3850         2014-02-14          22.0             71.6    medium
3851         2014-02-15          35.0             95.0    medium
3852 
3853         >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame([[28, 'low'],
3854         ...                     [30, 'low'],
3855         ...                     [35.1, 'medium']],
3856         ...                    columns=['temp_celsius', 'windspeed'],
3857         ...                    index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2014-02-12', '2014-02-13',
3858         ...                                            '2014-02-15']))
3859 
3860         >>> df2
3861                     temp_celsius windspeed
3862         2014-02-12          28.0       low
3863         2014-02-13          30.0       low
3864         2014-02-15          35.1    medium
3865 
3866         >>> df2.reindex_like(df1)
3867                     temp_celsius  temp_fahrenheit windspeed
3868         2014-02-12          28.0              NaN       low
3869         2014-02-13          30.0              NaN       low
3870         2014-02-14           NaN              NaN       NaN
3871         2014-02-15          35.1              NaN    medium
3872         """
3873         d = other._construct_axes_dict(
3874             axes=self._AXIS_ORDERS,
3875             method=method,
3876             copy=copy,
3877             limit=limit,
3878             tolerance=tolerance,
3879         )
3880 
3881         return self.reindex(**d)
3882 
3883     def drop(
3884         self,
3885         labels=None,
3886         axis=0,
3887         index=None,
3888         columns=None,
3889         level=None,
3890         inplace: bool_t = False,
3891         errors: str = "raise",
3892     ):
3893 
3894         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
3895 
3896         if labels is not None:
3897             if index is not None or columns is not None:
3898                 raise ValueError("Cannot specify both 'labels' and 'index'/'columns'")
3899             axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis)
3900             axes = {axis_name: labels}
3901         elif index is not None or columns is not None:
3902             axes, _ = self._construct_axes_from_arguments((index, columns), {})
3903         else:
3904             raise ValueError(
3905                 "Need to specify at least one of 'labels', 'index' or 'columns'"
3906             )
3907 
3908         obj = self
3909 
3910         for axis, labels in axes.items():
3911             if labels is not None:
3912                 obj = obj._drop_axis(labels, axis, level=level, errors=errors)
3913 
3914         if inplace:
3915             self._update_inplace(obj)
3916         else:
3917             return obj
3918 
3919     def _drop_axis(
3920         self: FrameOrSeries, labels, axis, level=None, errors: str = "raise"
3921     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
3922         """
3923         Drop labels from specified axis. Used in the ``drop`` method
3924         internally.
3925 
3926         Parameters
3927         ----------
3928         labels : single label or list-like
3929         axis : int or axis name
3930         level : int or level name, default None
3931             For MultiIndex
3932         errors : {'ignore', 'raise'}, default 'raise'
3933             If 'ignore', suppress error and existing labels are dropped.
3934 
3935         """
3936         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
3937         axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis)
3938         axis = self._get_axis(axis)
3939 
3940         if axis.is_unique:
3941             if level is not None:
3942                 if not isinstance(axis, MultiIndex):
3943                     raise AssertionError("axis must be a MultiIndex")
3944                 new_axis = axis.drop(labels, level=level, errors=errors)
3945             else:
3946                 new_axis = axis.drop(labels, errors=errors)
3947             result = self.reindex(**{axis_name: new_axis})
3948 
3949         # Case for non-unique axis
3950         else:
3951             labels = ensure_object(com.index_labels_to_array(labels))
3952             if level is not None:
3953                 if not isinstance(axis, MultiIndex):
3954                     raise AssertionError("axis must be a MultiIndex")
3955                 indexer = ~axis.get_level_values(level).isin(labels)
3956 
3957                 # GH 18561 MultiIndex.drop should raise if label is absent
3958                 if errors == "raise" and indexer.all():
3959                     raise KeyError(f"{labels} not found in axis")
3960             else:
3961                 indexer = ~axis.isin(labels)
3962                 # Check if label doesn't exist along axis
3963                 labels_missing = (axis.get_indexer_for(labels) == -1).any()
3964                 if errors == "raise" and labels_missing:
3965                     raise KeyError(f"{labels} not found in axis")
3966 
3967             slicer = [slice(None)] * self.ndim
3968             slicer[self._get_axis_number(axis_name)] = indexer
3969 
3970             result = self.loc[tuple(slicer)]
3971 
3972         return result
3973 
3974     def _update_inplace(self, result, verify_is_copy: bool_t = True) -> None:
3975         """
3976         Replace self internals with result.
3977 
3978         Parameters
3979         ----------
3980         result : same type as self
3981         verify_is_copy : bool, default True
3982             Provide is_copy checks.
3983         """
3984         # NOTE: This does *not* call __finalize__ and that's an explicit
3985         # decision that we may revisit in the future.
3986         self._reset_cache()
3987         self._clear_item_cache()
3988         self._mgr = result._mgr
3989         self._maybe_update_cacher(verify_is_copy=verify_is_copy)
3990 
3991     def add_prefix(self: FrameOrSeries, prefix: str) -> FrameOrSeries:
3992         """
3993         Prefix labels with string `prefix`.
3994 
3995         For Series, the row labels are prefixed.
3996         For DataFrame, the column labels are prefixed.
3997 
3998         Parameters
3999         ----------
4000         prefix : str
4001             The string to add before each label.
4002 
4003         Returns
4004         -------
4005         Series or DataFrame
4006             New Series or DataFrame with updated labels.
4007 
4008         See Also
4009         --------
4010         Series.add_suffix: Suffix row labels with string `suffix`.
4011         DataFrame.add_suffix: Suffix column labels with string `suffix`.
4012 
4013         Examples
4014         --------
4015         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4])
4016         >>> s
4017         0    1
4018         1    2
4019         2    3
4020         3    4
4021         dtype: int64
4022 
4023         >>> s.add_prefix('item_')
4024         item_0    1
4025         item_1    2
4026         item_2    3
4027         item_3    4
4028         dtype: int64
4029 
4030         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4], 'B': [3, 4, 5, 6]})
4031         >>> df
4032            A  B
4033         0  1  3
4034         1  2  4
4035         2  3  5
4036         3  4  6
4037 
4038         >>> df.add_prefix('col_')
4039              col_A  col_B
4040         0       1       3
4041         1       2       4
4042         2       3       5
4043         3       4       6
4044         """
4045         f = functools.partial("{prefix}{}".format, prefix=prefix)
4046 
4047         mapper = {self._info_axis_name: f}
4048         return self.rename(**mapper)  # type: ignore
4049 
4050     def add_suffix(self: FrameOrSeries, suffix: str) -> FrameOrSeries:
4051         """
4052         Suffix labels with string `suffix`.
4053 
4054         For Series, the row labels are suffixed.
4055         For DataFrame, the column labels are suffixed.
4056 
4057         Parameters
4058         ----------
4059         suffix : str
4060             The string to add after each label.
4061 
4062         Returns
4063         -------
4064         Series or DataFrame
4065             New Series or DataFrame with updated labels.
4066 
4067         See Also
4068         --------
4069         Series.add_prefix: Prefix row labels with string `prefix`.
4070         DataFrame.add_prefix: Prefix column labels with string `prefix`.
4071 
4072         Examples
4073         --------
4074         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4])
4075         >>> s
4076         0    1
4077         1    2
4078         2    3
4079         3    4
4080         dtype: int64
4081 
4082         >>> s.add_suffix('_item')
4083         0_item    1
4084         1_item    2
4085         2_item    3
4086         3_item    4
4087         dtype: int64
4088 
4089         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4], 'B': [3, 4, 5, 6]})
4090         >>> df
4091            A  B
4092         0  1  3

4095         3  4  6
4096 
4097         >>> df.add_suffix('_col')

4100         1       2       4
4101         2       3       5
4102         3       4       6
4103         """
4104         f = functools.partial("{}{suffix}".format, suffix=suffix)
4105 
4106         mapper = {self._info_axis_name: f}
4107         return self.rename(**mapper)  # type: ignore

4109     def sort_values(
4110         self,
4111         axis=0,
4112         ascending=True,
4113         inplace: bool_t = False,
4114         kind: str = "quicksort",
4115         na_position: str = "last",
4116         ignore_index: bool_t = False,
4117         key: ValueKeyFunc = None,
4118     ):
4119         """
4120         Sort by the values along either axis.
4121 
4122         Parameters
4123         ----------%(optional_by)s
4124         axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default 0
4125              Axis to be sorted.
4126         ascending : bool or list of bool, default True
4127              Sort ascending vs. descending. Specify list for multiple sort
4128              orders.  If this is a list of bools, must match the length of
4129              the by.
4130         inplace : bool, default False
4131              If True, perform operation in-place.
4132         kind : {'quicksort', 'mergesort', 'heapsort'}, default 'quicksort'
4133              Choice of sorting algorithm. See also ndarray.np.sort for more
4134              information.  `mergesort` is the only stable algorithm. For
4135              DataFrames, this option is only applied when sorting on a single
4136              column or label.
4137         na_position : {'first', 'last'}, default 'last'
4138              Puts NaNs at the beginning if `first`; `last` puts NaNs at the
4139              end.
4140         ignore_index : bool, default False
4141              If True, the resulting axis will be labeled 0, 1, …, n - 1.
4142 
4143              .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
4144 
4145         key : callable, optional
4146             Apply the key function to the values
4147             before sorting. This is similar to the `key` argument in the
4148             builtin :meth:`sorted` function, with the notable difference that
4149             this `key` function should be *vectorized*. It should expect a
4150             ``Series`` and return a Series with the same shape as the input.
4151             It will be applied to each column in `by` independently.
4152 
4153             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
4154 
4155         Returns
4156         -------
4157         DataFrame or None
4158             DataFrame with sorted values if inplace=False, None otherwise.
4159 
4160         See Also
4161         --------
4162         DataFrame.sort_index : Sort a DataFrame by the index.
4163         Series.sort_values : Similar method for a Series.
4164 
4165         Examples
4166         --------
4167         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({
4168         ...     'col1': ['A', 'A', 'B', np.nan, 'D', 'C'],
4169         ...     'col2': [2, 1, 9, 8, 7, 4],
4170         ...     'col3': [0, 1, 9, 4, 2, 3],
4171         ...     'col4': ['a', 'B', 'c', 'D', 'e', 'F']
4172         ... })
4173         >>> df
4174           col1  col2  col3 col4
4175         0    A     2     0    a
4176         1    A     1     1    B
4177         2    B     9     9    c
4178         3  NaN     8     4    D
4179         4    D     7     2    e
4180         5    C     4     3    F
4181 
4182         Sort by col1
4183 
4184         >>> df.sort_values(by=['col1'])
4185           col1  col2  col3 col4
4186         0    A     2     0    a
4187         1    A     1     1    B
4188         2    B     9     9    c
4189         5    C     4     3    F
4190         4    D     7     2    e
4191         3  NaN     8     4    D
4192 
4193         Sort by multiple columns
4194 
4195         >>> df.sort_values(by=['col1', 'col2'])
4196           col1  col2  col3 col4
4197         1    A     1     1    B
4198         0    A     2     0    a
4199         2    B     9     9    c
4200         5    C     4     3    F
4201         4    D     7     2    e
4202         3  NaN     8     4    D
4203 
4204         Sort Descending
4205 
4206         >>> df.sort_values(by='col1', ascending=False)
4207           col1  col2  col3 col4
4208         4    D     7     2    e
4209         5    C     4     3    F
4210         2    B     9     9    c
4211         0    A     2     0    a
4212         1    A     1     1    B
4213         3  NaN     8     4    D
4214 
4215         Putting NAs first
4216 
4217         >>> df.sort_values(by='col1', ascending=False, na_position='first')
4218           col1  col2  col3 col4
4219         3  NaN     8     4    D
4220         4    D     7     2    e
4221         5    C     4     3    F
4222         2    B     9     9    c
4223         0    A     2     0    a
4224         1    A     1     1    B
4225 
4226         Sorting with a key function
4227 
4228         >>> df.sort_values(by='col4', key=lambda col: col.str.lower())
4229            col1  col2  col3 col4
4230         0    A     2     0    a
4231         1    A     1     1    B
4232         2    B     9     9    c
4233         3  NaN     8     4    D
4234         4    D     7     2    e
4235         5    C     4     3    F
4236         """
4237         raise AbstractMethodError(self)
4238 
4239     def reindex(self: FrameOrSeries, *args, **kwargs) -> FrameOrSeries:
4240         """
4241         Conform %(klass)s to new index with optional filling logic.
4242 
4243         Places NA/NaN in locations having no value in the previous index. A new object
4244         is produced unless the new index is equivalent to the current one and
4245         ``copy=False``.
4246 
4247         Parameters
4248         ----------
4249         %(optional_labels)s
4250         %(axes)s : array-like, optional
4251             New labels / index to conform to, should be specified using
4252             keywords. Preferably an Index object to avoid duplicating data.
4253         %(optional_axis)s
4254         method : {None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'}
4255             Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame.
4256             Please note: this is only applicable to DataFrames/Series with a
4257             monotonically increasing/decreasing index.
4258 
4259             * None (default): don't fill gaps
4260             * pad / ffill: Propagate last valid observation forward to next
4261               valid.
4262             * backfill / bfill: Use next valid observation to fill gap.
4263             * nearest: Use nearest valid observations to fill gap.
4264 
4265         copy : bool, default True
4266             Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same.
4267         level : int or name
4268             Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the
4269             passed MultiIndex level.
4270         fill_value : scalar, default np.NaN
4271             Value to use for missing values. Defaults to NaN, but can be any
4272             "compatible" value.
4273         limit : int, default None
4274             Maximum number of consecutive elements to forward or backward fill.
4275         tolerance : optional
4276             Maximum distance between original and new labels for inexact
4277             matches. The values of the index at the matching locations most
4278             satisfy the equation ``abs(index[indexer] - target) <= tolerance``.
4279 
4280             Tolerance may be a scalar value, which applies the same tolerance
4281             to all values, or list-like, which applies variable tolerance per
4282             element. List-like includes list, tuple, array, Series, and must be
4283             the same size as the index and its dtype must exactly match the
4284             index's type.
4285 
4286         Returns
4287         -------
4288         %(klass)s with changed index.
4289 
4290         See Also
4291         --------
4292         DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels.
4293         DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns.
4294         DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame.
4295 
4296         Examples
4297         --------
4298         ``DataFrame.reindex`` supports two calling conventions
4299 
4300         * ``(index=index_labels, columns=column_labels, ...)``
4301         * ``(labels, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)``
4302 
4303         We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your
4304         intent.
4305 
4306         Create a dataframe with some fictional data.
4307 
4308         >>> index = ['Firefox', 'Chrome', 'Safari', 'IE10', 'Konqueror']
4309         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'http_status': [200, 200, 404, 404, 301],
4310         ...                   'response_time': [0.04, 0.02, 0.07, 0.08, 1.0]},
4311         ...                   index=index)
4312         >>> df
4313                    http_status  response_time
4314         Firefox            200           0.04
4315         Chrome             200           0.02
4316         Safari             404           0.07
4317         IE10               404           0.08
4318         Konqueror          301           1.00
4319 
4320         Create a new index and reindex the dataframe. By default
4321         values in the new index that do not have corresponding
4322         records in the dataframe are assigned ``NaN``.
4323 
4324         >>> new_index = ['Safari', 'Iceweasel', 'Comodo Dragon', 'IE10',
4325         ...              'Chrome']
4326         >>> df.reindex(new_index)
4327                        http_status  response_time
4328         Safari               404.0           0.07
4329         Iceweasel              NaN            NaN
4330         Comodo Dragon          NaN            NaN
4331         IE10                 404.0           0.08
4332         Chrome               200.0           0.02
4333 
4334         We can fill in the missing values by passing a value to
4335         the keyword ``fill_value``. Because the index is not monotonically
4336         increasing or decreasing, we cannot use arguments to the keyword
4337         ``method`` to fill the ``NaN`` values.
4338 
4339         >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value=0)
4340                        http_status  response_time
4341         Safari                 404           0.07
4342         Iceweasel                0           0.00
4343         Comodo Dragon            0           0.00
4344         IE10                   404           0.08
4345         Chrome                 200           0.02
4346 
4347         >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value='missing')
4348                       http_status response_time
4349         Safari                404          0.07
4350         Iceweasel         missing       missing
4351         Comodo Dragon     missing       missing
4352         IE10                  404          0.08
4353         Chrome                200          0.02
4354 
4355         We can also reindex the columns.
4356 
4357         >>> df.reindex(columns=['http_status', 'user_agent'])
4358                    http_status  user_agent
4359         Firefox            200         NaN
4360         Chrome             200         NaN
4361         Safari             404         NaN
4362         IE10               404         NaN
4363         Konqueror          301         NaN
4364 
4365         Or we can use "axis-style" keyword arguments
4366 
4367         >>> df.reindex(['http_status', 'user_agent'], axis="columns")
4368                    http_status  user_agent
4369         Firefox            200         NaN
4370         Chrome             200         NaN
4371         Safari             404         NaN
4372         IE10               404         NaN
4373         Konqueror          301         NaN
4374 
4375         To further illustrate the filling functionality in
4376         ``reindex``, we will create a dataframe with a
4377         monotonically increasing index (for example, a sequence
4378         of dates).
4379 
4380         >>> date_index = pd.date_range('1/1/2010', periods=6, freq='D')
4381         >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({"prices": [100, 101, np.nan, 100, 89, 88]},
4382         ...                    index=date_index)
4383         >>> df2
4384                     prices
4385         2010-01-01   100.0
4386         2010-01-02   101.0
4387         2010-01-03     NaN
4388         2010-01-04   100.0
4389         2010-01-05    89.0
4390         2010-01-06    88.0
4391 
4392         Suppose we decide to expand the dataframe to cover a wider
4393         date range.
4394 
4395         >>> date_index2 = pd.date_range('12/29/2009', periods=10, freq='D')
4396         >>> df2.reindex(date_index2)
4397                     prices
4398         2009-12-29     NaN
4399         2009-12-30     NaN
4400         2009-12-31     NaN
4401         2010-01-01   100.0
4402         2010-01-02   101.0
4403         2010-01-03     NaN
4404         2010-01-04   100.0
4405         2010-01-05    89.0
4406         2010-01-06    88.0
4407         2010-01-07     NaN
4408 
4409         The index entries that did not have a value in the original data frame
4410         (for example, '2009-12-29') are by default filled with ``NaN``.
4411         If desired, we can fill in the missing values using one of several
4412         options.
4413 
4414         For example, to back-propagate the last valid value to fill the ``NaN``
4415         values, pass ``bfill`` as an argument to the ``method`` keyword.
4416 
4417         >>> df2.reindex(date_index2, method='bfill')
4418                     prices
4419         2009-12-29   100.0
4420         2009-12-30   100.0
4421         2009-12-31   100.0
4422         2010-01-01   100.0
4423         2010-01-02   101.0
4424         2010-01-03     NaN
4425         2010-01-04   100.0
4426         2010-01-05    89.0
4427         2010-01-06    88.0
4428         2010-01-07     NaN
4429 
4430         Please note that the ``NaN`` value present in the original dataframe
4431         (at index value 2010-01-03) will not be filled by any of the
4432         value propagation schemes. This is because filling while reindexing
4433         does not look at dataframe values, but only compares the original and
4434         desired indexes. If you do want to fill in the ``NaN`` values present
4435         in the original dataframe, use the ``fillna()`` method.
4436 
4437         See the :ref:`user guide <basics.reindexing>` for more.
4438         """
4439         # TODO: Decide if we care about having different examples for different
4440         # kinds
4441 
4442         # construct the args
4443         axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments(args, kwargs)
4444         method = missing.clean_reindex_fill_method(kwargs.pop("method", None))
4445         level = kwargs.pop("level", None)
4446         copy = kwargs.pop("copy", True)
4447         limit = kwargs.pop("limit", None)
4448         tolerance = kwargs.pop("tolerance", None)
4449         fill_value = kwargs.pop("fill_value", None)
4450 
4451         # Series.reindex doesn't use / need the axis kwarg
4452         # We pop and ignore it here, to make writing Series/Frame generic code
4453         # easier
4454         kwargs.pop("axis", None)
4455 
4456         if kwargs:
4457             raise TypeError(
4458                 "reindex() got an unexpected keyword "
4459                 f'argument "{list(kwargs.keys())[0]}"'
4460             )
4461 
4462         self._consolidate_inplace()
4463 
4464         # if all axes that are requested to reindex are equal, then only copy
4465         # if indicated must have index names equal here as well as values
4466         if all(
4467             self._get_axis(axis).identical(ax)
4468             for axis, ax in axes.items()
4469             if ax is not None
4470         ):
4471             if copy:
4472                 return self.copy()
4473             return self
4474 
4475         # check if we are a multi reindex
4476         if self._needs_reindex_multi(axes, method, level):
4477             return self._reindex_multi(axes, copy, fill_value)
4478 
4479         # perform the reindex on the axes
4480         return self._reindex_axes(
4481             axes, level, limit, tolerance, method, fill_value, copy
4482         ).__finalize__(self, method="reindex")
4483 
4484     def _reindex_axes(
4485         self: FrameOrSeries, axes, level, limit, tolerance, method, fill_value, copy
4486     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
4487         """Perform the reindex for all the axes."""
4488         obj = self
4489         for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS:
4490             labels = axes[a]
4491             if labels is None:
4492                 continue
4493 
4494             ax = self._get_axis(a)
4495             new_index, indexer = ax.reindex(
4496                 labels, level=level, limit=limit, tolerance=tolerance, method=method
4497             )
4498 
4499             axis = self._get_axis_number(a)
4500             obj = obj._reindex_with_indexers(
4501                 {axis: [new_index, indexer]},
4502                 fill_value=fill_value,
4503                 copy=copy,
4504                 allow_dups=False,
4505             )
4506 
4507         return obj
4508 
4509     def _needs_reindex_multi(self, axes, method, level) -> bool_t:
4510         """Check if we do need a multi reindex."""
4511         return (
4512             (com.count_not_none(*axes.values()) == self._AXIS_LEN)
4513             and method is None
4514             and level is None
4515             and not self._is_mixed_type
4516         )
4517 
4518     def _reindex_multi(self, axes, copy, fill_value):
4519         raise AbstractMethodError(self)
4520 
4521     def _reindex_with_indexers(
4522         self: FrameOrSeries,
4523         reindexers,
4524         fill_value=None,
4525         copy: bool_t = False,
4526         allow_dups: bool_t = False,
4527     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
4528         """allow_dups indicates an internal call here """
4529         # reindex doing multiple operations on different axes if indicated
4530         new_data = self._mgr
4531         for axis in sorted(reindexers.keys()):
4532             index, indexer = reindexers[axis]
4533             baxis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis)
4534 
4535             if index is None:
4536                 continue
4537 
4538             index = ensure_index(index)
4539             if indexer is not None:
4540                 indexer = ensure_int64(indexer)
4541 
4542             # TODO: speed up on homogeneous DataFrame objects
4543             new_data = new_data.reindex_indexer(
4544                 index,
4545                 indexer,
4546                 axis=baxis,
4547                 fill_value=fill_value,
4548                 allow_dups=allow_dups,
4549                 copy=copy,
4550             )
4551             # If we've made a copy once, no need to make another one
4552             copy = False
4553 
4554         if copy and new_data is self._mgr:
4555             new_data = new_data.copy()
4556 
4557         return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)
4558 
4559     def filter(
4560         self: FrameOrSeries,
4561         items=None,
4562         like: Optional[str] = None,
4563         regex: Optional[str] = None,
4564         axis=None,
4565     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
4566         """
4567         Subset the dataframe rows or columns according to the specified index labels.
4568 
4569         Note that this routine does not filter a dataframe on its
4570         contents. The filter is applied to the labels of the index.
4571 
4572         Parameters
4573         ----------
4574         items : list-like
4575             Keep labels from axis which are in items.
4576         like : str
4577             Keep labels from axis for which "like in label == True".
4578         regex : str (regular expression)
4579             Keep labels from axis for which re.search(regex, label) == True.
4580         axis : {0 or ‘index’, 1 or ‘columns’, None}, default None
4581             The axis to filter on, expressed either as an index (int)
4582             or axis name (str). By default this is the info axis,
4583             'index' for Series, 'columns' for DataFrame.
4584 
4585         Returns
4586         -------
4587         same type as input object
4588 
4589         See Also
4590         --------
4591         DataFrame.loc : Access a group of rows and columns
4592             by label(s) or a boolean array.
4593 
4594         Notes
4595         -----
4596         The ``items``, ``like``, and ``regex`` parameters are
4597         enforced to be mutually exclusive.
4598 
4599         ``axis`` defaults to the info axis that is used when indexing
4600         with ``[]``.
4601 
4602         Examples
4603         --------
4604         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.array(([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6])),
4605         ...                   index=['mouse', 'rabbit'],
4606         ...                   columns=['one', 'two', 'three'])
4607         >>> df
4608                 one  two  three
4609         mouse     1    2      3
4610         rabbit    4    5      6
4611 
4612         >>> # select columns by name
4613         >>> df.filter(items=['one', 'three'])
4614                  one  three
4615         mouse     1      3
4616         rabbit    4      6
4617 
4618         >>> # select columns by regular expression
4619         >>> df.filter(regex='e$', axis=1)
4620                  one  three
4621         mouse     1      3
4622         rabbit    4      6
4623 
4624         >>> # select rows containing 'bbi'
4625         >>> df.filter(like='bbi', axis=0)
4626                  one  two  three
4627         rabbit    4    5      6
4628         """
4629         nkw = com.count_not_none(items, like, regex)
4630         if nkw > 1:
4631             raise TypeError(
4632                 "Keyword arguments `items`, `like`, or `regex` "
4633                 "are mutually exclusive"
4634             )
4635 
4636         if axis is None:
4637             axis = self._info_axis_name
4638         labels = self._get_axis(axis)
4639 
4640         if items is not None:
4641             name = self._get_axis_name(axis)
4642             return self.reindex(**{name: [r for r in items if r in labels]})
4643         elif like:
4644 
4645             def f(x):
4646                 return like in ensure_str(x)
4647 
4648             values = labels.map(f)
4649             return self.loc(axis=axis)[values]
4650         elif regex:
4651 
4652             def f(x):
4653                 return matcher.search(ensure_str(x)) is not None
4654 
4655             matcher = re.compile(regex)
4656             values = labels.map(f)
4657             return self.loc(axis=axis)[values]
4658         else:
4659             raise TypeError("Must pass either `items`, `like`, or `regex`")
4660 
4661     def head(self: FrameOrSeries, n: int = 5) -> FrameOrSeries:
4662         """
4663         Return the first `n` rows.
4664 
4665         This function returns the first `n` rows for the object based
4666         on position. It is useful for quickly testing if your object
4667         has the right type of data in it.
4668 
4669         For negative values of `n`, this function returns all rows except
4670         the last `n` rows, equivalent to ``df[:-n]``.
4671 
4672         Parameters
4673         ----------
4674         n : int, default 5
4675             Number of rows to select.
4676 
4677         Returns
4678         -------
4679         same type as caller
4680             The first `n` rows of the caller object.
4681 
4682         See Also
4683         --------
4684         DataFrame.tail: Returns the last `n` rows.
4685 
4686         Examples
4687         --------
4688         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'animal': ['alligator', 'bee', 'falcon', 'lion',
4689         ...                    'monkey', 'parrot', 'shark', 'whale', 'zebra']})
4690         >>> df
4691               animal
4692         0  alligator
4693         1        bee
4694         2     falcon
4695         3       lion
4696         4     monkey
4697         5     parrot
4698         6      shark
4699         7      whale
4700         8      zebra
4701 
4702         Viewing the first 5 lines
4703 
4704         >>> df.head()
4705               animal
4706         0  alligator
4707         1        bee
4708         2     falcon
4709         3       lion
4710         4     monkey
4711 
4712         Viewing the first `n` lines (three in this case)
4713 
4714         >>> df.head(3)
4715               animal
4716         0  alligator
4717         1        bee
4718         2     falcon
4719 
4720         For negative values of `n`
4721 
4722         >>> df.head(-3)
4723               animal
4724         0  alligator
4725         1        bee
4726         2     falcon
4727         3       lion
4728         4     monkey
4729         5     parrot
4730         """
4731         return self.iloc[:n]
4732 
4733     def tail(self: FrameOrSeries, n: int = 5) -> FrameOrSeries:
4734         """
4735         Return the last `n` rows.
4736 
4737         This function returns last `n` rows from the object based on
4738         position. It is useful for quickly verifying data, for example,
4739         after sorting or appending rows.
4740 
4741         For negative values of `n`, this function returns all rows except
4742         the first `n` rows, equivalent to ``df[n:]``.
4743 
4744         Parameters
4745         ----------
4746         n : int, default 5
4747             Number of rows to select.
4748 
4749         Returns
4750         -------
4751         type of caller
4752             The last `n` rows of the caller object.
4753 
4754         See Also
4755         --------
4756         DataFrame.head : The first `n` rows of the caller object.
4757 
4758         Examples
4759         --------
4760         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'animal': ['alligator', 'bee', 'falcon', 'lion',
4761         ...                    'monkey', 'parrot', 'shark', 'whale', 'zebra']})
4762         >>> df
4763               animal
4764         0  alligator
4765         1        bee
4766         2     falcon
4767         3       lion
4768         4     monkey
4769         5     parrot
4770         6      shark
4771         7      whale
4772         8      zebra
4773 
4774         Viewing the last 5 lines
4775 
4776         >>> df.tail()
4777            animal
4778         4  monkey
4779         5  parrot
4780         6   shark
4781         7   whale
4782         8   zebra
4783 
4784         Viewing the last `n` lines (three in this case)
4785 
4786         >>> df.tail(3)
4787           animal
4788         6  shark
4789         7  whale
4790         8  zebra
4791 
4792         For negative values of `n`
4793 
4794         >>> df.tail(-3)
4795            animal
4796         3    lion
4797         4  monkey
4798         5  parrot
4799         6   shark
4800         7   whale
4801         8   zebra
4802         """
4803         if n == 0:
4804             return self.iloc[0:0]
4805         return self.iloc[-n:]
4806 
4807     def sample(
4808         self: FrameOrSeries,
4809         n=None,
4810         frac=None,
4811         replace=False,
4812         weights=None,
4813         random_state=None,
4814         axis=None,
4815     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
4816         """
4817         Return a random sample of items from an axis of object.
4818 
4819         You can use `random_state` for reproducibility.
4820 
4821         Parameters
4822         ----------
4823         n : int, optional
4824             Number of items from axis to return. Cannot be used with `frac`.
4825             Default = 1 if `frac` = None.
4826         frac : float, optional
4827             Fraction of axis items to return. Cannot be used with `n`.
4828         replace : bool, default False
4829             Allow or disallow sampling of the same row more than once.
4830         weights : str or ndarray-like, optional
4831             Default 'None' results in equal probability weighting.
4832             If passed a Series, will align with target object on index. Index
4833             values in weights not found in sampled object will be ignored and
4834             index values in sampled object not in weights will be assigned
4835             weights of zero.
4836             If called on a DataFrame, will accept the name of a column
4837             when axis = 0.
4838             Unless weights are a Series, weights must be same length as axis
4839             being sampled.
4840             If weights do not sum to 1, they will be normalized to sum to 1.
4841             Missing values in the weights column will be treated as zero.
4842             Infinite values not allowed.
4843         random_state : int, array-like, BitGenerator, np.random.RandomState, optional
4844             If int, array-like, or BitGenerator (NumPy>=1.17), seed for
4845             random number generator
4846             If np.random.RandomState, use as numpy RandomState object.
4847 
4848             ..versionchanged:: 1.1.0
4849 
4850                 array-like and BitGenerator (for NumPy>=1.17) object now passed to
4851                 np.random.RandomState() as seed
4852 
4853         axis : {0 or ‘index’, 1 or ‘columns’, None}, default None
4854             Axis to sample. Accepts axis number or name. Default is stat axis
4855             for given data type (0 for Series and DataFrames).
4856 
4857         Returns
4858         -------
4859         Series or DataFrame
4860             A new object of same type as caller containing `n` items randomly
4861             sampled from the caller object.
4862 
4863         See Also
4864         --------
4865         DataFrameGroupBy.sample: Generates random samples from each group of a
4866             DataFrame object.
4867         SeriesGroupBy.sample: Generates random samples from each group of a
4868             Series object.
4869         numpy.random.choice: Generates a random sample from a given 1-D numpy
4870             array.
4871 
4872         Notes
4873         -----
4874         If `frac` > 1, `replacement` should be set to `True`.
4875 
4876         Examples
4877         --------
4878         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'num_legs': [2, 4, 8, 0],
4879         ...                    'num_wings': [2, 0, 0, 0],
4880         ...                    'num_specimen_seen': [10, 2, 1, 8]},
4881         ...                   index=['falcon', 'dog', 'spider', 'fish'])
4882         >>> df
4883                 num_legs  num_wings  num_specimen_seen
4884         falcon         2          2                 10
4885         dog            4          0                  2
4886         spider         8          0                  1
4887         fish           0          0                  8
4888 
4889         Extract 3 random elements from the ``Series`` ``df['num_legs']``:
4890         Note that we use `random_state` to ensure the reproducibility of
4891         the examples.
4892 
4893         >>> df['num_legs'].sample(n=3, random_state=1)
4894         fish      0
4895         spider    8
4896         falcon    2
4897         Name: num_legs, dtype: int64
4898 
4899         A random 50% sample of the ``DataFrame`` with replacement:
4900 
4901         >>> df.sample(frac=0.5, replace=True, random_state=1)
4902               num_legs  num_wings  num_specimen_seen
4903         dog          4          0                  2
4904         fish         0          0                  8
4905 
4906         An upsample sample of the ``DataFrame`` with replacement:
4907         Note that `replace` parameter has to be `True` for `frac` parameter > 1.
4908 
4909         >>> df.sample(frac=2, replace=True, random_state=1)
4910                 num_legs  num_wings  num_specimen_seen
4911         dog            4          0                  2
4912         fish           0          0                  8
4913         falcon         2          2                 10
4914         falcon         2          2                 10
4915         fish           0          0                  8
4916         dog            4          0                  2
4917         fish           0          0                  8
4918         dog            4          0                  2
4919 
4920         Using a DataFrame column as weights. Rows with larger value in the
4921         `num_specimen_seen` column are more likely to be sampled.
4922 
4923         >>> df.sample(n=2, weights='num_specimen_seen', random_state=1)
4924                 num_legs  num_wings  num_specimen_seen
4925         falcon         2          2                 10
4926         fish           0          0                  8
4927         """
4928         if axis is None:
4929             axis = self._stat_axis_number
4930 
4931         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
4932         axis_length = self.shape[axis]
4933 
4934         # Process random_state argument
4935         rs = com.random_state(random_state)
4936 
4937         # Check weights for compliance
4938         if weights is not None:
4939 
4940             # If a series, align with frame
4941             if isinstance(weights, ABCSeries):
4942                 weights = weights.reindex(self.axes[axis])
4943 
4944             # Strings acceptable if a dataframe and axis = 0
4945             if isinstance(weights, str):
4946                 if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame):
4947                     if axis == 0:
4948                         try:
4949                             weights = self[weights]
4950                         except KeyError as err:
4951                             raise KeyError(
4952                                 "String passed to weights not a valid column"
4953                             ) from err
4954                     else:
4955                         raise ValueError(
4956                             "Strings can only be passed to "
4957                             "weights when sampling from rows on "
4958                             "a DataFrame"
4959                         )
4960                 else:
4961                     raise ValueError(
4962                         "Strings cannot be passed as weights "
4963                         "when sampling from a Series."
4964                     )
4965 
4966             weights = pd.Series(weights, dtype="float64")
4967 
4968             if len(weights) != axis_length:
4969                 raise ValueError(
4970                     "Weights and axis to be sampled must be of same length"
4971                 )
4972 
4973             if (weights == np.inf).any() or (weights == -np.inf).any():
4974                 raise ValueError("weight vector may not include `inf` values")
4975 
4976             if (weights < 0).any():
4977                 raise ValueError("weight vector many not include negative values")
4978 
4979             # If has nan, set to zero.
4980             weights = weights.fillna(0)
4981 
4982             # Renormalize if don't sum to 1
4983             if weights.sum() != 1:
4984                 if weights.sum() != 0:
4985                     weights = weights / weights.sum()
4986                 else:
4987                     raise ValueError("Invalid weights: weights sum to zero")
4988 
4989             weights = weights._values
4990 
4991         # If no frac or n, default to n=1.
4992         if n is None and frac is None:
4993             n = 1
4994         elif frac is not None and frac > 1 and not replace:
4995             raise ValueError(
4996                 "Replace has to be set to `True` when "
4997                 "upsampling the population `frac` > 1."
4998             )
4999         elif n is not None and frac is None and n % 1 != 0:
5000             raise ValueError("Only integers accepted as `n` values")
5001         elif n is None and frac is not None:
5002             n = int(round(frac * axis_length))
5003         elif n is not None and frac is not None:
5004             raise ValueError("Please enter a value for `frac` OR `n`, not both")
5005 
5006         # Check for negative sizes
5007         if n < 0:
5008             raise ValueError(
5009                 "A negative number of rows requested. Please provide positive value."
5010             )
5011 
5012         locs = rs.choice(axis_length, size=n, replace=replace, p=weights)
5013         return self.take(locs, axis=axis)
5014

5017     ] = r"""
5018         Apply func(self, \*args, \*\*kwargs).
5019 
5020         Parameters
5021         ----------
5022         func : function
5023             Function to apply to the %(klass)s.
5024             ``args``, and ``kwargs`` are passed into ``func``.
5025             Alternatively a ``(callable, data_keyword)`` tuple where
5026             ``data_keyword`` is a string indicating the keyword of
5027             ``callable`` that expects the %(klass)s.
5028         args : iterable, optional

5036

5041         Series.map : Apply a mapping correspondence on a
5042             :class:`~pandas.Series`.
5043 
5044         Notes
5045         -----
5046         Use ``.pipe`` when chaining together functions that expect
5047         Series, DataFrames or GroupBy objects. Instead of writing
5048

5050

5052

5054         ...    .pipe(g, arg1=a)
5055         ...    .pipe(func, arg2=b, arg3=c)
5056         ... )  # doctest: +SKIP
5057 
5058         If you have a function that takes the data as (say) the second
5059         argument, pass a tuple indicating which keyword expects the
5060         data. For example, suppose ``f`` takes its data as ``arg2``:
5061 
5062         >>> (df.pipe(h)
5063         ...    .pipe(g, arg1=a)
5064         ...    .pipe((func, 'arg2'), arg1=a, arg3=c)
5065         ...  )  # doctest: +SKIP
5066     """
5067 
5068     @Appender(_shared_docs["pipe"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
5069     def pipe(self, func, *args, **kwargs):
5070         return com.pipe(self, func, *args, **kwargs)
