5183     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
5184     # Attribute access
5185 
5186     def __finalize__(
5187         self: FrameOrSeries, other, method: Optional[str] = None, **kwargs
5188     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
5189         """
5190         Propagate metadata from other to self.
5191 
5192         Parameters
5193         ----------
5194         other : the object from which to get the attributes that we are going
5195             to propagate
5196         method : str, optional
5197             A passed method name providing context on where ``__finalize__``
5198             was called.
5199 
5200             .. warning:
5201 
5202                The value passed as `method` are not currently considered
5203                stable across pandas releases.
5204         """
5205         if isinstance(other, NDFrame):
5206             for name in other.attrs:
5207                 self.attrs[name] = other.attrs[name]
5208             # For subclasses using _metadata.
5209             for name in self._metadata:
5210                 assert isinstance(name, str)
5211                 object.__setattr__(self, name, getattr(other, name, None))
5212         return self
5213 
5214     def __getattr__(self, name: str):
5215         """
5216         After regular attribute access, try looking up the name
5217         This allows simpler access to columns for interactive use.
5218         """
5219         # Note: obj.x will always call obj.__getattribute__('x') prior to
5220         # calling obj.__getattr__('x').
5221         if (
5222             name in self._internal_names_set
5223             or name in self._metadata
5224             or name in self._accessors
5225         ):
5226             return object.__getattribute__(self, name)
5227         else:
5228             if self._info_axis._can_hold_identifiers_and_holds_name(name):
5229                 return self[name]
5230             return object.__getattribute__(self, name)
5231 
5232     def __setattr__(self, name: str, value) -> None:
5233         """
5234         After regular attribute access, try setting the name
5235         This allows simpler access to columns for interactive use.
5236         """
5237         # first try regular attribute access via __getattribute__, so that
5238         # e.g. ``obj.x`` and ``obj.x = 4`` will always reference/modify
5239         # the same attribute.
5240 
5241         try:
5242             object.__getattribute__(self, name)
5243             return object.__setattr__(self, name, value)
5244         except AttributeError:
5245             pass
5246 
5247         # if this fails, go on to more involved attribute setting
5248         # (note that this matches __getattr__, above).
5249         if name in self._internal_names_set:
5250             object.__setattr__(self, name, value)
5251         elif name in self._metadata:
5252             object.__setattr__(self, name, value)
5253         else:
5254             try:
5255                 existing = getattr(self, name)
5256                 if isinstance(existing, Index):
5257                     object.__setattr__(self, name, value)
5258                 elif name in self._info_axis:
5259                     self[name] = value
5260                 else:
5261                     object.__setattr__(self, name, value)
5262             except (AttributeError, TypeError):
5263                 if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) and (is_list_like(value)):
5264                     warnings.warn(
5265                         "Pandas doesn't allow columns to be "
5266                         "created via a new attribute name - see "
5267                         "https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/"
5268                         "stable/indexing.html#attribute-access",
5269                         stacklevel=2,
5270                     )
5271                 object.__setattr__(self, name, value)
5272 
5273     def _dir_additions(self):
5274         """
5275         add the string-like attributes from the info_axis.
5276         If info_axis is a MultiIndex, it's first level values are used.
5277         """
5278         additions = {
5279             c
5280             for c in self._info_axis.unique(level=0)[:100]
5281             if isinstance(c, str) and c.isidentifier()
5282         }
5283         return super()._dir_additions().union(additions)
5284 
5285     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
5286     # Consolidation of internals
5287 
5288     def _protect_consolidate(self, f):
5289         """
5290         Consolidate _mgr -- if the blocks have changed, then clear the
5291         cache
5292         """
5293         blocks_before = len(self._mgr.blocks)
5294         result = f()
5295         if len(self._mgr.blocks) != blocks_before:
5296             self._clear_item_cache()
5297         return result
5298 
5299     def _consolidate_inplace(self) -> None:
5300         """Consolidate data in place and return None"""
5301 
5302         def f():
5303             self._mgr = self._mgr.consolidate()
5304 
5305         self._protect_consolidate(f)
5306 
5307     def _consolidate(self, inplace: bool_t = False):
5308         """
5309         Compute NDFrame with "consolidated" internals (data of each dtype
5310         grouped together in a single ndarray).
5311 
5312         Parameters
5313         ----------
5314         inplace : bool, default False
5315             If False return new object, otherwise modify existing object.
5316 
5317         Returns
5318         -------
5319         consolidated : same type as caller
5320         """
5321         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
5322         if inplace:
5323             self._consolidate_inplace()
5324         else:
5325             f = lambda: self._mgr.consolidate()
5326             cons_data = self._protect_consolidate(f)
5327             return self._constructor(cons_data).__finalize__(self)
5328 
5329     @property
5330     def _is_mixed_type(self) -> bool_t:
5331         f = lambda: self._mgr.is_mixed_type
5332         return self._protect_consolidate(f)
5333 
5334     @property
5335     def _is_numeric_mixed_type(self) -> bool_t:
5336         f = lambda: self._mgr.is_numeric_mixed_type
5337         return self._protect_consolidate(f)
5338 
5339     def _check_inplace_setting(self, value) -> bool_t:
5340         """ check whether we allow in-place setting with this type of value """
5341         if self._is_mixed_type:
5342             if not self._is_numeric_mixed_type:
5343 
5344                 # allow an actual np.nan thru
5345                 if is_float(value) and np.isnan(value):
5346                     return True
5347 
5348                 raise TypeError(
5349                     "Cannot do inplace boolean setting on "
5350                     "mixed-types with a non np.nan value"
5351                 )
5352 
5353         return True
5354 
5355     def _get_numeric_data(self):
5356         return self._constructor(self._mgr.get_numeric_data()).__finalize__(self)
5357 
5358     def _get_bool_data(self):
5359         return self._constructor(self._mgr.get_bool_data()).__finalize__(self)
5360 
5361     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
5362     # Internal Interface Methods
5363 
5364     @property
5365     def values(self) -> np.ndarray:
5366         """
5367         Return a Numpy representation of the DataFrame.
5368 
5369         .. warning::
5370 
5371            We recommend using :meth:`DataFrame.to_numpy` instead.
5372 
5373         Only the values in the DataFrame will be returned, the axes labels
5374         will be removed.
5375 
5376         Returns
5377         -------
5378         numpy.ndarray
5379             The values of the DataFrame.
5380 
5381         See Also
5382         --------
5383         DataFrame.to_numpy : Recommended alternative to this method.
5384         DataFrame.index : Retrieve the index labels.
5385         DataFrame.columns : Retrieving the column names.
5386 
5387         Notes
5388         -----
5389         The dtype will be a lower-common-denominator dtype (implicit
5390         upcasting); that is to say if the dtypes (even of numeric types)
5391         are mixed, the one that accommodates all will be chosen. Use this
5392         with care if you are not dealing with the blocks.
5393 
5394         e.g. If the dtypes are float16 and float32, dtype will be upcast to
5395         float32.  If dtypes are int32 and uint8, dtype will be upcast to
5396         int32. By :func:`numpy.find_common_type` convention, mixing int64
5397         and uint64 will result in a float64 dtype.
5398 
5399         Examples
5400         --------
5401         A DataFrame where all columns are the same type (e.g., int64) results
5402         in an array of the same type.
5403 
5404         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age':    [ 3,  29],
5405         ...                    'height': [94, 170],
5406         ...                    'weight': [31, 115]})
5407         >>> df
5408            age  height  weight
5409         0    3      94      31
5410         1   29     170     115
5411         >>> df.dtypes
5412         age       int64
5413         height    int64
5414         weight    int64
5415         dtype: object
5416         >>> df.values
5417         array([[  3,  94,  31],
5418                [ 29, 170, 115]])
5419 
5420         A DataFrame with mixed type columns(e.g., str/object, int64, float32)
5421         results in an ndarray of the broadest type that accommodates these
5422         mixed types (e.g., object).
5423 
5424         >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame([('parrot',   24.0, 'second'),
5425         ...                     ('lion',     80.5, 1),
5426         ...                     ('monkey', np.nan, None)],
5427         ...                   columns=('name', 'max_speed', 'rank'))
5428         >>> df2.dtypes
5429         name          object
5430         max_speed    float64
5431         rank          object
5432         dtype: object
5433         >>> df2.values
5434         array([['parrot', 24.0, 'second'],
5435                ['lion', 80.5, 1],
5436                ['monkey', nan, None]], dtype=object)
5437         """
5438         return self._mgr.as_array(transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED)
5439 
5440     @property
5441     def _values(self) -> np.ndarray:
5442         """internal implementation"""
5443         return self.values
5444 
5445     @property
5446     def dtypes(self):
5447         """
5448         Return the dtypes in the DataFrame.
5449 
5450         This returns a Series with the data type of each column.
5451         The result's index is the original DataFrame's columns. Columns
5452         with mixed types are stored with the ``object`` dtype. See
5453         :ref:`the User Guide <basics.dtypes>` for more.
5454 
5455         Returns
5456         -------
5457         pandas.Series
5458             The data type of each column.
5459 
5460         Examples
5461         --------
5462         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'float': [1.0],
5463         ...                    'int': [1],
5464         ...                    'datetime': [pd.Timestamp('20180310')],
5465         ...                    'string': ['foo']})
5466         >>> df.dtypes
5467         float              float64
5468         int                  int64
5469         datetime    datetime64[ns]
5470         string              object
5471         dtype: object
5472         """
5473         from pandas import Series
5474 
5475         return Series(self._mgr.get_dtypes(), index=self._info_axis, dtype=np.object_)
5476 
5477     def _to_dict_of_blocks(self, copy: bool_t = True):
5478         """
5479         Return a dict of dtype -> Constructor Types that
5480         each is a homogeneous dtype.
5481 
5482         Internal ONLY
5483         """
5484         return {
5485             k: self._constructor(v).__finalize__(self)
5486             for k, v, in self._mgr.to_dict(copy=copy).items()
5487         }
5488 
5489     def astype(
5490         self: FrameOrSeries, dtype, copy: bool_t = True, errors: str = "raise"
5491     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
5492         """
5493         Cast a pandas object to a specified dtype ``dtype``.
5494 
5495         Parameters
5496         ----------
5497         dtype : data type, or dict of column name -> data type
5498             Use a numpy.dtype or Python type to cast entire pandas object to
5499             the same type. Alternatively, use {col: dtype, ...}, where col is a
5500             column label and dtype is a numpy.dtype or Python type to cast one
5501             or more of the DataFrame's columns to column-specific types.
5502         copy : bool, default True
5503             Return a copy when ``copy=True`` (be very careful setting
5504             ``copy=False`` as changes to values then may propagate to other
5505             pandas objects).
5506         errors : {'raise', 'ignore'}, default 'raise'
5507             Control raising of exceptions on invalid data for provided dtype.
5508 
5509             - ``raise`` : allow exceptions to be raised
5510             - ``ignore`` : suppress exceptions. On error return original object.
5511 
5512         Returns
5513         -------
5514         casted : same type as caller
5515 
5516         See Also
5517         --------
5518         to_datetime : Convert argument to datetime.
5519         to_timedelta : Convert argument to timedelta.
5520         to_numeric : Convert argument to a numeric type.
5521         numpy.ndarray.astype : Cast a numpy array to a specified type.
5522 
5523         Examples
5524         --------
5525         Create a DataFrame:
5526 
5527         >>> d = {'col1': [1, 2], 'col2': [3, 4]}
5528         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data=d)
5529         >>> df.dtypes
5530         col1    int64
5531         col2    int64
5532         dtype: object
5533 
5534         Cast all columns to int32:
5535 
5536         >>> df.astype('int32').dtypes
5537         col1    int32
5538         col2    int32
5539         dtype: object
5540 
5541         Cast col1 to int32 using a dictionary:
5542 
5543         >>> df.astype({'col1': 'int32'}).dtypes
5544         col1    int32
5545         col2    int64
5546         dtype: object
5547 
5548         Create a series:
5549 
5550         >>> ser = pd.Series([1, 2], dtype='int32')
5551         >>> ser
5552         0    1
5553         1    2
5554         dtype: int32
5555         >>> ser.astype('int64')
5556         0    1
5557         1    2
5558         dtype: int64
5559 
5560         Convert to categorical type:
5561 
5562         >>> ser.astype('category')
5563         0    1
5564         1    2
5565         dtype: category
5566         Categories (2, int64): [1, 2]
5567 
5568         Convert to ordered categorical type with custom ordering:
5569 
5570         >>> cat_dtype = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(
5571         ...     categories=[2, 1], ordered=True)
5572         >>> ser.astype(cat_dtype)
5573         0    1
5574         1    2
5575         dtype: category
5576         Categories (2, int64): [2 < 1]
5577 
5578         Note that using ``copy=False`` and changing data on a new
5579         pandas object may propagate changes:
5580 
5581         >>> s1 = pd.Series([1, 2])
5582         >>> s2 = s1.astype('int64', copy=False)
5583         >>> s2[0] = 10
5584         >>> s1  # note that s1[0] has changed too
5585         0    10
5586         1     2
5587         dtype: int64
5588 
5589         Create a series of dates:
5590 
5591         >>> ser_date = pd.Series(pd.date_range('20200101', periods=3))
5592         >>> ser_date
5593         0   2020-01-01
5594         1   2020-01-02
5595         2   2020-01-03
5596         dtype: datetime64[ns]
5597 
5598         Datetimes are localized to UTC first before
5599         converting to the specified timezone:
5600 
5601         >>> ser_date.astype('datetime64[ns, US/Eastern]')
5602         0   2019-12-31 19:00:00-05:00
5603         1   2020-01-01 19:00:00-05:00
5604         2   2020-01-02 19:00:00-05:00
5605         dtype: datetime64[ns, US/Eastern]
5606         """
5607         if is_dict_like(dtype):
5608             if self.ndim == 1:  # i.e. Series
5609                 if len(dtype) > 1 or self.name not in dtype:
5610                     raise KeyError(
5611                         "Only the Series name can be used for "
5612                         "the key in Series dtype mappings."
5613                     )
5614                 new_type = dtype[self.name]
5615                 return self.astype(new_type, copy, errors)
5616 
5617             for col_name in dtype.keys():
5618                 if col_name not in self:
5619                     raise KeyError(
5620                         "Only a column name can be used for the "
5621                         "key in a dtype mappings argument."
5622                     )
5623             results = []
5624             for col_name, col in self.items():
5625                 if col_name in dtype:
5626                     results.append(
5627                         col.astype(dtype=dtype[col_name], copy=copy, errors=errors)
5628                     )
5629                 else:
5630                     results.append(col.copy() if copy else col)
5631 
5632         elif is_extension_array_dtype(dtype) and self.ndim > 1:
5633             # GH 18099/22869: columnwise conversion to extension dtype
5634             # GH 24704: use iloc to handle duplicate column names
5635             results = [
5636                 self.iloc[:, i].astype(dtype, copy=copy)
5637                 for i in range(len(self.columns))
5638             ]
5639 
5640         else:
5641             # else, only a single dtype is given
5642             new_data = self._mgr.astype(dtype=dtype, copy=copy, errors=errors,)
5643             return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self, method="astype")
5644 
5645         # GH 19920: retain column metadata after concat
5646         result = pd.concat(results, axis=1, copy=False)
5647         result.columns = self.columns
5648         return result
5649 
5650     def copy(self: FrameOrSeries, deep: bool_t = True) -> FrameOrSeries:
5651         """
5652         Make a copy of this object's indices and data.
5653 
5654         When ``deep=True`` (default), a new object will be created with a
5655         copy of the calling object's data and indices. Modifications to
5656         the data or indices of the copy will not be reflected in the
5657         original object (see notes below).
5658 
5659         When ``deep=False``, a new object will be created without copying
5660         the calling object's data or index (only references to the data
5661         and index are copied). Any changes to the data of the original
5662         will be reflected in the shallow copy (and vice versa).
5663 
5664         Parameters
5665         ----------
5666         deep : bool, default True
5667             Make a deep copy, including a copy of the data and the indices.
5668             With ``deep=False`` neither the indices nor the data are copied.
5669 
5670         Returns
5671         -------
5672         copy : Series or DataFrame
5673             Object type matches caller.
5674 
5675         Notes
5676         -----
5677         When ``deep=True``, data is copied but actual Python objects
5678         will not be copied recursively, only the reference to the object.
5679         This is in contrast to `copy.deepcopy` in the Standard Library,
5680         which recursively copies object data (see examples below).
5681 
5682         While ``Index`` objects are copied when ``deep=True``, the underlying
5683         numpy array is not copied for performance reasons. Since ``Index`` is
5684         immutable, the underlying data can be safely shared and a copy
5685         is not needed.
5686 
5687         Examples
5688         --------
5689         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"])
5690         >>> s
5691         a    1
5692         b    2
5693         dtype: int64
5694 
5695         >>> s_copy = s.copy()
5696         >>> s_copy
5697         a    1
5698         b    2
5699         dtype: int64
5700 
5701         **Shallow copy versus default (deep) copy:**
5702 
5703         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"])
5704         >>> deep = s.copy()
5705         >>> shallow = s.copy(deep=False)
5706 
5707         Shallow copy shares data and index with original.
5708 
5709         >>> s is shallow
5710         False
5711         >>> s.values is shallow.values and s.index is shallow.index
5712         True
5713 
5714         Deep copy has own copy of data and index.
5715 
5716         >>> s is deep
5717         False
5718         >>> s.values is deep.values or s.index is deep.index
5719         False
5720 
5721         Updates to the data shared by shallow copy and original is reflected
5722         in both; deep copy remains unchanged.
5723 
5724         >>> s[0] = 3
5725         >>> shallow[1] = 4
5726         >>> s
5727         a    3
5728         b    4
5729         dtype: int64
5730         >>> shallow
5731         a    3
5732         b    4
5733         dtype: int64
5734         >>> deep
5735         a    1
5736         b    2
5737         dtype: int64
5738 
5739         Note that when copying an object containing Python objects, a deep copy
5740         will copy the data, but will not do so recursively. Updating a nested
5741         data object will be reflected in the deep copy.
5742 
5743         >>> s = pd.Series([[1, 2], [3, 4]])
5744         >>> deep = s.copy()
5745         >>> s[0][0] = 10
5746         >>> s
5747         0    [10, 2]
5748         1     [3, 4]
5749         dtype: object
5750         >>> deep
5751         0    [10, 2]
5752         1     [3, 4]
5753         dtype: object
5754         """
5755         data = self._mgr.copy(deep=deep)
5756         self._clear_item_cache()
5757         return self._constructor(data).__finalize__(self, method="copy")
5758 
5759     def __copy__(self: FrameOrSeries, deep: bool_t = True) -> FrameOrSeries:
5760         return self.copy(deep=deep)
5761 
5762     def __deepcopy__(self: FrameOrSeries, memo=None) -> FrameOrSeries:
5763         """
5764         Parameters
5765         ----------
5766         memo, default None
5767             Standard signature. Unused
5768         """
5769         return self.copy(deep=True)
5770 
5771     def _convert(
5772         self: FrameOrSeries,
5773         datetime: bool_t = False,
5774         numeric: bool_t = False,
5775         timedelta: bool_t = False,
5776         coerce: bool_t = False,
5777     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
5778         """
5779         Attempt to infer better dtype for object columns
5780 
5781         Parameters
5782         ----------
5783         datetime : bool, default False
5784             If True, convert to date where possible.
5785         numeric : bool, default False
5786             If True, attempt to convert to numbers (including strings), with
5787             unconvertible values becoming NaN.
5788         timedelta : bool, default False
5789             If True, convert to timedelta where possible.
5790         coerce : bool, default False
5791             If True, force conversion with unconvertible values converted to
5792             nulls (NaN or NaT).
5793 
5794         Returns
5795         -------
5796         converted : same as input object
5797         """
5798         validate_bool_kwarg(datetime, "datetime")
5799         validate_bool_kwarg(numeric, "numeric")
5800         validate_bool_kwarg(timedelta, "timedelta")
5801         validate_bool_kwarg(coerce, "coerce")
5802         return self._constructor(
5803             self._mgr.convert(
5804                 datetime=datetime,
5805                 numeric=numeric,
5806                 timedelta=timedelta,
5807                 coerce=coerce,
5808                 copy=True,
5809             )
5810         ).__finalize__(self)
5811 
5812     def infer_objects(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
5813         """
5814         Attempt to infer better dtypes for object columns.
5815 
5816         Attempts soft conversion of object-dtyped
5817         columns, leaving non-object and unconvertible
5818         columns unchanged. The inference rules are the
5819         same as during normal Series/DataFrame construction.
5820 
5821         Returns
5822         -------
5823         converted : same type as input object
5824 
5825         See Also
5826         --------
5827         to_datetime : Convert argument to datetime.
5828         to_timedelta : Convert argument to timedelta.
5829         to_numeric : Convert argument to numeric type.
5830         convert_dtypes : Convert argument to best possible dtype.
5831 
5832         Examples
5833         --------
5834         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": ["a", 1, 2, 3]})
5835         >>> df = df.iloc[1:]
5836         >>> df
5837            A
5838         1  1
5839         2  2
5840         3  3
5841 
5842         >>> df.dtypes
5843         A    object
5844         dtype: object
5845 
5846         >>> df.infer_objects().dtypes
5847         A    int64
5848         dtype: object
5849         """
5850         # numeric=False necessary to only soft convert;
5851         # python objects will still be converted to
5852         # native numpy numeric types
5853         return self._constructor(
5854             self._mgr.convert(
5855                 datetime=True, numeric=False, timedelta=True, coerce=False, copy=True
5856             )
5857         ).__finalize__(self, method="infer_objects")
5858 
5859     def convert_dtypes(
5860         self: FrameOrSeries,
5861         infer_objects: bool_t = True,
5862         convert_string: bool_t = True,
5863         convert_integer: bool_t = True,
5864         convert_boolean: bool_t = True,
5865     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
5866         """
5867         Convert columns to best possible dtypes using dtypes supporting ``pd.NA``.
5868 
5869         .. versionadded:: 1.0.0
5870 
5871         Parameters
5872         ----------
5873         infer_objects : bool, default True
5874             Whether object dtypes should be converted to the best possible types.
5875         convert_string : bool, default True
5876             Whether object dtypes should be converted to ``StringDtype()``.
5877         convert_integer : bool, default True
5878             Whether, if possible, conversion can be done to integer extension types.
5879         convert_boolean : bool, defaults True
5880             Whether object dtypes should be converted to ``BooleanDtypes()``.
5881 
5882         Returns
5883         -------
5884         Series or DataFrame
5885             Copy of input object with new dtype.
5886 
5887         See Also
5888         --------
5889         infer_objects : Infer dtypes of objects.
5890         to_datetime : Convert argument to datetime.
5891         to_timedelta : Convert argument to timedelta.
5892         to_numeric : Convert argument to a numeric type.
5893 
5894         Notes
5895         -----
5896         By default, ``convert_dtypes`` will attempt to convert a Series (or each
5897         Series in a DataFrame) to dtypes that support ``pd.NA``. By using the options
5898         ``convert_string``, ``convert_integer``, and ``convert_boolean``, it is
5899         possible to turn off individual conversions to ``StringDtype``, the integer
5900         extension types or ``BooleanDtype``, respectively.
5901 
5902         For object-dtyped columns, if ``infer_objects`` is ``True``, use the inference
5903         rules as during normal Series/DataFrame construction.  Then, if possible,
5904         convert to ``StringDtype``, ``BooleanDtype`` or an appropriate integer extension
5905         type, otherwise leave as ``object``.
5906 
5907         If the dtype is integer, convert to an appropriate integer extension type.
5908 
5909         If the dtype is numeric, and consists of all integers, convert to an
5910         appropriate integer extension type.
5911 
5912         In the future, as new dtypes are added that support ``pd.NA``, the results
5913         of this method will change to support those new dtypes.
5914 
5915         Examples
5916         --------
5917         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(
5918         ...     {
5919         ...         "a": pd.Series([1, 2, 3], dtype=np.dtype("int32")),
5920         ...         "b": pd.Series(["x", "y", "z"], dtype=np.dtype("O")),
5921         ...         "c": pd.Series([True, False, np.nan], dtype=np.dtype("O")),
5922         ...         "d": pd.Series(["h", "i", np.nan], dtype=np.dtype("O")),
5923         ...         "e": pd.Series([10, np.nan, 20], dtype=np.dtype("float")),
5924         ...         "f": pd.Series([np.nan, 100.5, 200], dtype=np.dtype("float")),
5925         ...     }
5926         ... )
5927 
5928         Start with a DataFrame with default dtypes.
5929 
5930         >>> df
5931            a  b      c    d     e      f
5932         0  1  x   True    h  10.0    NaN
5933         1  2  y  False    i   NaN  100.5
5934         2  3  z    NaN  NaN  20.0  200.0
5935 
5936         >>> df.dtypes
5937         a      int32
5938         b     object
5939         c     object
5940         d     object
5941         e    float64
5942         f    float64
5943         dtype: object
5944 
5945         Convert the DataFrame to use best possible dtypes.
5946 
5947         >>> dfn = df.convert_dtypes()
5948         >>> dfn
5949            a  b      c     d     e      f
5950         0  1  x   True     h    10    NaN
5951         1  2  y  False     i  <NA>  100.5
5952         2  3  z   <NA>  <NA>    20  200.0
5953 
5954         >>> dfn.dtypes
5955         a      Int32
5956         b     string
5957         c    boolean
5958         d     string
5959         e      Int64
5960         f    float64
5961         dtype: object
5962 
5963         Start with a Series of strings and missing data represented by ``np.nan``.
5964 
5965         >>> s = pd.Series(["a", "b", np.nan])
5966         >>> s
5967         0      a
5968         1      b
5969         2    NaN
5970         dtype: object
5971 
5972         Obtain a Series with dtype ``StringDtype``.
5973 
5974         >>> s.convert_dtypes()
5975         0       a
5976         1       b
5977         2    <NA>
5978         dtype: string
5979         """
5980         if self.ndim == 1:
5981             return self._convert_dtypes(
5982                 infer_objects, convert_string, convert_integer, convert_boolean
5983             )
5984         else:
5985             results = [
5986                 col._convert_dtypes(
5987                     infer_objects, convert_string, convert_integer, convert_boolean
5988                 )
5989                 for col_name, col in self.items()
5990             ]
5991             result = pd.concat(results, axis=1, copy=False)
5992             return result
5993 
5994     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
5995     # Filling NA's
5996 
5997     @doc(**_shared_doc_kwargs)
5998     def fillna(
5999         self: FrameOrSeries,
6000         value=None,
6001         method=None,
6002         axis=None,
6003         inplace: bool_t = False,
6004         limit=None,
6005         downcast=None,
6006     ) -> Optional[FrameOrSeries]:
6007         """
6008         Fill NA/NaN values using the specified method.
6009 
6010         Parameters
6011         ----------
6012         value : scalar, dict, Series, or DataFrame
6013             Value to use to fill holes (e.g. 0), alternately a
6014             dict/Series/DataFrame of values specifying which value to use for
6015             each index (for a Series) or column (for a DataFrame).  Values not
6016             in the dict/Series/DataFrame will not be filled. This value cannot
6017             be a list.
6018         method : {{'backfill', 'bfill', 'pad', 'ffill', None}}, default None
6019             Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series
6020             pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next valid
6021             backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap.
6022         axis : {axes_single_arg}
6023             Axis along which to fill missing values.
6024         inplace : bool, default False
6025             If True, fill in-place. Note: this will modify any
6026             other views on this object (e.g., a no-copy slice for a column in a
6027             DataFrame).
6028         limit : int, default None
6029             If method is specified, this is the maximum number of consecutive
6030             NaN values to forward/backward fill. In other words, if there is
6031             a gap with more than this number of consecutive NaNs, it will only
6032             be partially filled. If method is not specified, this is the
6033             maximum number of entries along the entire axis where NaNs will be
6034             filled. Must be greater than 0 if not None.
6035         downcast : dict, default is None
6036             A dict of item->dtype of what to downcast if possible,
6037             or the string 'infer' which will try to downcast to an appropriate
6038             equal type (e.g. float64 to int64 if possible).
6039 
6040         Returns
6041         -------
6042         {klass} or None
6043             Object with missing values filled or None if ``inplace=True``.
6044 
6045         See Also
6046         --------
6047         interpolate : Fill NaN values using interpolation.
6048         reindex : Conform object to new index.
6049         asfreq : Convert TimeSeries to specified frequency.
6050 
6051         Examples
6052         --------
6053         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[np.nan, 2, np.nan, 0],
6054         ...                    [3, 4, np.nan, 1],
6055         ...                    [np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, 5],
6056         ...                    [np.nan, 3, np.nan, 4]],
6057         ...                   columns=list('ABCD'))
6058         >>> df
6059              A    B   C  D
6060         0  NaN  2.0 NaN  0
6061         1  3.0  4.0 NaN  1
6062         2  NaN  NaN NaN  5
6063         3  NaN  3.0 NaN  4
6064 
6065         Replace all NaN elements with 0s.
6066 
6067         >>> df.fillna(0)
6068             A   B   C   D
6069         0   0.0 2.0 0.0 0
6070         1   3.0 4.0 0.0 1
6071         2   0.0 0.0 0.0 5
6072         3   0.0 3.0 0.0 4
6073 
6074         We can also propagate non-null values forward or backward.
6075 
6076         >>> df.fillna(method='ffill')
6077             A   B   C   D
6078         0   NaN 2.0 NaN 0
6079         1   3.0 4.0 NaN 1
6080         2   3.0 4.0 NaN 5
6081         3   3.0 3.0 NaN 4
6082 
6083         Replace all NaN elements in column 'A', 'B', 'C', and 'D', with 0, 1,
6084         2, and 3 respectively.
6085 
6086         >>> values = {{'A': 0, 'B': 1, 'C': 2, 'D': 3}}
6087         >>> df.fillna(value=values)
6088             A   B   C   D
6089         0   0.0 2.0 2.0 0
6090         1   3.0 4.0 2.0 1
6091         2   0.0 1.0 2.0 5
6092         3   0.0 3.0 2.0 4
6093 
6094         Only replace the first NaN element.
6095 
6096         >>> df.fillna(value=values, limit=1)
6097             A   B   C   D
6098         0   0.0 2.0 2.0 0
6099         1   3.0 4.0 NaN 1
6100         2   NaN 1.0 NaN 5
6101         3   NaN 3.0 NaN 4
6102         """
6103         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
6104         value, method = validate_fillna_kwargs(value, method)
6105 
6106         # set the default here, so functions examining the signaure
6107         # can detect if something was set (e.g. in groupby) (GH9221)
6108         if axis is None:
6109             axis = 0
6110         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
6111 
6112         if value is None:
6113 
6114             if self._is_mixed_type and axis == 1:
6115                 if inplace:
6116                     raise NotImplementedError()
6117                 result = self.T.fillna(method=method, limit=limit).T
6118 
6119                 # need to downcast here because of all of the transposes
6120                 result._mgr = result._mgr.downcast()
6121 
6122                 return result
6123 
6124             new_data = self._mgr.interpolate(
6125                 method=method,
6126                 axis=axis,
6127                 limit=limit,
6128                 inplace=inplace,
6129                 coerce=True,
6130                 downcast=downcast,
6131             )
6132         else:
6133             if self.ndim == 1:
6134                 if isinstance(value, (dict, ABCSeries)):
6135                     value = create_series_with_explicit_dtype(
6136                         value, dtype_if_empty=object
6137                     )
6138                     value = value.reindex(self.index, copy=False)
6139                     value = value._values
6140                 elif not is_list_like(value):
6141                     pass
6142                 else:
6143                     raise TypeError(
6144                         '"value" parameter must be a scalar, dict '
6145                         "or Series, but you passed a "
6146                         f'"{type(value).__name__}"'
6147                     )
6148 
6149                 new_data = self._mgr.fillna(
6150                     value=value, limit=limit, inplace=inplace, downcast=downcast
6151                 )
6152 
6153             elif isinstance(value, (dict, ABCSeries)):
6154                 if axis == 1:
6155                     raise NotImplementedError(
6156                         "Currently only can fill "
6157                         "with dict/Series column "
6158                         "by column"
6159                     )
6160 
6161                 result = self if inplace else self.copy()
6162                 for k, v in value.items():
6163                     if k not in result:
6164                         continue
6165                     obj = result[k]
6166                     obj.fillna(v, limit=limit, inplace=True, downcast=downcast)
6167                 return result if not inplace else None
6168 
6169             elif not is_list_like(value):
6170                 new_data = self._mgr.fillna(
6171                     value=value, limit=limit, inplace=inplace, downcast=downcast
6172                 )
6173             elif isinstance(value, ABCDataFrame) and self.ndim == 2:
6174                 new_data = self.where(self.notna(), value)._data
6175             else:
6176                 raise ValueError(f"invalid fill value with a {type(value)}")
6177 
6178         result = self._constructor(new_data)
6179         if inplace:
6180             return self._update_inplace(result)
6181         else:
6182             return result.__finalize__(self, method="fillna")
6183 
6184     def ffill(
6185         self: FrameOrSeries,
6186         axis=None,
6187         inplace: bool_t = False,
6188         limit=None,
6189         downcast=None,
6190     ) -> Optional[FrameOrSeries]:
6191         """
6192         Synonym for :meth:`DataFrame.fillna` with ``method='ffill'``.
6193 
6194         Returns
6195         -------
6196         %(klass)s or None
6197             Object with missing values filled or None if ``inplace=True``.
6198         """
6199         return self.fillna(
6200             method="ffill", axis=axis, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, downcast=downcast
6201         )
6202 
6203     pad = ffill
6204 
6205     def bfill(
6206         self: FrameOrSeries,
6207         axis=None,
6208         inplace: bool_t = False,
6209         limit=None,
6210         downcast=None,
6211     ) -> Optional[FrameOrSeries]:
6212         """
6213         Synonym for :meth:`DataFrame.fillna` with ``method='bfill'``.
6214 
6215         Returns
6216         -------
6217         %(klass)s or None
6218             Object with missing values filled or None if ``inplace=True``.
6219         """
6220         return self.fillna(
6221             method="bfill", axis=axis, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, downcast=downcast
6222         )
6223 
6224     backfill = bfill
6225 
6226     @doc(klass=_shared_doc_kwargs["klass"])
6227     def replace(
6228         self,
6229         to_replace=None,
6230         value=None,
6231         inplace=False,
6232         limit=None,
6233         regex=False,
6234         method="pad",
6235     ):
6236         """
6237         Replace values given in `to_replace` with `value`.
6238 
6239         Values of the {klass} are replaced with other values dynamically.
6240         This differs from updating with ``.loc`` or ``.iloc``, which require
6241         you to specify a location to update with some value.
6242 
6243         Parameters
6244         ----------
6245         to_replace : str, regex, list, dict, Series, int, float, or None
6246             How to find the values that will be replaced.
6247 
6248             * numeric, str or regex:
6249 
6250                 - numeric: numeric values equal to `to_replace` will be
6251                   replaced with `value`
6252                 - str: string exactly matching `to_replace` will be replaced
6253                   with `value`
6254                 - regex: regexs matching `to_replace` will be replaced with
6255                   `value`
6256 
6257             * list of str, regex, or numeric:
6258 
6259                 - First, if `to_replace` and `value` are both lists, they
6260                   **must** be the same length.
6261                 - Second, if ``regex=True`` then all of the strings in **both**
6262                   lists will be interpreted as regexs otherwise they will match
6263                   directly. This doesn't matter much for `value` since there
6264                   are only a few possible substitution regexes you can use.
6265                 - str, regex and numeric rules apply as above.
6266 
6267             * dict:
6268 
6269                 - Dicts can be used to specify different replacement values
6270                   for different existing values. For example,
6271                   ``{{'a': 'b', 'y': 'z'}}`` replaces the value 'a' with 'b' and
6272                   'y' with 'z'. To use a dict in this way the `value`
6273                   parameter should be `None`.
6274                 - For a DataFrame a dict can specify that different values
6275                   should be replaced in different columns. For example,
6276                   ``{{'a': 1, 'b': 'z'}}`` looks for the value 1 in column 'a'
6277                   and the value 'z' in column 'b' and replaces these values
6278                   with whatever is specified in `value`. The `value` parameter
6279                   should not be ``None`` in this case. You can treat this as a
6280                   special case of passing two lists except that you are
6281                   specifying the column to search in.
6282                 - For a DataFrame nested dictionaries, e.g.,
6283                   ``{{'a': {{'b': np.nan}}}}``, are read as follows: look in column
6284                   'a' for the value 'b' and replace it with NaN. The `value`
6285                   parameter should be ``None`` to use a nested dict in this
6286                   way. You can nest regular expressions as well. Note that
6287                   column names (the top-level dictionary keys in a nested
6288                   dictionary) **cannot** be regular expressions.
6289 
6290             * None:
6291 
6292                 - This means that the `regex` argument must be a string,
6293                   compiled regular expression, or list, dict, ndarray or
6294                   Series of such elements. If `value` is also ``None`` then
6295                   this **must** be a nested dictionary or Series.
6296 
6297             See the examples section for examples of each of these.
6298         value : scalar, dict, list, str, regex, default None
6299             Value to replace any values matching `to_replace` with.
6300             For a DataFrame a dict of values can be used to specify which
6301             value to use for each column (columns not in the dict will not be
6302             filled). Regular expressions, strings and lists or dicts of such
6303             objects are also allowed.
6304         inplace : bool, default False
6305             If True, in place. Note: this will modify any
6306             other views on this object (e.g. a column from a DataFrame).
6307             Returns the caller if this is True.
6308         limit : int, default None
6309             Maximum size gap to forward or backward fill.
6310         regex : bool or same types as `to_replace`, default False
6311             Whether to interpret `to_replace` and/or `value` as regular
6312             expressions. If this is ``True`` then `to_replace` *must* be a
6313             string. Alternatively, this could be a regular expression or a
6314             list, dict, or array of regular expressions in which case
6315             `to_replace` must be ``None``.
6316         method : {{'pad', 'ffill', 'bfill', `None`}}
6317             The method to use when for replacement, when `to_replace` is a
6318             scalar, list or tuple and `value` is ``None``.
6319 
6320             .. versionchanged:: 0.23.0
6321                 Added to DataFrame.
6322 
6323         Returns
6324         -------
6325         {klass}
6326             Object after replacement.
6327 
6328         Raises
6329         ------
6330         AssertionError
6331             * If `regex` is not a ``bool`` and `to_replace` is not
6332               ``None``.
6333 
6334         TypeError
6335             * If `to_replace` is not a scalar, array-like, ``dict``, or ``None``
6336             * If `to_replace` is a ``dict`` and `value` is not a ``list``,
6337               ``dict``, ``ndarray``, or ``Series``
6338             * If `to_replace` is ``None`` and `regex` is not compilable
6339               into a regular expression or is a list, dict, ndarray, or
6340               Series.
6341             * When replacing multiple ``bool`` or ``datetime64`` objects and
6342               the arguments to `to_replace` does not match the type of the
6343               value being replaced
6344 
6345         ValueError
6346             * If a ``list`` or an ``ndarray`` is passed to `to_replace` and
6347               `value` but they are not the same length.
6348 
6349         See Also
6350         --------
6351         {klass}.fillna : Fill NA values.
6352         {klass}.where : Replace values based on boolean condition.
6353         Series.str.replace : Simple string replacement.
6354 
6355         Notes
6356         -----
6357         * Regex substitution is performed under the hood with ``re.sub``. The
6358           rules for substitution for ``re.sub`` are the same.
6359         * Regular expressions will only substitute on strings, meaning you
6360           cannot provide, for example, a regular expression matching floating
6361           point numbers and expect the columns in your frame that have a
6362           numeric dtype to be matched. However, if those floating point
6363           numbers *are* strings, then you can do this.
6364         * This method has *a lot* of options. You are encouraged to experiment
6365           and play with this method to gain intuition about how it works.
6366         * When dict is used as the `to_replace` value, it is like
6367           key(s) in the dict are the to_replace part and
6368           value(s) in the dict are the value parameter.
6369 
6370         Examples
6371         --------
6372 
6373         **Scalar `to_replace` and `value`**
6374 
6375         >>> s = pd.Series([0, 1, 2, 3, 4])
6376         >>> s.replace(0, 5)
6377         0    5
6378         1    1
6379         2    2
6380         3    3
6381         4    4
6382         dtype: int64
6383 
6384         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({{'A': [0, 1, 2, 3, 4],
6385         ...                    'B': [5, 6, 7, 8, 9],
6386         ...                    'C': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']}})
6387         >>> df.replace(0, 5)
6388            A  B  C
6389         0  5  5  a
6390         1  1  6  b
6391         2  2  7  c
6392         3  3  8  d
6393         4  4  9  e
6394 
6395         **List-like `to_replace`**
6396 
6397         >>> df.replace([0, 1, 2, 3], 4)
6398            A  B  C
6399         0  4  5  a
6400         1  4  6  b
6401         2  4  7  c
6402         3  4  8  d
6403         4  4  9  e
6404 
6405         >>> df.replace([0, 1, 2, 3], [4, 3, 2, 1])
6406            A  B  C
6407         0  4  5  a
6408         1  3  6  b
6409         2  2  7  c
6410         3  1  8  d
6411         4  4  9  e
6412 
6413         >>> s.replace([1, 2], method='bfill')
6414         0    0
6415         1    3
6416         2    3
6417         3    3
6418         4    4
6419         dtype: int64
6420 
6421         **dict-like `to_replace`**
6422 
6423         >>> df.replace({{0: 10, 1: 100}})
6424              A  B  C
6425         0   10  5  a
6426         1  100  6  b
6427         2    2  7  c
6428         3    3  8  d
6429         4    4  9  e
6430 
6431         >>> df.replace({{'A': 0, 'B': 5}}, 100)
6432              A    B  C
6433         0  100  100  a
6434         1    1    6  b
6435         2    2    7  c
6436         3    3    8  d
6437         4    4    9  e
6438 
6439         >>> df.replace({{'A': {{0: 100, 4: 400}}}})
6440              A  B  C
6441         0  100  5  a
6442         1    1  6  b
6443         2    2  7  c
6444         3    3  8  d
6445         4  400  9  e
6446 
6447         **Regular expression `to_replace`**
6448 
6449         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({{'A': ['bat', 'foo', 'bait'],
6450         ...                    'B': ['abc', 'bar', 'xyz']}})
6451         >>> df.replace(to_replace=r'^ba.$', value='new', regex=True)
6452               A    B
6453         0   new  abc
6454         1   foo  new
6455         2  bait  xyz
6456 
6457         >>> df.replace({{'A': r'^ba.$'}}, {{'A': 'new'}}, regex=True)
6458               A    B
6459         0   new  abc
6460         1   foo  bar
6461         2  bait  xyz
6462 
6463         >>> df.replace(regex=r'^ba.$', value='new')
6464               A    B
6465         0   new  abc
6466         1   foo  new
6467         2  bait  xyz
6468 
6469         >>> df.replace(regex={{r'^ba.$': 'new', 'foo': 'xyz'}})
6470               A    B
6471         0   new  abc
6472         1   xyz  new
6473         2  bait  xyz
6474 
6475         >>> df.replace(regex=[r'^ba.$', 'foo'], value='new')
6476               A    B
6477         0   new  abc
6478         1   new  new
6479         2  bait  xyz
6480 
6481         Note that when replacing multiple ``bool`` or ``datetime64`` objects,
6482         the data types in the `to_replace` parameter must match the data
6483         type of the value being replaced:
6484 
6485         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({{'A': [True, False, True],
6486         ...                    'B': [False, True, False]}})
6487         >>> df.replace({{'a string': 'new value', True: False}})  # raises
6488         Traceback (most recent call last):
6489             ...
6490         TypeError: Cannot compare types 'ndarray(dtype=bool)' and 'str'
6491 
6492         This raises a ``TypeError`` because one of the ``dict`` keys is not of
6493         the correct type for replacement.
6494 
6495         Compare the behavior of ``s.replace({{'a': None}})`` and
6496         ``s.replace('a', None)`` to understand the peculiarities
6497         of the `to_replace` parameter:
6498 
6499         >>> s = pd.Series([10, 'a', 'a', 'b', 'a'])
6500 
6501         When one uses a dict as the `to_replace` value, it is like the
6502         value(s) in the dict are equal to the `value` parameter.
6503         ``s.replace({{'a': None}})`` is equivalent to
6504         ``s.replace(to_replace={{'a': None}}, value=None, method=None)``:
6505 
6506         >>> s.replace({{'a': None}})
6507         0      10
6508         1    None
6509         2    None
6510         3       b
6511         4    None
6512         dtype: object
6513 
6514         When ``value=None`` and `to_replace` is a scalar, list or
6515         tuple, `replace` uses the method parameter (default 'pad') to do the
6516         replacement. So this is why the 'a' values are being replaced by 10
6517         in rows 1 and 2 and 'b' in row 4 in this case.
6518         The command ``s.replace('a', None)`` is actually equivalent to
6519         ``s.replace(to_replace='a', value=None, method='pad')``:
6520 
6521         >>> s.replace('a', None)
6522         0    10
6523         1    10
6524         2    10
6525         3     b
6526         4     b
6527         dtype: object
6528     """
6529         if not (
6530             is_scalar(to_replace)
6531             or is_re_compilable(to_replace)
6532             or is_list_like(to_replace)
6533         ):
6534             raise TypeError(
6535                 "Expecting 'to_replace' to be either a scalar, array-like, "
6536                 "dict or None, got invalid type "
6537                 f"{repr(type(to_replace).__name__)}"
6538             )
6539 
6540         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
6541         if not is_bool(regex) and to_replace is not None:
6542             raise AssertionError("'to_replace' must be 'None' if 'regex' is not a bool")
6543 
6544         if value is None:
6545             # passing a single value that is scalar like
6546             # when value is None (GH5319), for compat
6547             if not is_dict_like(to_replace) and not is_dict_like(regex):
6548                 to_replace = [to_replace]
6549 
6550             if isinstance(to_replace, (tuple, list)):
6551                 if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame):
6552                     return self.apply(
6553                         _single_replace, args=(to_replace, method, inplace, limit)
6554                     )
6555                 return _single_replace(self, to_replace, method, inplace, limit)
6556 
6557             if not is_dict_like(to_replace):
6558                 if not is_dict_like(regex):
6559                     raise TypeError(
6560                         'If "to_replace" and "value" are both None '
6561                         'and "to_replace" is not a list, then '
6562                         "regex must be a mapping"
6563                     )
6564                 to_replace = regex
6565                 regex = True
6566 
6567             items = list(to_replace.items())
6568             keys, values = zip(*items) if items else ([], [])
6569 
6570             are_mappings = [is_dict_like(v) for v in values]
6571 
6572             if any(are_mappings):
6573                 if not all(are_mappings):
6574                     raise TypeError(
6575                         "If a nested mapping is passed, all values "
6576                         "of the top level mapping must be mappings"
6577                     )
6578                 # passed a nested dict/Series
6579                 to_rep_dict = {}
6580                 value_dict = {}
6581 
6582                 for k, v in items:
6583                     keys, values = list(zip(*v.items())) or ([], [])
6584 
6585                     to_rep_dict[k] = list(keys)
6586                     value_dict[k] = list(values)
6587 
6588                 to_replace, value = to_rep_dict, value_dict
6589             else:
6590                 to_replace, value = keys, values
6591 
6592             return self.replace(
6593                 to_replace, value, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, regex=regex
6594             )
6595         else:
6596 
6597             # need a non-zero len on all axes
6598             if not self.size:
6599                 return self
6600 
6601             if is_dict_like(to_replace):
6602                 if is_dict_like(value):  # {'A' : NA} -> {'A' : 0}
6603                     # Note: Checking below for `in foo.keys()` instead of
6604                     #  `in foo`is needed for when we have a Series and not dict
6605                     mapping = {
6606                         col: (to_replace[col], value[col])
6607                         for col in to_replace.keys()
6608                         if col in value.keys() and col in self
6609                     }
6610                     return self._replace_columnwise(mapping, inplace, regex)
6611 
6612                 # {'A': NA} -> 0
6613                 elif not is_list_like(value):
6614                     # Operate column-wise
6615                     if self.ndim == 1:
6616                         raise ValueError(
6617                             "Series.replace cannot use dict-like to_replace "
6618                             "and non-None value"
6619                         )
6620                     mapping = {
6621                         col: (to_rep, value) for col, to_rep in to_replace.items()
6622                     }
6623                     return self._replace_columnwise(mapping, inplace, regex)
6624                 else:
6625                     raise TypeError("value argument must be scalar, dict, or Series")
6626 
6627             elif is_list_like(to_replace):  # [NA, ''] -> [0, 'missing']
6628                 if is_list_like(value):
6629                     if len(to_replace) != len(value):
6630                         raise ValueError(
6631                             f"Replacement lists must match in length. "
6632                             f"Expecting {len(to_replace)} got {len(value)} "
6633                         )
6634 
6635                     new_data = self._mgr.replace_list(
6636                         src_list=to_replace,
6637                         dest_list=value,
6638                         inplace=inplace,
6639                         regex=regex,
6640                     )
6641 
6642                 else:  # [NA, ''] -> 0
6643                     new_data = self._mgr.replace(
6644                         to_replace=to_replace, value=value, inplace=inplace, regex=regex
6645                     )
6646             elif to_replace is None:
6647                 if not (
6648                     is_re_compilable(regex)
6649                     or is_list_like(regex)
6650                     or is_dict_like(regex)
6651                 ):
6652                     raise TypeError(
6653                         f"'regex' must be a string or a compiled regular expression "
6654                         f"or a list or dict of strings or regular expressions, "
6655                         f"you passed a {repr(type(regex).__name__)}"
6656                     )
6657                 return self.replace(
6658                     regex, value, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, regex=True
6659                 )
6660             else:
6661 
6662                 # dest iterable dict-like
6663                 if is_dict_like(value):  # NA -> {'A' : 0, 'B' : -1}
6664                     # Operate column-wise
6665                     if self.ndim == 1:
6666                         raise ValueError(
6667                             "Series.replace cannot use dict-value and "
6668                             "non-None to_replace"
6669                         )
6670                     mapping = {col: (to_replace, val) for col, val in value.items()}
6671                     return self._replace_columnwise(mapping, inplace, regex)
6672 
6673                 elif not is_list_like(value):  # NA -> 0
6674                     new_data = self._mgr.replace(
6675                         to_replace=to_replace, value=value, inplace=inplace, regex=regex
6676                     )
6677                 else:
6678                     raise TypeError(
6679                         f'Invalid "to_replace" type: {repr(type(to_replace).__name__)}'
6680                     )
6681 
6682         result = self._constructor(new_data)
6683         if inplace:
6684             return self._update_inplace(result)
6685         else:
6686             return result.__finalize__(self, method="replace")
6687 
6688     _shared_docs[
6689         "interpolate"
6690     ] = """
6691         Please note that only ``method='linear'`` is supported for
6692         DataFrame/Series with a MultiIndex.
6693 
6694         Parameters
6695         ----------
6696         method : str, default 'linear'
6697             Interpolation technique to use. One of:
6698 
6699             * 'linear': Ignore the index and treat the values as equally
6700               spaced. This is the only method supported on MultiIndexes.
6701             * 'time': Works on daily and higher resolution data to interpolate
6702               given length of interval.
6703             * 'index', 'values': use the actual numerical values of the index.
6704             * 'pad': Fill in NaNs using existing values.
6705             * 'nearest', 'zero', 'slinear', 'quadratic', 'cubic', 'spline',
6706               'barycentric', 'polynomial': Passed to
6707               `scipy.interpolate.interp1d`. These methods use the numerical
6708               values of the index.  Both 'polynomial' and 'spline' require that
6709               you also specify an `order` (int), e.g.
6710               ``df.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=5)``.
6711             * 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip', 'akima',
6712               'cubicspline': Wrappers around the SciPy interpolation methods of
6713               similar names. See `Notes`.
6714             * 'from_derivatives': Refers to
6715               `scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives` which
6716               replaces 'piecewise_polynomial' interpolation method in
6717               scipy 0.18.
6718         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None
6719             Axis to interpolate along.
6720         limit : int, optional
6721             Maximum number of consecutive NaNs to fill. Must be greater than
6722             0.
6723         inplace : bool, default False
6724             Update the data in place if possible.
6725         limit_direction : {'forward', 'backward', 'both'}, Optional
6726             Consecutive NaNs will be filled in this direction.
6727 
6728             If limit is specified:
6729                 * If 'method' is 'pad' or 'ffill', 'limit_direction' must be 'forward'.
6730                 * If 'method' is 'backfill' or 'bfill', 'limit_direction' must be
6731                   'backwards'.
6732 
6733             If 'limit' is not specified:
6734                 * If 'method' is 'backfill' or 'bfill', the default is 'backward'
6735                 * else the default is 'forward'
6736 
6737             .. versionchanged:: 1.1.0
6738                 raises ValueError if `limit_direction` is 'forward' or 'both' and
6739                     method is 'backfill' or 'bfill'.
6740                 raises ValueError if `limit_direction` is 'backward' or 'both' and
6741                     method is 'pad' or 'ffill'.
6742 
6743         limit_area : {`None`, 'inside', 'outside'}, default None
6744             If limit is specified, consecutive NaNs will be filled with this
6745             restriction.
6746 
6747             * ``None``: No fill restriction.
6748             * 'inside': Only fill NaNs surrounded by valid values
6749               (interpolate).
6750             * 'outside': Only fill NaNs outside valid values (extrapolate).
6751 
6752             .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
6753 
6754         downcast : optional, 'infer' or None, defaults to None
6755             Downcast dtypes if possible.
6756         **kwargs
6757             Keyword arguments to pass on to the interpolating function.
6758 
6759         Returns
6760         -------
6761         Series or DataFrame
6762             Returns the same object type as the caller, interpolated at
6763             some or all ``NaN`` values.
6764 
6765         See Also
6766         --------
6767         fillna : Fill missing values using different methods.
6768         scipy.interpolate.Akima1DInterpolator : Piecewise cubic polynomials
6769             (Akima interpolator).
6770         scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives : Piecewise polynomial in the
6771             Bernstein basis.
6772         scipy.interpolate.interp1d : Interpolate a 1-D function.
6773         scipy.interpolate.KroghInterpolator : Interpolate polynomial (Krogh
6774             interpolator).
6775         scipy.interpolate.PchipInterpolator : PCHIP 1-d monotonic cubic
6776             interpolation.
6777         scipy.interpolate.CubicSpline : Cubic spline data interpolator.
6778 
6779         Notes
6780         -----
6781         The 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip' and 'akima'
6782         methods are wrappers around the respective SciPy implementations of
6783         similar names. These use the actual numerical values of the index.
6784         For more information on their behavior, see the
6785         `SciPy documentation
6786         <https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/interpolate.html#univariate-interpolation>`__
6787         and `SciPy tutorial
6788         <https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/tutorial/interpolate.html>`__.
6789 
6790         Examples
6791         --------
6792         Filling in ``NaN`` in a :class:`~pandas.Series` via linear
6793         interpolation.
6794 
6795         >>> s = pd.Series([0, 1, np.nan, 3])
6796         >>> s
6797         0    0.0
6798         1    1.0
6799         2    NaN
6800         3    3.0
6801         dtype: float64
6802         >>> s.interpolate()
6803         0    0.0
6804         1    1.0
6805         2    2.0
6806         3    3.0
6807         dtype: float64
6808 
6809         Filling in ``NaN`` in a Series by padding, but filling at most two
6810         consecutive ``NaN`` at a time.
6811 
6812         >>> s = pd.Series([np.nan, "single_one", np.nan,
6813         ...                "fill_two_more", np.nan, np.nan, np.nan,
6814         ...                4.71, np.nan])
6815         >>> s
6816         0              NaN
6817         1       single_one
6818         2              NaN
6819         3    fill_two_more
6820         4              NaN
6821         5              NaN
6822         6              NaN
6823         7             4.71
6824         8              NaN
6825         dtype: object
6826         >>> s.interpolate(method='pad', limit=2)
6827         0              NaN
6828         1       single_one
6829         2       single_one
6830         3    fill_two_more
6831         4    fill_two_more
6832         5    fill_two_more
6833         6              NaN
6834         7             4.71
6835         8             4.71
6836         dtype: object
6837 
6838         Filling in ``NaN`` in a Series via polynomial interpolation or splines:
6839         Both 'polynomial' and 'spline' methods require that you also specify
6840         an ``order`` (int).
6841 
6842         >>> s = pd.Series([0, 2, np.nan, 8])
6843         >>> s.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=2)
6844         0    0.000000
6845         1    2.000000
6846         2    4.666667
6847         3    8.000000
6848         dtype: float64
6849 
6850         Fill the DataFrame forward (that is, going down) along each column
6851         using linear interpolation.
6852 
6853         Note how the last entry in column 'a' is interpolated differently,
6854         because there is no entry after it to use for interpolation.
6855         Note how the first entry in column 'b' remains ``NaN``, because there
6856         is no entry before it to use for interpolation.
6857 
6858         >>> df = pd.DataFrame([(0.0, np.nan, -1.0, 1.0),
6859         ...                    (np.nan, 2.0, np.nan, np.nan),
6860         ...                    (2.0, 3.0, np.nan, 9.0),
6861         ...                    (np.nan, 4.0, -4.0, 16.0)],
6862         ...                   columns=list('abcd'))
6863         >>> df
6864              a    b    c     d
6865         0  0.0  NaN -1.0   1.0
6866         1  NaN  2.0  NaN   NaN
6867         2  2.0  3.0  NaN   9.0
6868         3  NaN  4.0 -4.0  16.0
6869         >>> df.interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='forward', axis=0)
6870              a    b    c     d
6871         0  0.0  NaN -1.0   1.0
6872         1  1.0  2.0 -2.0   5.0
6873         2  2.0  3.0 -3.0   9.0
6874         3  2.0  4.0 -4.0  16.0
6875 
6876         Using polynomial interpolation.
6877 
6878         >>> df['d'].interpolate(method='polynomial', order=2)
6879         0     1.0
6880         1     4.0
6881         2     9.0
6882         3    16.0
6883         Name: d, dtype: float64
6884         """
6885 
6886     @Appender(_shared_docs["interpolate"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
6887     def interpolate(
6888         self: FrameOrSeries,
6889         method: str = "linear",
6890         axis: Axis = 0,
6891         limit: Optional[int] = None,
6892         inplace: bool_t = False,
6893         limit_direction: Optional[str] = None,
6894         limit_area: Optional[str] = None,
6895         downcast: Optional[str] = None,
6896         **kwargs,
6897     ) -> Optional[FrameOrSeries]:
6898         """
6899         Interpolate values according to different methods.
6900         """
6901         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
6902 
6903         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
6904 
6905         fillna_methods = ["ffill", "bfill", "pad", "backfill"]
6906         should_transpose = axis == 1 and method not in fillna_methods
6907 
6908         obj = self.T if should_transpose else self
6909 
6910         if method not in fillna_methods:
6911             axis = self._info_axis_number
6912 
6913         if isinstance(obj.index, MultiIndex) and method != "linear":
6914             raise ValueError(
6915                 "Only `method=linear` interpolation is supported on MultiIndexes."
6916             )
6917 
6918         # Set `limit_direction` depending on `method`
6919         if limit_direction is None:
6920             limit_direction = (
6921                 "backward" if method in ("backfill", "bfill") else "forward"
6922             )
6923         else:
6924             if method in ("pad", "ffill") and limit_direction != "forward":
6925                 raise ValueError(
6926                     f"`limit_direction` must be 'forward' for method `{method}`"
6927                 )
6928             if method in ("backfill", "bfill") and limit_direction != "backward":
6929                 raise ValueError(
6930                     f"`limit_direction` must be 'backward' for method `{method}`"
6931                 )
6932 
6933         if obj.ndim == 2 and np.all(obj.dtypes == np.dtype(object)):
6934             raise TypeError(
6935                 "Cannot interpolate with all object-dtype columns "
6936                 "in the DataFrame. Try setting at least one "
6937                 "column to a numeric dtype."
6938             )
6939 
6940         # create/use the index
6941         if method == "linear":
6942             # prior default
6943             index = np.arange(len(obj.index))
6944         else:
6945             index = obj.index
6946             methods = {"index", "values", "nearest", "time"}
6947             is_numeric_or_datetime = (
6948                 is_numeric_dtype(index.dtype)
6949                 or is_datetime64_any_dtype(index.dtype)
6950                 or is_timedelta64_dtype(index.dtype)
6951             )
6952             if method not in methods and not is_numeric_or_datetime:
6953                 raise ValueError(
6954                     "Index column must be numeric or datetime type when "
6955                     f"using {method} method other than linear. "
6956                     "Try setting a numeric or datetime index column before "
6957                     "interpolating."
6958                 )
6959 
6960         if isna(index).any():
6961             raise NotImplementedError(
6962                 "Interpolation with NaNs in the index "
6963                 "has not been implemented. Try filling "
6964                 "those NaNs before interpolating."
6965             )
6966         new_data = obj._mgr.interpolate(
6967             method=method,
6968             axis=axis,
6969             index=index,
6970             limit=limit,
6971             limit_direction=limit_direction,
6972             limit_area=limit_area,
6973             inplace=inplace,
6974             downcast=downcast,
6975             **kwargs,
6976         )
6977 
6978         result = self._constructor(new_data)
6979         if should_transpose:
6980             result = result.T
6981         if inplace:
6982             return self._update_inplace(result)
6983         else:
6984             return result.__finalize__(self, method="interpolate")
6985

6989     def asof(self, where, subset=None):
6990         """
6991         Return the last row(s) without any NaNs before `where`.
6992 
6993         The last row (for each element in `where`, if list) without any
6994         NaN is taken.
6995         In case of a :class:`~pandas.DataFrame`, the last row without NaN
6996         considering only the subset of columns (if not `None`)
6997 
6998         If there is no good value, NaN is returned for a Series or
6999         a Series of NaN values for a DataFrame
7000 
7001         Parameters
7002         ----------
7003         where : date or array-like of dates
7004             Date(s) before which the last row(s) are returned.
7005         subset : str or array-like of str, default `None`
7006             For DataFrame, if not `None`, only use these columns to
7007             check for NaNs.
7008 
7009         Returns
7010         -------
7011         scalar, Series, or DataFrame
7012 
7013             The return can be:
7014 
7015             * scalar : when `self` is a Series and `where` is a scalar
7016             * Series: when `self` is a Series and `where` is an array-like,
7017               or when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is a scalar
7018             * DataFrame : when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is an
7019               array-like
7020 
7021             Return scalar, Series, or DataFrame.
7022 
7023         See Also
7024         --------
7025         merge_asof : Perform an asof merge. Similar to left join.
7026 
7027         Notes
7028         -----
7029         Dates are assumed to be sorted. Raises if this is not the case.
7030 
7031         Examples
7032         --------
7033         A Series and a scalar `where`.
7034 
7035         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, np.nan, 4], index=[10, 20, 30, 40])
7036         >>> s
7037         10    1.0
7038         20    2.0
7039         30    NaN
7040         40    4.0
7041         dtype: float64
7042 
7043         >>> s.asof(20)
7044         2.0
7045 
7046         For a sequence `where`, a Series is returned. The first value is
7047         NaN, because the first element of `where` is before the first
7048         index value.
7049 
7050         >>> s.asof([5, 20])
7051         5     NaN
7052         20    2.0
7053         dtype: float64
7054 
7055         Missing values are not considered. The following is ``2.0``, not
7056         NaN, even though NaN is at the index location for ``30``.
7057 
7058         >>> s.asof(30)
7059         2.0
7060 
7061         Take all columns into consideration
7062 
7063         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'a': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50],
7064         ...                    'b': [None, None, None, None, 500]},
7065         ...                   index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:01:00',
7066         ...                                           '2018-02-27 09:02:00',
7067         ...                                           '2018-02-27 09:03:00',
7068         ...                                           '2018-02-27 09:04:00',
7069         ...                                           '2018-02-27 09:05:00']))
7070         >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30',
7071         ...                           '2018-02-27 09:04:30']))
7072                               a   b
7073         2018-02-27 09:03:30 NaN NaN
7074         2018-02-27 09:04:30 NaN NaN
7075 
7076         Take a single column into consideration
7077 
7078         >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30',
7079         ...                           '2018-02-27 09:04:30']),
7080         ...         subset=['a'])
7081                                  a   b
7082         2018-02-27 09:03:30   30.0 NaN
7083         2018-02-27 09:04:30   40.0 NaN
7084         """
7085         if isinstance(where, str):
7086             where = Timestamp(where)
7087 
7088         if not self.index.is_monotonic:
7089             raise ValueError("asof requires a sorted index")
7090 
7091         is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries)
7092         if is_series:
7093             if subset is not None:
7094                 raise ValueError("subset is not valid for Series")
7095         else:
7096             if subset is None:
7097                 subset = self.columns
7098             if not is_list_like(subset):
7099                 subset = [subset]
7100 
7101         is_list = is_list_like(where)
7102         if not is_list:
7103             start = self.index[0]
7104             if isinstance(self.index, PeriodIndex):
7105                 where = Period(where, freq=self.index.freq)
7106 
7107             if where < start:
7108                 if not is_series:
7109                     return self._constructor_sliced(
7110                         index=self.columns, name=where, dtype=np.float64
7111                     )
7112                 return np.nan
7113 
7114             # It's always much faster to use a *while* loop here for
7115             # Series than pre-computing all the NAs. However a
7116             # *while* loop is extremely expensive for DataFrame
7117             # so we later pre-compute all the NAs and use the same
7118             # code path whether *where* is a scalar or list.
7119             # See PR: https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/14476
7120             if is_series:
7121                 loc = self.index.searchsorted(where, side="right")
7122                 if loc > 0:
7123                     loc -= 1
7124 
7125                 values = self._values
7126                 while loc > 0 and isna(values[loc]):
7127                     loc -= 1
7128                 return values[loc]
7129 
7130         if not isinstance(where, Index):
7131             where = Index(where) if is_list else Index([where])
7132 
7133         nulls = self.isna() if is_series else self[subset].isna().any(1)
7134         if nulls.all():
7135             if is_series:
7136                 return self._constructor(np.nan, index=where, name=self.name)
7137             elif is_list:
7138                 return self._constructor(np.nan, index=where, columns=self.columns)
7139             else:
7140                 return self._constructor_sliced(
7141                     np.nan, index=self.columns, name=where[0]
7142                 )
7143 
7144         locs = self.index.asof_locs(where, ~(nulls._values))
7145 
7146         # mask the missing
7147         missing = locs == -1
7148         data = self.take(locs)
7149         data.index = where
7150         data.loc[missing] = np.nan
7151         return data if is_list else data.iloc[-1]
7152
