7156     _shared_docs[
7157         "isna"
7158     ] = """
7159         Detect missing values.
7160 
7161         Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are NA.
7162         NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, gets mapped to True
7163         values.
7164         Everything else gets mapped to False values. Characters such as empty
7165         strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values
7166         (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``).
7167 
7168         Returns
7169         -------
7170         %(klass)s
7171             Mask of bool values for each element in %(klass)s that
7172             indicates whether an element is not an NA value.
7173 
7174         See Also
7175         --------
7176         %(klass)s.isnull : Alias of isna.
7177         %(klass)s.notna : Boolean inverse of isna.
7178         %(klass)s.dropna : Omit axes labels with missing values.
7179         isna : Top-level isna.
7180 
7181         Examples
7182         --------
7183         Show which entries in a DataFrame are NA.
7184 
7185         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age': [5, 6, np.NaN],
7186         ...                    'born': [pd.NaT, pd.Timestamp('1939-05-27'),
7187         ...                             pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25')],
7188         ...                    'name': ['Alfred', 'Batman', ''],
7189         ...                    'toy': [None, 'Batmobile', 'Joker']})
7190         >>> df
7191            age       born    name        toy
7192         0  5.0        NaT  Alfred       None
7193         1  6.0 1939-05-27  Batman  Batmobile
7194         2  NaN 1940-04-25              Joker
7195 
7196         >>> df.isna()
7197              age   born   name    toy
7198         0  False   True  False   True
7199         1  False  False  False  False
7200         2   True  False  False  False
7201 
7202         Show which entries in a Series are NA.
7203 
7204         >>> ser = pd.Series([5, 6, np.NaN])
7205         >>> ser
7206         0    5.0
7207         1    6.0
7208         2    NaN
7209         dtype: float64
7210 
7211         >>> ser.isna()
7212         0    False
7213         1    False
7214         2     True
7215         dtype: bool
7216         """
7217 
7218     @Appender(_shared_docs["isna"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
7219     def isna(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
7220         return isna(self).__finalize__(self, method="isna")
7221 
7222     @Appender(_shared_docs["isna"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
7223     def isnull(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
7224         return isna(self).__finalize__(self, method="isnull")
7225 
7226     _shared_docs[
7227         "notna"
7228     ] = """
7229         Detect existing (non-missing) values.
7230 
7231         Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are not NA.
7232         Non-missing values get mapped to True. Characters such as empty
7233         strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values
7234         (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``).
7235         NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, get mapped to False
7236         values.
7237 
7238         Returns
7239         -------
7240         %(klass)s
7241             Mask of bool values for each element in %(klass)s that
7242             indicates whether an element is not an NA value.
7243 
7244         See Also
7245         --------
7246         %(klass)s.notnull : Alias of notna.
7247         %(klass)s.isna : Boolean inverse of notna.
7248         %(klass)s.dropna : Omit axes labels with missing values.
7249         notna : Top-level notna.
7250 
7251         Examples
7252         --------
7253         Show which entries in a DataFrame are not NA.
7254 
7255         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age': [5, 6, np.NaN],
7256         ...                    'born': [pd.NaT, pd.Timestamp('1939-05-27'),
7257         ...                             pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25')],
7258         ...                    'name': ['Alfred', 'Batman', ''],
7259         ...                    'toy': [None, 'Batmobile', 'Joker']})
7260         >>> df
7261            age       born    name        toy
7262         0  5.0        NaT  Alfred       None
7263         1  6.0 1939-05-27  Batman  Batmobile
7264         2  NaN 1940-04-25              Joker
7265 
7266         >>> df.notna()
7267              age   born  name    toy
7268         0   True  False  True  False
7269         1   True   True  True   True
7270         2  False   True  True   True
7271 
7272         Show which entries in a Series are not NA.
7273 
7274         >>> ser = pd.Series([5, 6, np.NaN])
7275         >>> ser
7276         0    5.0
7277         1    6.0
7278         2    NaN
7279         dtype: float64
7280 
7281         >>> ser.notna()
7282         0     True
7283         1     True
7284         2    False
7285         dtype: bool
7286         """
7287 
7288     @Appender(_shared_docs["notna"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
7289     def notna(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
7290         return notna(self).__finalize__(self, method="notna")
7291 
7292     @Appender(_shared_docs["notna"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
7293     def notnull(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
7294         return notna(self).__finalize__(self, method="notnull")
7295 
7296     def _clip_with_scalar(self, lower, upper, inplace: bool_t = False):
7297         if (lower is not None and np.any(isna(lower))) or (
7298             upper is not None and np.any(isna(upper))
7299         ):
7300             raise ValueError("Cannot use an NA value as a clip threshold")
7301 
7302         result = self
7303         mask = isna(self._values)
7304 
7305         with np.errstate(all="ignore"):
7306             if upper is not None:
7307                 subset = self.to_numpy() <= upper
7308                 result = result.where(subset, upper, axis=None, inplace=False)
7309             if lower is not None:
7310                 subset = self.to_numpy() >= lower
7311                 result = result.where(subset, lower, axis=None, inplace=False)
7312 
7313         if np.any(mask):
7314             result[mask] = np.nan
7315 
7316         if inplace:
7317             return self._update_inplace(result)
7318         else:
7319             return result
7320 
7321     def _clip_with_one_bound(self, threshold, method, axis, inplace):
7322 
7323         if axis is not None:
7324             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
7325 
7326         # method is self.le for upper bound and self.ge for lower bound
7327         if is_scalar(threshold) and is_number(threshold):
7328             if method.__name__ == "le":
7329                 return self._clip_with_scalar(None, threshold, inplace=inplace)
7330             return self._clip_with_scalar(threshold, None, inplace=inplace)
7331 
7332         subset = method(threshold, axis=axis) | isna(self)
7333 
7334         # GH #15390
7335         # In order for where method to work, the threshold must
7336         # be transformed to NDFrame from other array like structure.
7337         if (not isinstance(threshold, ABCSeries)) and is_list_like(threshold):
7338             if isinstance(self, ABCSeries):
7339                 threshold = self._constructor(threshold, index=self.index)
7340             else:
7341                 threshold = _align_method_FRAME(self, threshold, axis, flex=None)[1]
7342         return self.where(subset, threshold, axis=axis, inplace=inplace)
7343 
7344     def clip(
7345         self: FrameOrSeries,
7346         lower=None,
7347         upper=None,
7348         axis=None,
7349         inplace: bool_t = False,
7350         *args,
7351         **kwargs,
7352     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
7353         """
7354         Trim values at input threshold(s).
7355 
7356         Assigns values outside boundary to boundary values. Thresholds
7357         can be singular values or array like, and in the latter case
7358         the clipping is performed element-wise in the specified axis.
7359 
7360         Parameters
7361         ----------
7362         lower : float or array_like, default None
7363             Minimum threshold value. All values below this
7364             threshold will be set to it.
7365         upper : float or array_like, default None
7366             Maximum threshold value. All values above this
7367             threshold will be set to it.
7368         axis : int or str axis name, optional
7369             Align object with lower and upper along the given axis.
7370         inplace : bool, default False
7371             Whether to perform the operation in place on the data.
7372         *args, **kwargs
7373             Additional keywords have no effect but might be accepted
7374             for compatibility with numpy.
7375 
7376         Returns
7377         -------
7378         Series or DataFrame
7379             Same type as calling object with the values outside the
7380             clip boundaries replaced.
7381 
7382         See Also
7383         --------
7384         Series.clip : Trim values at input threshold in series.
7385         DataFrame.clip : Trim values at input threshold in dataframe.
7386         numpy.clip : Clip (limit) the values in an array.
7387 
7388         Examples
7389         --------
7390         >>> data = {'col_0': [9, -3, 0, -1, 5], 'col_1': [-2, -7, 6, 8, -5]}
7391         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data)
7392         >>> df
7393            col_0  col_1
7394         0      9     -2
7395         1     -3     -7
7396         2      0      6
7397         3     -1      8
7398         4      5     -5
7399 
7400         Clips per column using lower and upper thresholds:
7401 
7402         >>> df.clip(-4, 6)
7403            col_0  col_1
7404         0      6     -2
7405         1     -3     -4
7406         2      0      6
7407         3     -1      6
7408         4      5     -4
7409 
7410         Clips using specific lower and upper thresholds per column element:
7411 
7412         >>> t = pd.Series([2, -4, -1, 6, 3])
7413         >>> t
7414         0    2
7415         1   -4
7416         2   -1
7417         3    6
7418         4    3
7419         dtype: int64
7420 
7421         >>> df.clip(t, t + 4, axis=0)
7422            col_0  col_1
7423         0      6      2
7424         1     -3     -4
7425         2      0      3
7426         3      6      8
7427         4      5      3
7428         """
7429         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
7430 
7431         axis = nv.validate_clip_with_axis(axis, args, kwargs)
7432         if axis is not None:
7433             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
7434 
7435         # GH 17276
7436         # numpy doesn't like NaN as a clip value
7437         # so ignore
7438         # GH 19992
7439         # numpy doesn't drop a list-like bound containing NaN
7440         if not is_list_like(lower) and np.any(isna(lower)):
7441             lower = None
7442         if not is_list_like(upper) and np.any(isna(upper)):
7443             upper = None
7444 
7445         # GH 2747 (arguments were reversed)
7446         if lower is not None and upper is not None:
7447             if is_scalar(lower) and is_scalar(upper):
7448                 lower, upper = min(lower, upper), max(lower, upper)
7449 
7450         # fast-path for scalars
7451         if (lower is None or (is_scalar(lower) and is_number(lower))) and (
7452             upper is None or (is_scalar(upper) and is_number(upper))
7453         ):
7454             return self._clip_with_scalar(lower, upper, inplace=inplace)
7455 
7456         result = self
7457         if lower is not None:
7458             result = result._clip_with_one_bound(
7459                 lower, method=self.ge, axis=axis, inplace=inplace
7460             )
7461         if upper is not None:
7462             if inplace:
7463                 result = self
7464             result = result._clip_with_one_bound(
7465                 upper, method=self.le, axis=axis, inplace=inplace
7466             )
7467 
7468         return result
7469 
7470     _shared_docs[
7471         "groupby"
7472     ] = """
7473         Group %(klass)s using a mapper or by a Series of columns.
7474 
7475         A groupby operation involves some combination of splitting the
7476         object, applying a function, and combining the results. This can be
7477         used to group large amounts of data and compute operations on these
7478         groups.
7479 
7480         Parameters
7481         ----------
7482         by : mapping, function, label, or list of labels
7483             Used to determine the groups for the groupby.
7484             If ``by`` is a function, it's called on each value of the object's
7485             index. If a dict or Series is passed, the Series or dict VALUES
7486             will be used to determine the groups (the Series' values are first
7487             aligned; see ``.align()`` method). If an ndarray is passed, the
7488             values are used as-is determine the groups. A label or list of
7489             labels may be passed to group by the columns in ``self``. Notice
7490             that a tuple is interpreted as a (single) key.
7491         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
7492             Split along rows (0) or columns (1).
7493         level : int, level name, or sequence of such, default None
7494             If the axis is a MultiIndex (hierarchical), group by a particular
7495             level or levels.
7496         as_index : bool, default True
7497             For aggregated output, return object with group labels as the
7498             index. Only relevant for DataFrame input. as_index=False is
7499             effectively "SQL-style" grouped output.
7500         sort : bool, default True
7501             Sort group keys. Get better performance by turning this off.
7502             Note this does not influence the order of observations within each
7503             group. Groupby preserves the order of rows within each group.
7504         group_keys : bool, default True
7505             When calling apply, add group keys to index to identify pieces.
7506         squeeze : bool, default False
7507             Reduce the dimensionality of the return type if possible,
7508             otherwise return a consistent type.
7509 
7510             .. deprecated:: 1.1.0
7511 
7512         observed : bool, default False
7513             This only applies if any of the groupers are Categoricals.
7514             If True: only show observed values for categorical groupers.
7515             If False: show all values for categorical groupers.
7516 
7517             .. versionadded:: 0.23.0
7518         dropna : bool, default True
7519             If True, and if group keys contain NA values, NA values together
7520             with row/column will be dropped.
7521             If False, NA values will also be treated as the key in groups
7522 
7523             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
7524 
7525         Returns
7526         -------
7527         %(klass)sGroupBy
7528             Returns a groupby object that contains information about the groups.
7529 
7530         See Also
7531         --------
7532         resample : Convenience method for frequency conversion and resampling
7533             of time series.
7534 
7535         Notes
7536         -----
7537         See the `user guide
7538         <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/groupby.html>`_ for more.
7539         """

7541     def asfreq(
7542         self: FrameOrSeries,
7543         freq,
7544         method=None,
7545         how: Optional[str] = None,
7546         normalize: bool_t = False,
7547         fill_value=None,
7548     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
7549         """
7550         Convert TimeSeries to specified frequency.
7551 
7552         Optionally provide filling method to pad/backfill missing values.
7553 
7554         Returns the original data conformed to a new index with the specified
7555         frequency. ``resample`` is more appropriate if an operation, such as
7556         summarization, is necessary to represent the data at the new frequency.
7557 
7558         Parameters
7559         ----------
7560         freq : DateOffset or str
7561             Frequency DateOffset or string.
7562         method : {'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill'}, default None
7563             Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series (note this
7564             does not fill NaNs that already were present):
7565 
7566             * 'pad' / 'ffill': propagate last valid observation forward to next
7567               valid
7568             * 'backfill' / 'bfill': use NEXT valid observation to fill.
7569         how : {'start', 'end'}, default end
7570             For PeriodIndex only (see PeriodIndex.asfreq).
7571         normalize : bool, default False
7572             Whether to reset output index to midnight.
7573         fill_value : scalar, optional
7574             Value to use for missing values, applied during upsampling (note
7575             this does not fill NaNs that already were present).
7576 
7577         Returns
7578         -------
7579         Same type as caller
7580             Object converted to the specified frequency.
7581 
7582         See Also
7583         --------
7584         reindex : Conform DataFrame to new index with optional filling logic.
7585 
7586         Notes
7587         -----
7588         To learn more about the frequency strings, please see `this link
7589         <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/timeseries.html#offset-aliases>`__.
7590 
7591         Examples
7592         --------
7593         Start by creating a series with 4 one minute timestamps.
7594 
7595         >>> index = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=4, freq='T')
7596         >>> series = pd.Series([0.0, None, 2.0, 3.0], index=index)
7597         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'s':series})
7598         >>> df
7599                                s
7600         2000-01-01 00:00:00    0.0
7601         2000-01-01 00:01:00    NaN
7602         2000-01-01 00:02:00    2.0
7603         2000-01-01 00:03:00    3.0
7604 
7605         Upsample the series into 30 second bins.
7606 
7607         >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S')
7608                                s
7609         2000-01-01 00:00:00    0.0
7610         2000-01-01 00:00:30    NaN
7611         2000-01-01 00:01:00    NaN
7612         2000-01-01 00:01:30    NaN
7613         2000-01-01 00:02:00    2.0
7614         2000-01-01 00:02:30    NaN
7615         2000-01-01 00:03:00    3.0
7616 
7617         Upsample again, providing a ``fill value``.
7618 
7619         >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S', fill_value=9.0)
7620                                s
7621         2000-01-01 00:00:00    0.0
7622         2000-01-01 00:00:30    9.0
7623         2000-01-01 00:01:00    NaN
7624         2000-01-01 00:01:30    9.0
7625         2000-01-01 00:02:00    2.0
7626         2000-01-01 00:02:30    9.0
7627         2000-01-01 00:03:00    3.0
7628 
7629         Upsample again, providing a ``method``.
7630 
7631         >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S', method='bfill')
7632                                s
7633         2000-01-01 00:00:00    0.0
7634         2000-01-01 00:00:30    NaN
7635         2000-01-01 00:01:00    NaN
7636         2000-01-01 00:01:30    2.0
7637         2000-01-01 00:02:00    2.0
7638         2000-01-01 00:02:30    3.0
7639         2000-01-01 00:03:00    3.0
7640         """
7641         from pandas.core.resample import asfreq
7642 
7643         return asfreq(
7644             self,
7645             freq,
7646             method=method,
7647             how=how,
7648             normalize=normalize,
7649             fill_value=fill_value,
7650         )
7651 
7652     def at_time(
7653         self: FrameOrSeries, time, asof: bool_t = False, axis=None
7654     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
7655         """
7656         Select values at particular time of day (e.g., 9:30AM).
7657 
7658         Parameters
7659         ----------
7660         time : datetime.time or str
7661         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
7662 
7663             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
7664 
7665         Returns
7666         -------
7667         Series or DataFrame
7668 
7669         Raises
7670         ------
7671         TypeError
7672             If the index is not  a :class:`DatetimeIndex`
7673 
7674         See Also
7675         --------
7676         between_time : Select values between particular times of the day.
7677         first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset.
7678         last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset.
7679         DatetimeIndex.indexer_at_time : Get just the index locations for
7680             values at particular time of the day.
7681 
7682         Examples
7683         --------
7684         >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='12H')
7685         >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4]}, index=i)
7686         >>> ts
7687                              A
7688         2018-04-09 00:00:00  1
7689         2018-04-09 12:00:00  2
7690         2018-04-10 00:00:00  3
7691         2018-04-10 12:00:00  4
7692 
7693         >>> ts.at_time('12:00')
7694                              A
7695         2018-04-09 12:00:00  2
7696         2018-04-10 12:00:00  4
7697         """
7698         if axis is None:
7699             axis = self._stat_axis_number
7700         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
7701 
7702         index = self._get_axis(axis)
7703 
7704         if not isinstance(index, DatetimeIndex):
7705             raise TypeError("Index must be DatetimeIndex")
7706 
7707         indexer = index.indexer_at_time(time, asof=asof)
7708         return self._take_with_is_copy(indexer, axis=axis)
7709 
7710     def between_time(
7711         self: FrameOrSeries,
7712         start_time,
7713         end_time,
7714         include_start: bool_t = True,
7715         include_end: bool_t = True,
7716         axis=None,
7717     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
7718         """
7719         Select values between particular times of the day (e.g., 9:00-9:30 AM).
7720 
7721         By setting ``start_time`` to be later than ``end_time``,
7722         you can get the times that are *not* between the two times.
7723 
7724         Parameters
7725         ----------
7726         start_time : datetime.time or str
7727             Initial time as a time filter limit.
7728         end_time : datetime.time or str
7729             End time as a time filter limit.
7730         include_start : bool, default True
7731             Whether the start time needs to be included in the result.
7732         include_end : bool, default True
7733             Whether the end time needs to be included in the result.
7734         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
7735             Determine range time on index or columns value.
7736 
7737             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
7738 
7739         Returns
7740         -------
7741         Series or DataFrame
7742             Data from the original object filtered to the specified dates range.
7743 
7744         Raises
7745         ------
7746         TypeError
7747             If the index is not  a :class:`DatetimeIndex`
7748 
7749         See Also
7750         --------
7751         at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day.
7752         first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset.
7753         last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset.
7754         DatetimeIndex.indexer_between_time : Get just the index locations for
7755             values between particular times of the day.
7756 
7757         Examples
7758         --------
7759         >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='1D20min')
7760         >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4]}, index=i)
7761         >>> ts
7762                              A
7763         2018-04-09 00:00:00  1
7764         2018-04-10 00:20:00  2
7765         2018-04-11 00:40:00  3
7766         2018-04-12 01:00:00  4
7767 
7768         >>> ts.between_time('0:15', '0:45')
7769                              A
7770         2018-04-10 00:20:00  2
7771         2018-04-11 00:40:00  3
7772 
7773         You get the times that are *not* between two times by setting
7774         ``start_time`` later than ``end_time``:
7775 
7776         >>> ts.between_time('0:45', '0:15')
7777                              A
7778         2018-04-09 00:00:00  1
7779         2018-04-12 01:00:00  4
7780         """
7781         if axis is None:
7782             axis = self._stat_axis_number
7783         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
7784 
7785         index = self._get_axis(axis)
7786         if not isinstance(index, DatetimeIndex):
7787             raise TypeError("Index must be DatetimeIndex")
7788 
7789         indexer = index.indexer_between_time(
7790             start_time, end_time, include_start=include_start, include_end=include_end,
7791         )
7792         return self._take_with_is_copy(indexer, axis=axis)
7793 
7794     def resample(
7795         self,
7796         rule,
7797         axis=0,
7798         closed: Optional[str] = None,
7799         label: Optional[str] = None,
7800         convention: str = "start",
7801         kind: Optional[str] = None,
7802         loffset=None,
7803         base: Optional[int] = None,
7804         on=None,
7805         level=None,
7806         origin: Union[str, TimestampConvertibleTypes] = "start_day",
7807         offset: Optional[TimedeltaConvertibleTypes] = None,
7808     ) -> "Resampler":
7809         """
7810         Resample time-series data.
7811 
7812         Convenience method for frequency conversion and resampling of time
7813         series. Object must have a datetime-like index (`DatetimeIndex`,
7814         `PeriodIndex`, or `TimedeltaIndex`), or pass datetime-like values
7815         to the `on` or `level` keyword.
7816 
7817         Parameters
7818         ----------
7819         rule : DateOffset, Timedelta or str
7820             The offset string or object representing target conversion.
7821         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
7822             Which axis to use for up- or down-sampling. For `Series` this
7823             will default to 0, i.e. along the rows. Must be
7824             `DatetimeIndex`, `TimedeltaIndex` or `PeriodIndex`.
7825         closed : {'right', 'left'}, default None
7826             Which side of bin interval is closed. The default is 'left'
7827             for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM',
7828             'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'.
7829         label : {'right', 'left'}, default None
7830             Which bin edge label to label bucket with. The default is 'left'
7831             for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM',
7832             'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'.
7833         convention : {'start', 'end', 's', 'e'}, default 'start'
7834             For `PeriodIndex` only, controls whether to use the start or
7835             end of `rule`.
7836         kind : {'timestamp', 'period'}, optional, default None
7837             Pass 'timestamp' to convert the resulting index to a
7838             `DateTimeIndex` or 'period' to convert it to a `PeriodIndex`.
7839             By default the input representation is retained.
7840         loffset : timedelta, default None
7841             Adjust the resampled time labels.
7842 
7843             .. deprecated:: 1.1.0
7844                 You should add the loffset to the `df.index` after the resample.
7845                 See below.
7846 
7847         base : int, default 0
7848             For frequencies that evenly subdivide 1 day, the "origin" of the
7849             aggregated intervals. For example, for '5min' frequency, base could
7850             range from 0 through 4. Defaults to 0.
7851 
7852             .. deprecated:: 1.1.0
7853                 The new arguments that you should use are 'offset' or 'origin'.
7854 
7855         on : str, optional
7856             For a DataFrame, column to use instead of index for resampling.
7857             Column must be datetime-like.
7858         level : str or int, optional
7859             For a MultiIndex, level (name or number) to use for
7860             resampling. `level` must be datetime-like.
7861         origin : {'epoch', 'start', 'start_day'}, Timestamp or str, default 'start_day'
7862             The timestamp on which to adjust the grouping. The timezone of origin
7863             must match the timezone of the index.
7864             If a timestamp is not used, these values are also supported:
7865 
7866             - 'epoch': `origin` is 1970-01-01
7867             - 'start': `origin` is the first value of the timeseries
7868             - 'start_day': `origin` is the first day at midnight of the timeseries
7869 
7870             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
7871 
7872         offset : Timedelta or str, default is None
7873             An offset timedelta added to the origin.
7874 
7875             .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
7876 
7877         Returns
7878         -------
7879         Resampler object
7880 
7881         See Also
7882         --------
7883         groupby : Group by mapping, function, label, or list of labels.
7884         Series.resample : Resample a Series.
7885         DataFrame.resample: Resample a DataFrame.
7886 
7887         Notes
7888         -----
7889         See the `user guide
7890         <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/timeseries.html#resampling>`_
7891         for more.
7892 
7893         To learn more about the offset strings, please see `this link
7894         <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/timeseries.html#dateoffset-objects>`__.
7895 
7896         Examples
7897         --------
7898         Start by creating a series with 9 one minute timestamps.
7899 
7900         >>> index = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=9, freq='T')
7901         >>> series = pd.Series(range(9), index=index)
7902         >>> series
7903         2000-01-01 00:00:00    0
7904         2000-01-01 00:01:00    1
7905         2000-01-01 00:02:00    2
7906         2000-01-01 00:03:00    3
7907         2000-01-01 00:04:00    4
7908         2000-01-01 00:05:00    5
7909         2000-01-01 00:06:00    6
7910         2000-01-01 00:07:00    7
7911         2000-01-01 00:08:00    8
7912         Freq: T, dtype: int64
7913 
7914         Downsample the series into 3 minute bins and sum the values
7915         of the timestamps falling into a bin.
7916 
7917         >>> series.resample('3T').sum()
7918         2000-01-01 00:00:00     3
7919         2000-01-01 00:03:00    12
7920         2000-01-01 00:06:00    21
7921         Freq: 3T, dtype: int64
7922 
7923         Downsample the series into 3 minute bins as above, but label each
7924         bin using the right edge instead of the left. Please note that the
7925         value in the bucket used as the label is not included in the bucket,
7926         which it labels. For example, in the original series the
7927         bucket ``2000-01-01 00:03:00`` contains the value 3, but the summed
7928         value in the resampled bucket with the label ``2000-01-01 00:03:00``
7929         does not include 3 (if it did, the summed value would be 6, not 3).
7930         To include this value close the right side of the bin interval as
7931         illustrated in the example below this one.
7932 
7933         >>> series.resample('3T', label='right').sum()
7934         2000-01-01 00:03:00     3
7935         2000-01-01 00:06:00    12
7936         2000-01-01 00:09:00    21
7937         Freq: 3T, dtype: int64
7938 
7939         Downsample the series into 3 minute bins as above, but close the right
7940         side of the bin interval.
7941 
7942         >>> series.resample('3T', label='right', closed='right').sum()
7943         2000-01-01 00:00:00     0
7944         2000-01-01 00:03:00     6
7945         2000-01-01 00:06:00    15
7946         2000-01-01 00:09:00    15
7947         Freq: 3T, dtype: int64
7948 
7949         Upsample the series into 30 second bins.
7950 
7951         >>> series.resample('30S').asfreq()[0:5]   # Select first 5 rows
7952         2000-01-01 00:00:00   0.0
7953         2000-01-01 00:00:30   NaN
7954         2000-01-01 00:01:00   1.0
7955         2000-01-01 00:01:30   NaN
7956         2000-01-01 00:02:00   2.0
7957         Freq: 30S, dtype: float64
7958 
7959         Upsample the series into 30 second bins and fill the ``NaN``
7960         values using the ``pad`` method.
7961 
7962         >>> series.resample('30S').pad()[0:5]
7963         2000-01-01 00:00:00    0
7964         2000-01-01 00:00:30    0
7965         2000-01-01 00:01:00    1
7966         2000-01-01 00:01:30    1
7967         2000-01-01 00:02:00    2
7968         Freq: 30S, dtype: int64
7969 
7970         Upsample the series into 30 second bins and fill the
7971         ``NaN`` values using the ``bfill`` method.
7972 
7973         >>> series.resample('30S').bfill()[0:5]
7974         2000-01-01 00:00:00    0
7975         2000-01-01 00:00:30    1
7976         2000-01-01 00:01:00    1
7977         2000-01-01 00:01:30    2
7978         2000-01-01 00:02:00    2
7979         Freq: 30S, dtype: int64
7980 
7981         Pass a custom function via ``apply``
7982 
7983         >>> def custom_resampler(array_like):
7984         ...     return np.sum(array_like) + 5
7985         ...
7986         >>> series.resample('3T').apply(custom_resampler)
7987         2000-01-01 00:00:00     8
7988         2000-01-01 00:03:00    17
7989         2000-01-01 00:06:00    26
7990         Freq: 3T, dtype: int64
7991 
7992         For a Series with a PeriodIndex, the keyword `convention` can be
7993         used to control whether to use the start or end of `rule`.
7994 
7995         Resample a year by quarter using 'start' `convention`. Values are
7996         assigned to the first quarter of the period.
7997 
7998         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=pd.period_range('2012-01-01',
7999         ...                                             freq='A',
8000         ...                                             periods=2))
8001         >>> s
8002         2012    1
8003         2013    2
8004         Freq: A-DEC, dtype: int64
8005         >>> s.resample('Q', convention='start').asfreq()
8006         2012Q1    1.0
8007         2012Q2    NaN
8008         2012Q3    NaN
8009         2012Q4    NaN
8010         2013Q1    2.0
8011         2013Q2    NaN
8012         2013Q3    NaN
8013         2013Q4    NaN
8014         Freq: Q-DEC, dtype: float64
8015 
8016         Resample quarters by month using 'end' `convention`. Values are
8017         assigned to the last month of the period.
8018 
8019         >>> q = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4], index=pd.period_range('2018-01-01',
8020         ...                                                   freq='Q',
8021         ...                                                   periods=4))
8022         >>> q
8023         2018Q1    1
8024         2018Q2    2
8025         2018Q3    3
8026         2018Q4    4
8027         Freq: Q-DEC, dtype: int64
8028         >>> q.resample('M', convention='end').asfreq()
8029         2018-03    1.0
8030         2018-04    NaN
8031         2018-05    NaN
8032         2018-06    2.0
8033         2018-07    NaN
8034         2018-08    NaN
8035         2018-09    3.0
8036         2018-10    NaN
8037         2018-11    NaN
8038         2018-12    4.0
8039         Freq: M, dtype: float64
8040 
8041         For DataFrame objects, the keyword `on` can be used to specify the
8042         column instead of the index for resampling.
8043 
8044         >>> d = dict({'price': [10, 11, 9, 13, 14, 18, 17, 19],
8045         ...           'volume': [50, 60, 40, 100, 50, 100, 40, 50]})
8046         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(d)
8047         >>> df['week_starting'] = pd.date_range('01/01/2018',
8048         ...                                     periods=8,
8049         ...                                     freq='W')
8050         >>> df
8051            price  volume week_starting
8052         0     10      50    2018-01-07
8053         1     11      60    2018-01-14
8054         2      9      40    2018-01-21
8055         3     13     100    2018-01-28
8056         4     14      50    2018-02-04
8057         5     18     100    2018-02-11
8058         6     17      40    2018-02-18
8059         7     19      50    2018-02-25
8060         >>> df.resample('M', on='week_starting').mean()
8061                        price  volume
8062         week_starting
8063         2018-01-31     10.75    62.5
8064         2018-02-28     17.00    60.0
8065 
8066         For a DataFrame with MultiIndex, the keyword `level` can be used to
8067         specify on which level the resampling needs to take place.
8068 
8069         >>> days = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=4, freq='D')
8070         >>> d2 = dict({'price': [10, 11, 9, 13, 14, 18, 17, 19],
8071         ...            'volume': [50, 60, 40, 100, 50, 100, 40, 50]})
8072         >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame(d2,
8073         ...                    index=pd.MultiIndex.from_product([days,
8074         ...                                                     ['morning',
8075         ...                                                      'afternoon']]
8076         ...                                                     ))
8077         >>> df2
8078                               price  volume
8079         2000-01-01 morning       10      50
8080                    afternoon     11      60
8081         2000-01-02 morning        9      40
8082                    afternoon     13     100
8083         2000-01-03 morning       14      50
8084                    afternoon     18     100
8085         2000-01-04 morning       17      40
8086                    afternoon     19      50
8087         >>> df2.resample('D', level=0).sum()
8088                     price  volume
8089         2000-01-01     21     110
8090         2000-01-02     22     140
8091         2000-01-03     32     150
8092         2000-01-04     36      90
8093 
8094         If you want to adjust the start of the bins based on a fixed timestamp:
8095 
8096         >>> start, end = '2000-10-01 23:30:00', '2000-10-02 00:30:00'
8097         >>> rng = pd.date_range(start, end, freq='7min')
8098         >>> ts = pd.Series(np.arange(len(rng)) * 3, index=rng)
8099         >>> ts
8100         2000-10-01 23:30:00     0
8101         2000-10-01 23:37:00     3
8102         2000-10-01 23:44:00     6
8103         2000-10-01 23:51:00     9
8104         2000-10-01 23:58:00    12
8105         2000-10-02 00:05:00    15
8106         2000-10-02 00:12:00    18
8107         2000-10-02 00:19:00    21
8108         2000-10-02 00:26:00    24
8109         Freq: 7T, dtype: int64
8110 
8111         >>> ts.resample('17min').sum()
8112         2000-10-01 23:14:00     0
8113         2000-10-01 23:31:00     9
8114         2000-10-01 23:48:00    21
8115         2000-10-02 00:05:00    54
8116         2000-10-02 00:22:00    24
8117         Freq: 17T, dtype: int64
8118 
8119         >>> ts.resample('17min', origin='epoch').sum()
8120         2000-10-01 23:18:00     0
8121         2000-10-01 23:35:00    18
8122         2000-10-01 23:52:00    27
8123         2000-10-02 00:09:00    39
8124         2000-10-02 00:26:00    24
8125         Freq: 17T, dtype: int64
8126 
8127         >>> ts.resample('17min', origin='2000-01-01').sum()
8128         2000-10-01 23:24:00     3
8129         2000-10-01 23:41:00    15
8130         2000-10-01 23:58:00    45
8131         2000-10-02 00:15:00    45
8132         Freq: 17T, dtype: int64
8133 
8134         If you want to adjust the start of the bins with an `offset` Timedelta, the two
8135         following lines are equivalent:
8136 
8137         >>> ts.resample('17min', origin='start').sum()
8138         2000-10-01 23:30:00     9
8139         2000-10-01 23:47:00    21
8140         2000-10-02 00:04:00    54
8141         2000-10-02 00:21:00    24
8142         Freq: 17T, dtype: int64
8143 
8144         >>> ts.resample('17min', offset='23h30min').sum()
8145         2000-10-01 23:30:00     9
8146         2000-10-01 23:47:00    21
8147         2000-10-02 00:04:00    54
8148         2000-10-02 00:21:00    24
8149         Freq: 17T, dtype: int64
8150 
8151         To replace the use of the deprecated `base` argument, you can now use `offset`,
8152         in this example it is equivalent to have `base=2`:
8153 
8154         >>> ts.resample('17min', offset='2min').sum()
8155         2000-10-01 23:16:00     0
8156         2000-10-01 23:33:00     9
8157         2000-10-01 23:50:00    36
8158         2000-10-02 00:07:00    39
8159         2000-10-02 00:24:00    24
8160         Freq: 17T, dtype: int64
8161 
8162         To replace the use of the deprecated `loffset` argument:
8163 
8164         >>> from pandas.tseries.frequencies import to_offset
8165         >>> loffset = '19min'
8166         >>> ts_out = ts.resample('17min').sum()
8167         >>> ts_out.index = ts_out.index + to_offset(loffset)
8168         >>> ts_out
8169         2000-10-01 23:33:00     0
8170         2000-10-01 23:50:00     9
8171         2000-10-02 00:07:00    21
8172         2000-10-02 00:24:00    54
8173         2000-10-02 00:41:00    24
8174         Freq: 17T, dtype: int64
8175         """
8176         from pandas.core.resample import get_resampler
8177 
8178         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
8179         return get_resampler(
8180             self,
8181             freq=rule,
8182             label=label,
8183             closed=closed,
8184             axis=axis,
8185             kind=kind,
8186             loffset=loffset,
8187             convention=convention,
8188             base=base,
8189             key=on,
8190             level=level,
8191             origin=origin,
8192             offset=offset,
8193         )
8194 
8195     def first(self: FrameOrSeries, offset) -> FrameOrSeries:
8196         """
8197         Select initial periods of time series data based on a date offset.
8198 
8199         When having a DataFrame with dates as index, this function can
8200         select the first few rows based on a date offset.
8201 
8202         Parameters
8203         ----------
8204         offset : str, DateOffset or dateutil.relativedelta
8205             The offset length of the data that will be selected. For instance,
8206             '1M' will display all the rows having their index within the first month.
8207 
8208         Returns
8209         -------
8210         Series or DataFrame
8211             A subset of the caller.
8212 
8213         Raises
8214         ------
8215         TypeError
8216             If the index is not  a :class:`DatetimeIndex`
8217 
8218         See Also
8219         --------
8220         last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset.
8221         at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day.
8222         between_time : Select values between particular times of the day.
8223 
8224         Examples
8225         --------
8226         >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='2D')
8227         >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4]}, index=i)
8228         >>> ts
8229                     A
8230         2018-04-09  1
8231         2018-04-11  2
8232         2018-04-13  3
8233         2018-04-15  4
8234 
8235         Get the rows for the first 3 days:
8236 
8237         >>> ts.first('3D')
8238                     A
8239         2018-04-09  1
8240         2018-04-11  2
8241 
8242         Notice the data for 3 first calendar days were returned, not the first
8243         3 days observed in the dataset, and therefore data for 2018-04-13 was
8244         not returned.
8245         """
8246         if not isinstance(self.index, DatetimeIndex):
8247             raise TypeError("'first' only supports a DatetimeIndex index")
8248 
8249         if len(self.index) == 0:
8250             return self
8251 
8252         offset = to_offset(offset)
8253         end_date = end = self.index[0] + offset
8254 
8255         # Tick-like, e.g. 3 weeks
8256         if isinstance(offset, Tick):
8257             if end_date in self.index:
8258                 end = self.index.searchsorted(end_date, side="left")
8259                 return self.iloc[:end]
8260 
8261         return self.loc[:end]
8262 
8263     def last(self: FrameOrSeries, offset) -> FrameOrSeries:
8264         """
8265         Select final periods of time series data based on a date offset.
8266 
8267         When having a DataFrame with dates as index, this function can
8268         select the last few rows based on a date offset.
8269 
8270         Parameters
8271         ----------
8272         offset : str, DateOffset, dateutil.relativedelta
8273             The offset length of the data that will be selected. For instance,
8274             '3D' will display all the rows having their index within the last 3 days.
8275 
8276         Returns
8277         -------
8278         Series or DataFrame
8279             A subset of the caller.
8280 
8281         Raises
8282         ------
8283         TypeError
8284             If the index is not  a :class:`DatetimeIndex`
8285 
8286         See Also
8287         --------
8288         first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset.
8289         at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day.
8290         between_time : Select values between particular times of the day.
8291 
8292         Examples
8293         --------
8294         >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='2D')
8295         >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4]}, index=i)
8296         >>> ts
8297                     A
8298         2018-04-09  1
8299         2018-04-11  2
8300         2018-04-13  3
8301         2018-04-15  4
8302 
8303         Get the rows for the last 3 days:
8304 
8305         >>> ts.last('3D')
8306                     A
8307         2018-04-13  3
8308         2018-04-15  4
8309 
8310         Notice the data for 3 last calendar days were returned, not the last
8311         3 observed days in the dataset, and therefore data for 2018-04-11 was
8312         not returned.
8313         """
8314         if not isinstance(self.index, DatetimeIndex):
8315             raise TypeError("'last' only supports a DatetimeIndex index")
8316 
8317         if len(self.index) == 0:
8318             return self
8319 
8320         offset = to_offset(offset)
8321 
8322         start_date = self.index[-1] - offset
8323         start = self.index.searchsorted(start_date, side="right")
8324         return self.iloc[start:]
8325 
8326     def rank(
8327         self: FrameOrSeries,
8328         axis=0,
8329         method: str = "average",
8330         numeric_only: Optional[bool_t] = None,
8331         na_option: str = "keep",
8332         ascending: bool_t = True,
8333         pct: bool_t = False,
8334     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
8335         """
8336         Compute numerical data ranks (1 through n) along axis.
8337 
8338         By default, equal values are assigned a rank that is the average of the
8339         ranks of those values.
8340 
8341         Parameters
8342         ----------
8343         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
8344             Index to direct ranking.
8345         method : {'average', 'min', 'max', 'first', 'dense'}, default 'average'
8346             How to rank the group of records that have the same value (i.e. ties):
8347 
8348             * average: average rank of the group
8349             * min: lowest rank in the group
8350             * max: highest rank in the group
8351             * first: ranks assigned in order they appear in the array
8352             * dense: like 'min', but rank always increases by 1 between groups.
8353 
8354         numeric_only : bool, optional
8355             For DataFrame objects, rank only numeric columns if set to True.
8356         na_option : {'keep', 'top', 'bottom'}, default 'keep'
8357             How to rank NaN values:
8358 
8359             * keep: assign NaN rank to NaN values
8360             * top: assign smallest rank to NaN values if ascending
8361             * bottom: assign highest rank to NaN values if ascending.
8362 
8363         ascending : bool, default True
8364             Whether or not the elements should be ranked in ascending order.
8365         pct : bool, default False
8366             Whether or not to display the returned rankings in percentile
8367             form.
8368 
8369         Returns
8370         -------
8371         same type as caller
8372             Return a Series or DataFrame with data ranks as values.
8373 
8374         See Also
8375         --------
8376         core.groupby.GroupBy.rank : Rank of values within each group.
8377 
8378         Examples
8379         --------
8380         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data={'Animal': ['cat', 'penguin', 'dog',
8381         ...                                    'spider', 'snake'],
8382         ...                         'Number_legs': [4, 2, 4, 8, np.nan]})
8383         >>> df
8384             Animal  Number_legs
8385         0      cat          4.0
8386         1  penguin          2.0
8387         2      dog          4.0
8388         3   spider          8.0
8389         4    snake          NaN
8390 
8391         The following example shows how the method behaves with the above
8392         parameters:
8393 
8394         * default_rank: this is the default behaviour obtained without using
8395           any parameter.
8396         * max_rank: setting ``method = 'max'`` the records that have the
8397           same values are ranked using the highest rank (e.g.: since 'cat'
8398           and 'dog' are both in the 2nd and 3rd position, rank 3 is assigned.)
8399         * NA_bottom: choosing ``na_option = 'bottom'``, if there are records
8400           with NaN values they are placed at the bottom of the ranking.
8401         * pct_rank: when setting ``pct = True``, the ranking is expressed as
8402           percentile rank.
8403 
8404         >>> df['default_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank()
8405         >>> df['max_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(method='max')
8406         >>> df['NA_bottom'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(na_option='bottom')
8407         >>> df['pct_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(pct=True)
8408         >>> df
8409             Animal  Number_legs  default_rank  max_rank  NA_bottom  pct_rank
8410         0      cat          4.0           2.5       3.0        2.5     0.625
8411         1  penguin          2.0           1.0       1.0        1.0     0.250
8412         2      dog          4.0           2.5       3.0        2.5     0.625
8413         3   spider          8.0           4.0       4.0        4.0     1.000
8414         4    snake          NaN           NaN       NaN        5.0       NaN
8415         """
8416         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
8417 
8418         if na_option not in {"keep", "top", "bottom"}:
8419             msg = "na_option must be one of 'keep', 'top', or 'bottom'"
8420             raise ValueError(msg)
8421 
8422         def ranker(data):
8423             ranks = algos.rank(
8424                 data.values,
8425                 axis=axis,
8426                 method=method,
8427                 ascending=ascending,
8428                 na_option=na_option,
8429                 pct=pct,
8430             )
8431             ranks = self._constructor(ranks, **data._construct_axes_dict())
8432             return ranks.__finalize__(self, method="rank")
8433 
8434         # if numeric_only is None, and we can't get anything, we try with
8435         # numeric_only=True
8436         if numeric_only is None:
8437             try:
8438                 return ranker(self)
8439             except TypeError:
8440                 numeric_only = True
8441 
8442         if numeric_only:
8443             data = self._get_numeric_data()
8444         else:
8445             data = self
8446 
8447         return ranker(data)
8448 
8449     _shared_docs[
8450         "compare"
8451     ] = """
8452         Compare to another %(klass)s and show the differences.
8453 
8454         .. versionadded:: 1.1.0
8455 
8456         Parameters
8457         ----------
8458         other : %(klass)s
8459             Object to compare with.
8460 
8461         align_axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 1
8462             Determine which axis to align the comparison on.
8463 
8464             * 0, or 'index' : Resulting differences are stacked vertically
8465                 with rows drawn alternately from self and other.
8466             * 1, or 'columns' : Resulting differences are aligned horizontally
8467                 with columns drawn alternately from self and other.
8468 
8469         keep_shape : bool, default False
8470             If true, all rows and columns are kept.
8471             Otherwise, only the ones with different values are kept.
8472 
8473         keep_equal : bool, default False
8474             If true, the result keeps values that are equal.
8475             Otherwise, equal values are shown as NaNs.
8476         """
8477 
8478     @Appender(_shared_docs["compare"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
8479     def compare(
8480         self,
8481         other,
8482         align_axis: Axis = 1,
8483         keep_shape: bool_t = False,
8484         keep_equal: bool_t = False,
8485     ):
8486         from pandas.core.reshape.concat import concat
8487 
8488         if type(self) is not type(other):
8489             cls_self, cls_other = type(self).__name__, type(other).__name__
8490             raise TypeError(
8491                 f"can only compare '{cls_self}' (not '{cls_other}') with '{cls_self}'"
8492             )
8493 
8494         mask = ~((self == other) | (self.isna() & other.isna()))
8495         keys = ["self", "other"]
8496 
8497         if not keep_equal:
8498             self = self.where(mask)
8499             other = other.where(mask)
8500 
8501         if not keep_shape:
8502             if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame):
8503                 cmask = mask.any()
8504                 rmask = mask.any(axis=1)
8505                 self = self.loc[rmask, cmask]
8506                 other = other.loc[rmask, cmask]
8507             else:
8508                 self = self[mask]
8509                 other = other[mask]
8510 
8511         if align_axis in (1, "columns"):  # This is needed for Series
8512             axis = 1
8513         else:
8514             axis = self._get_axis_number(align_axis)
8515 
8516         diff = concat([self, other], axis=axis, keys=keys)
8517 
8518         if axis >= self.ndim:
8519             # No need to reorganize data if stacking on new axis
8520             # This currently applies for stacking two Series on columns
8521             return diff
8522 
8523         ax = diff._get_axis(axis)
8524         ax_names = np.array(ax.names)
8525 
8526         # set index names to positions to avoid confusion
8527         ax.names = np.arange(len(ax_names))
8528 
8529         # bring self-other to inner level
8530         order = list(range(1, ax.nlevels)) + [0]
8531         if isinstance(diff, ABCDataFrame):
8532             diff = diff.reorder_levels(order, axis=axis)
8533         else:
8534             diff = diff.reorder_levels(order)
8535 
8536         # restore the index names in order
8537         diff._get_axis(axis=axis).names = ax_names[order]
8538 
8539         # reorder axis to keep things organized
8540         indices = (
8541             np.arange(diff.shape[axis]).reshape([2, diff.shape[axis] // 2]).T.flatten()
8542         )
8543         diff = diff.take(indices, axis=axis)
8544 
8545         return diff
8546 
8547     @doc(**_shared_doc_kwargs)
8548     def align(
8549         self,
8550         other,
8551         join="outer",
8552         axis=None,
8553         level=None,
8554         copy=True,
8555         fill_value=None,
8556         method=None,
8557         limit=None,
8558         fill_axis=0,
8559         broadcast_axis=None,
8560     ):
8561         """
8562         Align two objects on their axes with the specified join method.
8563 
8564         Join method is specified for each axis Index.
8565 
8566         Parameters
8567         ----------
8568         other : DataFrame or Series
8569         join : {{'outer', 'inner', 'left', 'right'}}, default 'outer'
8570         axis : allowed axis of the other object, default None
8571             Align on index (0), columns (1), or both (None).
8572         level : int or level name, default None
8573             Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the
8574             passed MultiIndex level.
8575         copy : bool, default True
8576             Always returns new objects. If copy=False and no reindexing is
8577             required then original objects are returned.
8578         fill_value : scalar, default np.NaN
8579             Value to use for missing values. Defaults to NaN, but can be any
8580             "compatible" value.
8581         method : {{'backfill', 'bfill', 'pad', 'ffill', None}}, default None
8582             Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series:
8583 
8584             - pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next valid.
8585             - backfill / bfill: use NEXT valid observation to fill gap.
8586 
8587         limit : int, default None
8588             If method is specified, this is the maximum number of consecutive
8589             NaN values to forward/backward fill. In other words, if there is
8590             a gap with more than this number of consecutive NaNs, it will only
8591             be partially filled. If method is not specified, this is the
8592             maximum number of entries along the entire axis where NaNs will be
8593             filled. Must be greater than 0 if not None.
8594         fill_axis : {axes_single_arg}, default 0
8595             Filling axis, method and limit.
8596         broadcast_axis : {axes_single_arg}, default None
8597             Broadcast values along this axis, if aligning two objects of
8598             different dimensions.
8599 
8600         Returns
8601         -------
8602         (left, right) : ({klass}, type of other)
8603             Aligned objects.
8604         """
8605 
8606         method = missing.clean_fill_method(method)
8607 
8608         if broadcast_axis == 1 and self.ndim != other.ndim:
8609             if isinstance(self, ABCSeries):
8610                 # this means other is a DataFrame, and we need to broadcast
8611                 # self
8612                 cons = self._constructor_expanddim
8613                 df = cons(
8614                     {c: self for c in other.columns}, **other._construct_axes_dict()
8615                 )
8616                 return df._align_frame(
8617                     other,
8618                     join=join,
8619                     axis=axis,
8620                     level=level,
8621                     copy=copy,
8622                     fill_value=fill_value,
8623                     method=method,
8624                     limit=limit,
8625                     fill_axis=fill_axis,
8626                 )
8627             elif isinstance(other, ABCSeries):
8628                 # this means self is a DataFrame, and we need to broadcast
8629                 # other
8630                 cons = other._constructor_expanddim
8631                 df = cons(
8632                     {c: other for c in self.columns}, **self._construct_axes_dict()
8633                 )
8634                 return self._align_frame(
8635                     df,
8636                     join=join,
8637                     axis=axis,
8638                     level=level,
8639                     copy=copy,
8640                     fill_value=fill_value,
8641                     method=method,
8642                     limit=limit,
8643                     fill_axis=fill_axis,
8644                 )
8645 
8646         if axis is not None:
8647             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
8648         if isinstance(other, ABCDataFrame):
8649             return self._align_frame(
8650                 other,
8651                 join=join,
8652                 axis=axis,
8653                 level=level,
8654                 copy=copy,
8655                 fill_value=fill_value,
8656                 method=method,
8657                 limit=limit,
8658                 fill_axis=fill_axis,
8659             )
8660         elif isinstance(other, ABCSeries):
8661             return self._align_series(
8662                 other,
8663                 join=join,
8664                 axis=axis,
8665                 level=level,
8666                 copy=copy,
8667                 fill_value=fill_value,
8668                 method=method,
8669                 limit=limit,
8670                 fill_axis=fill_axis,
8671             )
8672         else:  # pragma: no cover
8673             raise TypeError(f"unsupported type: {type(other)}")
8674 
8675     def _align_frame(
8676         self,
8677         other,
8678         join="outer",
8679         axis=None,
8680         level=None,
8681         copy: bool_t = True,
8682         fill_value=None,
8683         method=None,
8684         limit=None,
8685         fill_axis=0,
8686     ):
8687         # defaults
8688         join_index, join_columns = None, None
8689         ilidx, iridx = None, None
8690         clidx, cridx = None, None
8691 
8692         is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries)
8693 
8694         if axis is None or axis == 0:
8695             if not self.index.equals(other.index):
8696                 join_index, ilidx, iridx = self.index.join(
8697                     other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True
8698                 )
8699 
8700         if axis is None or axis == 1:
8701             if not is_series and not self.columns.equals(other.columns):
8702                 join_columns, clidx, cridx = self.columns.join(
8703                     other.columns, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True
8704                 )
8705 
8706         if is_series:
8707             reindexers = {0: [join_index, ilidx]}
8708         else:
8709             reindexers = {0: [join_index, ilidx], 1: [join_columns, clidx]}
8710 
8711         left = self._reindex_with_indexers(
8712             reindexers, copy=copy, fill_value=fill_value, allow_dups=True
8713         )
8714         # other must be always DataFrame
8715         right = other._reindex_with_indexers(
8716             {0: [join_index, iridx], 1: [join_columns, cridx]},
8717             copy=copy,
8718             fill_value=fill_value,
8719             allow_dups=True,
8720         )
8721 
8722         if method is not None:
8723             _left = left.fillna(method=method, axis=fill_axis, limit=limit)
8724             assert _left is not None  # needed for mypy
8725             left = _left
8726             right = right.fillna(method=method, axis=fill_axis, limit=limit)
8727 
8728         # if DatetimeIndex have different tz, convert to UTC
8729         if is_datetime64tz_dtype(left.index.dtype):
8730             if left.index.tz != right.index.tz:
8731                 if join_index is not None:
8732                     left.index = join_index
8733                     right.index = join_index
8734 
8735         return (
8736             left.__finalize__(self),
8737             right.__finalize__(other),
8738         )
8739 
8740     def _align_series(
8741         self,
8742         other,
8743         join="outer",
8744         axis=None,
8745         level=None,
8746         copy: bool_t = True,
8747         fill_value=None,
8748         method=None,
8749         limit=None,
8750         fill_axis=0,
8751     ):
8752 
8753         is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries)
8754 
8755         # series/series compat, other must always be a Series
8756         if is_series:
8757             if axis:
8758                 raise ValueError("cannot align series to a series other than axis 0")
8759 
8760             # equal
8761             if self.index.equals(other.index):
8762                 join_index, lidx, ridx = None, None, None
8763             else:
8764                 join_index, lidx, ridx = self.index.join(
8765                     other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True
8766                 )
8767 
8768             left = self._reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, copy)
8769             right = other._reindex_indexer(join_index, ridx, copy)
8770 
8771         else:
8772             # one has > 1 ndim
8773             fdata = self._mgr
8774             if axis == 0:
8775                 join_index = self.index
8776                 lidx, ridx = None, None
8777                 if not self.index.equals(other.index):
8778                     join_index, lidx, ridx = self.index.join(
8779                         other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True
8780                     )
8781 
8782                 if lidx is not None:
8783                     fdata = fdata.reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, axis=1)
8784 
8785             elif axis == 1:
8786                 join_index = self.columns
8787                 lidx, ridx = None, None
8788                 if not self.columns.equals(other.index):
8789                     join_index, lidx, ridx = self.columns.join(
8790                         other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True
8791                     )
8792 
8793                 if lidx is not None:
8794                     fdata = fdata.reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, axis=0)
8795             else:
8796                 raise ValueError("Must specify axis=0 or 1")
8797 
8798             if copy and fdata is self._mgr:
8799                 fdata = fdata.copy()
8800 
8801             left = self._constructor(fdata)
8802 
8803             if ridx is None:
8804                 right = other
8805             else:
8806                 right = other.reindex(join_index, level=level)
8807 
8808         # fill
8809         fill_na = notna(fill_value) or (method is not None)
8810         if fill_na:
8811             left = left.fillna(fill_value, method=method, limit=limit, axis=fill_axis)
8812             right = right.fillna(fill_value, method=method, limit=limit)
8813 
8814         # if DatetimeIndex have different tz, convert to UTC
8815         if is_series or (not is_series and axis == 0):
8816             if is_datetime64tz_dtype(left.index.dtype):
8817                 if left.index.tz != right.index.tz:
8818                     if join_index is not None:
8819                         left.index = join_index
8820                         right.index = join_index
8821 
8822         return (
8823             left.__finalize__(self),
8824             right.__finalize__(other),
8825         )
8826 
8827     def _where(
8828         self,
8829         cond,
8830         other=np.nan,
8831         inplace=False,
8832         axis=None,
8833         level=None,
8834         errors="raise",
8835         try_cast=False,
8836     ):
8837         """
8838         Equivalent to public method `where`, except that `other` is not
8839         applied as a function even if callable. Used in __setitem__.
8840         """
8841         inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace")
8842 
8843         # align the cond to same shape as myself
8844         cond = com.apply_if_callable(cond, self)
8845         if isinstance(cond, NDFrame):
8846             cond, _ = cond.align(self, join="right", broadcast_axis=1)
8847         else:
8848             if not hasattr(cond, "shape"):
8849                 cond = np.asanyarray(cond)
8850             if cond.shape != self.shape:
8851                 raise ValueError("Array conditional must be same shape as self")
8852             cond = self._constructor(cond, **self._construct_axes_dict())
8853 
8854         # make sure we are boolean
8855         fill_value = bool(inplace)
8856         cond = cond.fillna(fill_value)
8857 
8858         msg = "Boolean array expected for the condition, not {dtype}"
8859 
8860         if not cond.empty:
8861             if not isinstance(cond, ABCDataFrame):
8862                 # This is a single-dimensional object.
8863                 if not is_bool_dtype(cond):
8864                     raise ValueError(msg.format(dtype=cond.dtype))
8865             else:
8866                 for dt in cond.dtypes:
8867                     if not is_bool_dtype(dt):
8868                         raise ValueError(msg.format(dtype=dt))
8869         else:
8870             # GH#21947 we have an empty DataFrame/Series, could be object-dtype
8871             cond = cond.astype(bool)
8872 
8873         cond = -cond if inplace else cond
8874 
8875         # try to align with other
8876         try_quick = True
8877         if isinstance(other, NDFrame):
8878 
8879             # align with me
8880             if other.ndim <= self.ndim:
8881 
8882                 _, other = self.align(
8883                     other, join="left", axis=axis, level=level, fill_value=np.nan
8884                 )
8885 
8886                 # if we are NOT aligned, raise as we cannot where index
8887                 if axis is None and not all(
8888                     other._get_axis(i).equals(ax) for i, ax in enumerate(self.axes)
8889                 ):
8890                     raise InvalidIndexError
8891 
8892             # slice me out of the other
8893             else:
8894                 raise NotImplementedError(
8895                     "cannot align with a higher dimensional NDFrame"
8896                 )
8897 
8898         if isinstance(other, np.ndarray):
8899 
8900             if other.shape != self.shape:
8901 
8902                 if self.ndim == 1:
8903 
8904                     icond = cond._values
8905 
8906                     # GH 2745 / GH 4192
8907                     # treat like a scalar
8908                     if len(other) == 1:
8909                         other = other[0]
8910 
8911                     # GH 3235
8912                     # match True cond to other
8913                     elif len(cond[icond]) == len(other):
8914 
8915                         # try to not change dtype at first (if try_quick)
8916                         if try_quick:
8917                             new_other = np.asarray(self)
8918                             new_other = new_other.copy()
8919                             new_other[icond] = other
8920                             other = new_other
8921 
8922                     else:
8923                         raise ValueError(
8924                             "Length of replacements must equal series length"
8925                         )
8926 
8927                 else:
8928                     raise ValueError(
8929                         "other must be the same shape as self when an ndarray"
8930                     )
8931 
8932             # we are the same shape, so create an actual object for alignment
8933             else:
8934                 other = self._constructor(other, **self._construct_axes_dict())
8935 
8936         if axis is None:
8937             axis = 0
8938 
8939         if self.ndim == getattr(other, "ndim", 0):
8940             align = True
8941         else:
8942             align = self._get_axis_number(axis) == 1
8943 
8944         if align and isinstance(other, NDFrame):
8945             other = other.reindex(self._info_axis, axis=self._info_axis_number)
8946         if isinstance(cond, NDFrame):
8947             cond = cond.reindex(self._info_axis, axis=self._info_axis_number)
8948 
8949         block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis)
8950 
8951         if inplace:
8952             # we may have different type blocks come out of putmask, so
8953             # reconstruct the block manager
8954 
8955             self._check_inplace_setting(other)
8956             new_data = self._mgr.putmask(
8957                 mask=cond, new=other, align=align, axis=block_axis,
8958             )
8959             result = self._constructor(new_data)
8960             return self._update_inplace(result)
8961 
8962         else:
8963             new_data = self._mgr.where(
8964                 other=other,
8965                 cond=cond,
8966                 align=align,
8967                 errors=errors,
8968                 try_cast=try_cast,
8969                 axis=block_axis,
8970             )
8971             result = self._constructor(new_data)
8972             return result.__finalize__(self)
8973 
8974     _shared_docs[
8975         "where"
8976     ] = """
8977         Replace values where the condition is %(cond_rev)s.
8978 
8979         Parameters
8980         ----------
8981         cond : bool %(klass)s, array-like, or callable
8982             Where `cond` is %(cond)s, keep the original value. Where
8983             %(cond_rev)s, replace with corresponding value from `other`.
8984             If `cond` is callable, it is computed on the %(klass)s and
8985             should return boolean %(klass)s or array. The callable must
8986             not change input %(klass)s (though pandas doesn't check it).
8987         other : scalar, %(klass)s, or callable
8988             Entries where `cond` is %(cond_rev)s are replaced with
8989             corresponding value from `other`.
8990             If other is callable, it is computed on the %(klass)s and
8991             should return scalar or %(klass)s. The callable must not
8992             change input %(klass)s (though pandas doesn't check it).
8993         inplace : bool, default False
8994             Whether to perform the operation in place on the data.
8995         axis : int, default None
8996             Alignment axis if needed.
8997         level : int, default None
8998             Alignment level if needed.
8999         errors : str, {'raise', 'ignore'}, default 'raise'
9000             Note that currently this parameter won't affect
9001             the results and will always coerce to a suitable dtype.
9002 
9003             - 'raise' : allow exceptions to be raised.
9004             - 'ignore' : suppress exceptions. On error return original object.
9005 
9006         try_cast : bool, default False
9007             Try to cast the result back to the input type (if possible).
9008 
9009         Returns
9010         -------
9011         Same type as caller
9012 
9013         See Also
9014         --------
9015         :func:`DataFrame.%(name_other)s` : Return an object of same shape as
9016             self.
9017 
9018         Notes
9019         -----
9020         The %(name)s method is an application of the if-then idiom. For each
9021         element in the calling DataFrame, if ``cond`` is ``%(cond)s`` the
9022         element is used; otherwise the corresponding element from the DataFrame
9023         ``other`` is used.
9024 
9025         The signature for :func:`DataFrame.where` differs from
9026         :func:`numpy.where`. Roughly ``df1.where(m, df2)`` is equivalent to
9027         ``np.where(m, df1, df2)``.
9028 
9029         For further details and examples see the ``%(name)s`` documentation in
9030         :ref:`indexing <indexing.where_mask>`.
9031 
9032         Examples
9033         --------
9034         >>> s = pd.Series(range(5))
9035         >>> s.where(s > 0)
9036         0    NaN
9037         1    1.0
9038         2    2.0
9039         3    3.0
9040         4    4.0
9041         dtype: float64
9042 
9043         >>> s.mask(s > 0)
9044         0    0.0
9045         1    NaN
9046         2    NaN
9047         3    NaN
9048         4    NaN
9049         dtype: float64
9050 
9051         >>> s.where(s > 1, 10)
9052         0    10
9053         1    10
9054         2    2
9055         3    3
9056         4    4
9057         dtype: int64
9058 
9059         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.arange(10).reshape(-1, 2), columns=['A', 'B'])
9060         >>> df
9061            A  B
9062         0  0  1
9063         1  2  3
9064         2  4  5
9065         3  6  7
9066         4  8  9
9067         >>> m = df %% 3 == 0
9068         >>> df.where(m, -df)
9069            A  B
9070         0  0 -1
9071         1 -2  3
9072         2 -4 -5
9073         3  6 -7
9074         4 -8  9
9075         >>> df.where(m, -df) == np.where(m, df, -df)
9076               A     B
9077         0  True  True
9078         1  True  True
9079         2  True  True
9080         3  True  True
9081         4  True  True
9082         >>> df.where(m, -df) == df.mask(~m, -df)
9083               A     B
9084         0  True  True
9085         1  True  True
9086         2  True  True
9087         3  True  True
9088         4  True  True
9089         """
9090
