9155     @doc(klass=_shared_doc_kwargs["klass"])
9156     def shift(
9157         self: FrameOrSeries, periods=1, freq=None, axis=0, fill_value=None
9158     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
9159         """
9160         Shift index by desired number of periods with an optional time `freq`.
9161 
9162         When `freq` is not passed, shift the index without realigning the data.
9163         If `freq` is passed (in this case, the index must be date or datetime,
9164         or it will raise a `NotImplementedError`), the index will be
9165         increased using the periods and the `freq`.
9166 
9167         Parameters
9168         ----------
9169         periods : int
9170             Number of periods to shift. Can be positive or negative.
9171         freq : DateOffset, tseries.offsets, timedelta, or str, optional
9172             Offset to use from the tseries module or time rule (e.g. 'EOM').
9173             If `freq` is specified then the index values are shifted but the
9174             data is not realigned. That is, use `freq` if you would like to
9175             extend the index when shifting and preserve the original data.
9176         axis : {{0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}}, default None
9177             Shift direction.
9178         fill_value : object, optional
9179             The scalar value to use for newly introduced missing values.
9180             the default depends on the dtype of `self`.
9181             For numeric data, ``np.nan`` is used.
9182             For datetime, timedelta, or period data, etc. :attr:`NaT` is used.
9183             For extension dtypes, ``self.dtype.na_value`` is used.
9184 
9185             .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0
9186 
9187         Returns
9188         -------
9189         {klass}
9190             Copy of input object, shifted.
9191 
9192         See Also
9193         --------
9194         Index.shift : Shift values of Index.
9195         DatetimeIndex.shift : Shift values of DatetimeIndex.
9196         PeriodIndex.shift : Shift values of PeriodIndex.
9197         tshift : Shift the time index, using the index's frequency if
9198             available.
9199 
9200         Examples
9201         --------
9202         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({{'Col1': [10, 20, 15, 30, 45],
9203         ...                    'Col2': [13, 23, 18, 33, 48],
9204         ...                    'Col3': [17, 27, 22, 37, 52]}})
9205 
9206         >>> df.shift(periods=3)
9207            Col1  Col2  Col3
9208         0   NaN   NaN   NaN
9209         1   NaN   NaN   NaN
9210         2   NaN   NaN   NaN
9211         3  10.0  13.0  17.0
9212         4  20.0  23.0  27.0
9213 
9214         >>> df.shift(periods=1, axis='columns')
9215            Col1  Col2  Col3
9216         0   NaN  10.0  13.0
9217         1   NaN  20.0  23.0
9218         2   NaN  15.0  18.0
9219         3   NaN  30.0  33.0
9220         4   NaN  45.0  48.0
9221 
9222         >>> df.shift(periods=3, fill_value=0)
9223            Col1  Col2  Col3
9224         0     0     0     0
9225         1     0     0     0
9226         2     0     0     0
9227         3    10    13    17
9228         4    20    23    27
9229         """
9230         if periods == 0:
9231             return self.copy()
9232 
9233         block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis)
9234         if freq is None:
9235             new_data = self._mgr.shift(
9236                 periods=periods, axis=block_axis, fill_value=fill_value
9237             )
9238         else:
9239             return self.tshift(periods, freq)
9240 
9241         return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self, method="shift")
9242 
9243     def slice_shift(self: FrameOrSeries, periods: int = 1, axis=0) -> FrameOrSeries:
9244         """
9245         Equivalent to `shift` without copying data.
9246 
9247         The shifted data will not include the dropped periods and the
9248         shifted axis will be smaller than the original.
9249 
9250         Parameters
9251         ----------
9252         periods : int
9253             Number of periods to move, can be positive or negative.
9254 
9255         Returns
9256         -------
9257         shifted : same type as caller
9258 
9259         Notes
9260         -----
9261         While the `slice_shift` is faster than `shift`, you may pay for it
9262         later during alignment.
9263         """
9264         if periods == 0:
9265             return self
9266 
9267         if periods > 0:
9268             vslicer = slice(None, -periods)
9269             islicer = slice(periods, None)
9270         else:
9271             vslicer = slice(-periods, None)
9272             islicer = slice(None, periods)
9273 
9274         new_obj = self._slice(vslicer, axis=axis)
9275         shifted_axis = self._get_axis(axis)[islicer]
9276         new_obj.set_axis(shifted_axis, axis=axis, inplace=True)
9277 
9278         return new_obj.__finalize__(self, method="slice_shift")
9279 
9280     def tshift(
9281         self: FrameOrSeries, periods: int = 1, freq=None, axis: Axis = 0
9282     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
9283         """
9284         Shift the time index, using the index's frequency if available.
9285 
9286         Parameters
9287         ----------
9288         periods : int
9289             Number of periods to move, can be positive or negative.
9290         freq : DateOffset, timedelta, or str, default None
9291             Increment to use from the tseries module
9292             or time rule expressed as a string (e.g. 'EOM').
9293         axis : {0 or ‘index’, 1 or ‘columns’, None}, default 0
9294             Corresponds to the axis that contains the Index.
9295 
9296         Returns
9297         -------
9298         shifted : Series/DataFrame
9299 
9300         Notes
9301         -----
9302         If freq is not specified then tries to use the freq or inferred_freq
9303         attributes of the index. If neither of those attributes exist, a
9304         ValueError is thrown
9305         """
9306         index = self._get_axis(axis)
9307         if freq is None:
9308             freq = getattr(index, "freq", None)
9309 
9310         if freq is None:
9311             freq = getattr(index, "inferred_freq", None)
9312 
9313         if freq is None:
9314             msg = "Freq was not given and was not set in the index"
9315             raise ValueError(msg)
9316 
9317         if periods == 0:
9318             return self
9319 
9320         if isinstance(freq, str):
9321             freq = to_offset(freq)
9322 
9323         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
9324         if isinstance(index, PeriodIndex):
9325             orig_freq = to_offset(index.freq)
9326             if freq != orig_freq:
9327                 assert orig_freq is not None  # for mypy
9328                 raise ValueError(
9329                     f"Given freq {freq.rule_code} does not match "
9330                     f"PeriodIndex freq {orig_freq.rule_code}"
9331                 )
9332             new_ax = index.shift(periods)
9333         else:
9334             new_ax = index.shift(periods, freq)
9335 
9336         result = self.copy()
9337         result.set_axis(new_ax, axis, inplace=True)
9338         return result.__finalize__(self, method="tshift")
9339 
9340     def truncate(
9341         self: FrameOrSeries, before=None, after=None, axis=None, copy: bool_t = True
9342     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
9343         """
9344         Truncate a Series or DataFrame before and after some index value.
9345 
9346         This is a useful shorthand for boolean indexing based on index
9347         values above or below certain thresholds.
9348 
9349         Parameters
9350         ----------
9351         before : date, str, int
9352             Truncate all rows before this index value.
9353         after : date, str, int
9354             Truncate all rows after this index value.
9355         axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, optional
9356             Axis to truncate. Truncates the index (rows) by default.
9357         copy : bool, default is True,
9358             Return a copy of the truncated section.
9359 
9360         Returns
9361         -------
9362         type of caller
9363             The truncated Series or DataFrame.
9364 
9365         See Also
9366         --------
9367         DataFrame.loc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by label.
9368         DataFrame.iloc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by position.
9369 
9370         Notes
9371         -----
9372         If the index being truncated contains only datetime values,
9373         `before` and `after` may be specified as strings instead of
9374         Timestamps.
9375 
9376         Examples
9377         --------
9378         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'],
9379         ...                    'B': ['f', 'g', 'h', 'i', 'j'],
9380         ...                    'C': ['k', 'l', 'm', 'n', 'o']},
9381         ...                   index=[1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
9382         >>> df
9383            A  B  C
9384         1  a  f  k
9385         2  b  g  l
9386         3  c  h  m
9387         4  d  i  n
9388         5  e  j  o
9389 
9390         >>> df.truncate(before=2, after=4)
9391            A  B  C
9392         2  b  g  l
9393         3  c  h  m
9394         4  d  i  n
9395 
9396         The columns of a DataFrame can be truncated.
9397 
9398         >>> df.truncate(before="A", after="B", axis="columns")
9399            A  B
9400         1  a  f
9401         2  b  g
9402         3  c  h
9403         4  d  i
9404         5  e  j
9405 
9406         For Series, only rows can be truncated.
9407 
9408         >>> df['A'].truncate(before=2, after=4)
9409         2    b
9410         3    c
9411         4    d
9412         Name: A, dtype: object
9413 
9414         The index values in ``truncate`` can be datetimes or string
9415         dates.
9416 
9417         >>> dates = pd.date_range('2016-01-01', '2016-02-01', freq='s')
9418         >>> df = pd.DataFrame(index=dates, data={'A': 1})
9419         >>> df.tail()
9420                              A
9421         2016-01-31 23:59:56  1
9422         2016-01-31 23:59:57  1
9423         2016-01-31 23:59:58  1
9424         2016-01-31 23:59:59  1
9425         2016-02-01 00:00:00  1
9426 
9427         >>> df.truncate(before=pd.Timestamp('2016-01-05'),
9428         ...             after=pd.Timestamp('2016-01-10')).tail()
9429                              A
9430         2016-01-09 23:59:56  1
9431         2016-01-09 23:59:57  1
9432         2016-01-09 23:59:58  1
9433         2016-01-09 23:59:59  1
9434         2016-01-10 00:00:00  1
9435 
9436         Because the index is a DatetimeIndex containing only dates, we can
9437         specify `before` and `after` as strings. They will be coerced to
9438         Timestamps before truncation.
9439 
9440         >>> df.truncate('2016-01-05', '2016-01-10').tail()
9441                              A
9442         2016-01-09 23:59:56  1
9443         2016-01-09 23:59:57  1
9444         2016-01-09 23:59:58  1
9445         2016-01-09 23:59:59  1
9446         2016-01-10 00:00:00  1
9447 
9448         Note that ``truncate`` assumes a 0 value for any unspecified time
9449         component (midnight). This differs from partial string slicing, which
9450         returns any partially matching dates.
9451 
9452         >>> df.loc['2016-01-05':'2016-01-10', :].tail()
9453                              A
9454         2016-01-10 23:59:55  1
9455         2016-01-10 23:59:56  1
9456         2016-01-10 23:59:57  1
9457         2016-01-10 23:59:58  1
9458         2016-01-10 23:59:59  1
9459         """
9460         if axis is None:
9461             axis = self._stat_axis_number
9462         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
9463         ax = self._get_axis(axis)
9464 
9465         # GH 17935
9466         # Check that index is sorted
9467         if not ax.is_monotonic_increasing and not ax.is_monotonic_decreasing:
9468             raise ValueError("truncate requires a sorted index")
9469 
9470         # if we have a date index, convert to dates, otherwise
9471         # treat like a slice
9472         if ax.is_all_dates:
9473             from pandas.core.tools.datetimes import to_datetime
9474 
9475             before = to_datetime(before)
9476             after = to_datetime(after)
9477 
9478         if before is not None and after is not None:
9479             if before > after:
9480                 raise ValueError(f"Truncate: {after} must be after {before}")
9481 
9482         if ax.is_monotonic_decreasing:
9483             before, after = after, before
9484 
9485         slicer = [slice(None, None)] * self._AXIS_LEN
9486         slicer[axis] = slice(before, after)
9487         result = self.loc[tuple(slicer)]
9488 
9489         if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex):
9490             setattr(result, self._get_axis_name(axis), ax.truncate(before, after))
9491 
9492         if copy:
9493             result = result.copy()
9494 
9495         return result
9496 
9497     def tz_convert(
9498         self: FrameOrSeries, tz, axis=0, level=None, copy: bool_t = True
9499     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
9500         """
9501         Convert tz-aware axis to target time zone.
9502 
9503         Parameters
9504         ----------
9505         tz : str or tzinfo object
9506         axis : the axis to convert
9507         level : int, str, default None
9508             If axis is a MultiIndex, convert a specific level. Otherwise
9509             must be None.
9510         copy : bool, default True
9511             Also make a copy of the underlying data.
9512 
9513         Returns
9514         -------
9515         %(klass)s
9516             Object with time zone converted axis.
9517 
9518         Raises
9519         ------
9520         TypeError
9521             If the axis is tz-naive.
9522         """
9523         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
9524         ax = self._get_axis(axis)
9525 
9526         def _tz_convert(ax, tz):
9527             if not hasattr(ax, "tz_convert"):
9528                 if len(ax) > 0:
9529                     ax_name = self._get_axis_name(axis)
9530                     raise TypeError(
9531                         f"{ax_name} is not a valid DatetimeIndex or PeriodIndex"
9532                     )
9533                 else:
9534                     ax = DatetimeIndex([], tz=tz)
9535             else:
9536                 ax = ax.tz_convert(tz)
9537             return ax
9538 
9539         # if a level is given it must be a MultiIndex level or
9540         # equivalent to the axis name
9541         if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex):
9542             level = ax._get_level_number(level)
9543             new_level = _tz_convert(ax.levels[level], tz)
9544             ax = ax.set_levels(new_level, level=level)
9545         else:
9546             if level not in (None, 0, ax.name):
9547                 raise ValueError(f"The level {level} is not valid")
9548             ax = _tz_convert(ax, tz)
9549 
9550         result = self.copy(deep=copy)
9551         result = result.set_axis(ax, axis=axis, inplace=False)
9552         return result.__finalize__(self, method="tz_convert")
9553 
9554     def tz_localize(
9555         self: FrameOrSeries,
9556         tz,
9557         axis=0,
9558         level=None,
9559         copy: bool_t = True,
9560         ambiguous="raise",
9561         nonexistent: str = "raise",
9562     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
9563         """
9564         Localize tz-naive index of a Series or DataFrame to target time zone.
9565 
9566         This operation localizes the Index. To localize the values in a
9567         timezone-naive Series, use :meth:`Series.dt.tz_localize`.
9568 
9569         Parameters
9570         ----------
9571         tz : str or tzinfo
9572         axis : the axis to localize
9573         level : int, str, default None
9574             If axis ia a MultiIndex, localize a specific level. Otherwise
9575             must be None.
9576         copy : bool, default True
9577             Also make a copy of the underlying data.
9578         ambiguous : 'infer', bool-ndarray, 'NaT', default 'raise'
9579             When clocks moved backward due to DST, ambiguous times may arise.
9580             For example in Central European Time (UTC+01), when going from
9581             03:00 DST to 02:00 non-DST, 02:30:00 local time occurs both at
9582             00:30:00 UTC and at 01:30:00 UTC. In such a situation, the
9583             `ambiguous` parameter dictates how ambiguous times should be
9584             handled.
9585 
9586             - 'infer' will attempt to infer fall dst-transition hours based on
9587               order
9588             - bool-ndarray where True signifies a DST time, False designates
9589               a non-DST time (note that this flag is only applicable for
9590               ambiguous times)
9591             - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are ambiguous times
9592             - 'raise' will raise an AmbiguousTimeError if there are ambiguous
9593               times.
9594         nonexistent : str, default 'raise'
9595             A nonexistent time does not exist in a particular timezone
9596             where clocks moved forward due to DST. Valid values are:
9597 
9598             - 'shift_forward' will shift the nonexistent time forward to the
9599               closest existing time
9600             - 'shift_backward' will shift the nonexistent time backward to the
9601               closest existing time
9602             - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are nonexistent times
9603             - timedelta objects will shift nonexistent times by the timedelta
9604             - 'raise' will raise an NonExistentTimeError if there are
9605               nonexistent times.
9606 
9607             .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
9608 
9609         Returns
9610         -------
9611         Series or DataFrame
9612             Same type as the input.
9613 
9614         Raises
9615         ------
9616         TypeError
9617             If the TimeSeries is tz-aware and tz is not None.
9618 
9619         Examples
9620         --------
9621         Localize local times:
9622 
9623         >>> s = pd.Series([1],
9624         ...               index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-09-15 01:30:00']))
9625         >>> s.tz_localize('CET')
9626         2018-09-15 01:30:00+02:00    1
9627         dtype: int64
9628 
9629         Be careful with DST changes. When there is sequential data, pandas
9630         can infer the DST time:
9631 
9632         >>> s = pd.Series(range(7),
9633         ...               index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-10-28 01:30:00',
9634         ...                                       '2018-10-28 02:00:00',
9635         ...                                       '2018-10-28 02:30:00',
9636         ...                                       '2018-10-28 02:00:00',
9637         ...                                       '2018-10-28 02:30:00',
9638         ...                                       '2018-10-28 03:00:00',
9639         ...                                       '2018-10-28 03:30:00']))
9640         >>> s.tz_localize('CET', ambiguous='infer')
9641         2018-10-28 01:30:00+02:00    0
9642         2018-10-28 02:00:00+02:00    1
9643         2018-10-28 02:30:00+02:00    2
9644         2018-10-28 02:00:00+01:00    3
9645         2018-10-28 02:30:00+01:00    4
9646         2018-10-28 03:00:00+01:00    5
9647         2018-10-28 03:30:00+01:00    6
9648         dtype: int64
9649 
9650         In some cases, inferring the DST is impossible. In such cases, you can
9651         pass an ndarray to the ambiguous parameter to set the DST explicitly
9652 
9653         >>> s = pd.Series(range(3),
9654         ...               index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-10-28 01:20:00',
9655         ...                                       '2018-10-28 02:36:00',
9656         ...                                       '2018-10-28 03:46:00']))
9657         >>> s.tz_localize('CET', ambiguous=np.array([True, True, False]))
9658         2018-10-28 01:20:00+02:00    0
9659         2018-10-28 02:36:00+02:00    1
9660         2018-10-28 03:46:00+01:00    2
9661         dtype: int64
9662 
9663         If the DST transition causes nonexistent times, you can shift these
9664         dates forward or backwards with a timedelta object or `'shift_forward'`
9665         or `'shift_backwards'`.
9666         >>> s = pd.Series(range(2),
9667         ...               index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2015-03-29 02:30:00',
9668         ...                                       '2015-03-29 03:30:00']))
9669         >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent='shift_forward')
9670         2015-03-29 03:00:00+02:00    0
9671         2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00    1
9672         dtype: int64
9673         >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent='shift_backward')
9674         2015-03-29 01:59:59.999999999+01:00    0
9675         2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00              1
9676         dtype: int64
9677         >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent=pd.Timedelta('1H'))
9678         2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00    0
9679         2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00    1
9680         dtype: int64
9681         """
9682         nonexistent_options = ("raise", "NaT", "shift_forward", "shift_backward")
9683         if nonexistent not in nonexistent_options and not isinstance(
9684             nonexistent, timedelta
9685         ):
9686             raise ValueError(
9687                 "The nonexistent argument must be one of 'raise', "
9688                 "'NaT', 'shift_forward', 'shift_backward' or "
9689                 "a timedelta object"
9690             )
9691 
9692         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
9693         ax = self._get_axis(axis)
9694 
9695         def _tz_localize(ax, tz, ambiguous, nonexistent):
9696             if not hasattr(ax, "tz_localize"):
9697                 if len(ax) > 0:
9698                     ax_name = self._get_axis_name(axis)
9699                     raise TypeError(
9700                         f"{ax_name} is not a valid DatetimeIndex or PeriodIndex"
9701                     )
9702                 else:
9703                     ax = DatetimeIndex([], tz=tz)
9704             else:
9705                 ax = ax.tz_localize(tz, ambiguous=ambiguous, nonexistent=nonexistent)
9706             return ax
9707 
9708         # if a level is given it must be a MultiIndex level or
9709         # equivalent to the axis name
9710         if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex):
9711             level = ax._get_level_number(level)
9712             new_level = _tz_localize(ax.levels[level], tz, ambiguous, nonexistent)
9713             ax = ax.set_levels(new_level, level=level)
9714         else:
9715             if level not in (None, 0, ax.name):
9716                 raise ValueError(f"The level {level} is not valid")
9717             ax = _tz_localize(ax, tz, ambiguous, nonexistent)
9718 
9719         result = self.copy(deep=copy)
9720         result = result.set_axis(ax, axis=axis, inplace=False)
9721         return result.__finalize__(self, method="tz_localize")
9722 
9723     # ----------------------------------------------------------------------
9724     # Numeric Methods
9725     def abs(self: FrameOrSeries) -> FrameOrSeries:
9726         """
9727         Return a Series/DataFrame with absolute numeric value of each element.
9728 
9729         This function only applies to elements that are all numeric.
9730 
9731         Returns
9732         -------
9733         abs
9734             Series/DataFrame containing the absolute value of each element.
9735 
9736         See Also
9737         --------
9738         numpy.absolute : Calculate the absolute value element-wise.
9739 
9740         Notes
9741         -----
9742         For ``complex`` inputs, ``1.2 + 1j``, the absolute value is
9743         :math:`\\sqrt{ a^2 + b^2 }`.
9744 
9745         Examples
9746         --------
9747         Absolute numeric values in a Series.
9748 
9749         >>> s = pd.Series([-1.10, 2, -3.33, 4])
9750         >>> s.abs()
9751         0    1.10
9752         1    2.00
9753         2    3.33
9754         3    4.00
9755         dtype: float64
9756 
9757         Absolute numeric values in a Series with complex numbers.
9758 
9759         >>> s = pd.Series([1.2 + 1j])
9760         >>> s.abs()
9761         0    1.56205
9762         dtype: float64
9763 
9764         Absolute numeric values in a Series with a Timedelta element.
9765 
9766         >>> s = pd.Series([pd.Timedelta('1 days')])
9767         >>> s.abs()
9768         0   1 days
9769         dtype: timedelta64[ns]
9770 
9771         Select rows with data closest to certain value using argsort (from
9772         `StackOverflow <https://stackoverflow.com/a/17758115>`__).
9773 
9774         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({
9775         ...     'a': [4, 5, 6, 7],
9776         ...     'b': [10, 20, 30, 40],
9777         ...     'c': [100, 50, -30, -50]
9778         ... })
9779         >>> df
9780              a    b    c
9781         0    4   10  100
9782         1    5   20   50
9783         2    6   30  -30
9784         3    7   40  -50
9785         >>> df.loc[(df.c - 43).abs().argsort()]
9786              a    b    c
9787         1    5   20   50
9788         0    4   10  100
9789         2    6   30  -30
9790         3    7   40  -50
9791         """
9792         return np.abs(self)
9793 
9794     def describe(
9795         self: FrameOrSeries, percentiles=None, include=None, exclude=None
9796     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
9797         """
9798         Generate descriptive statistics.
9799 
9800         Descriptive statistics include those that summarize the central
9801         tendency, dispersion and shape of a
9802         dataset's distribution, excluding ``NaN`` values.
9803 
9804         Analyzes both numeric and object series, as well
9805         as ``DataFrame`` column sets of mixed data types. The output
9806         will vary depending on what is provided. Refer to the notes
9807         below for more detail.
9808 
9809         Parameters
9810         ----------
9811         percentiles : list-like of numbers, optional
9812             The percentiles to include in the output. All should
9813             fall between 0 and 1. The default is
9814             ``[.25, .5, .75]``, which returns the 25th, 50th, and
9815             75th percentiles.
9816         include : 'all', list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional
9817             A white list of data types to include in the result. Ignored
9818             for ``Series``. Here are the options:
9819 
9820             - 'all' : All columns of the input will be included in the output.
9821             - A list-like of dtypes : Limits the results to the
9822               provided data types.
9823               To limit the result to numeric types submit
9824               ``numpy.number``. To limit it instead to object columns submit
9825               the ``numpy.object`` data type. Strings
9826               can also be used in the style of
9827               ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To
9828               select pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'``
9829             - None (default) : The result will include all numeric columns.
9830         exclude : list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional,
9831             A black list of data types to omit from the result. Ignored
9832             for ``Series``. Here are the options:
9833 
9834             - A list-like of dtypes : Excludes the provided data types
9835               from the result. To exclude numeric types submit
9836               ``numpy.number``. To exclude object columns submit the data
9837               type ``numpy.object``. Strings can also be used in the style of
9838               ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To
9839               exclude pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'``
9840             - None (default) : The result will exclude nothing.
9841 
9842         Returns
9843         -------
9844         Series or DataFrame
9845             Summary statistics of the Series or Dataframe provided.
9846 
9847         See Also
9848         --------
9849         DataFrame.count: Count number of non-NA/null observations.
9850         DataFrame.max: Maximum of the values in the object.
9851         DataFrame.min: Minimum of the values in the object.
9852         DataFrame.mean: Mean of the values.
9853         DataFrame.std: Standard deviation of the observations.
9854         DataFrame.select_dtypes: Subset of a DataFrame including/excluding
9855             columns based on their dtype.
9856 
9857         Notes
9858         -----
9859         For numeric data, the result's index will include ``count``,
9860         ``mean``, ``std``, ``min``, ``max`` as well as lower, ``50`` and
9861         upper percentiles. By default the lower percentile is ``25`` and the
9862         upper percentile is ``75``. The ``50`` percentile is the
9863         same as the median.
9864 
9865         For object data (e.g. strings or timestamps), the result's index
9866         will include ``count``, ``unique``, ``top``, and ``freq``. The ``top``
9867         is the most common value. The ``freq`` is the most common value's
9868         frequency. Timestamps also include the ``first`` and ``last`` items.
9869 
9870         If multiple object values have the highest count, then the
9871         ``count`` and ``top`` results will be arbitrarily chosen from
9872         among those with the highest count.
9873 
9874         For mixed data types provided via a ``DataFrame``, the default is to
9875         return only an analysis of numeric columns. If the dataframe consists
9876         only of object and categorical data without any numeric columns, the
9877         default is to return an analysis of both the object and categorical
9878         columns. If ``include='all'`` is provided as an option, the result
9879         will include a union of attributes of each type.
9880 
9881         The `include` and `exclude` parameters can be used to limit
9882         which columns in a ``DataFrame`` are analyzed for the output.
9883         The parameters are ignored when analyzing a ``Series``.
9884 
9885         Examples
9886         --------
9887         Describing a numeric ``Series``.
9888 
9889         >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3])
9890         >>> s.describe()
9891         count    3.0
9892         mean     2.0
9893         std      1.0
9894         min      1.0
9895         25%      1.5
9896         50%      2.0
9897         75%      2.5
9898         max      3.0
9899         dtype: float64
9900 
9901         Describing a categorical ``Series``.
9902 
9903         >>> s = pd.Series(['a', 'a', 'b', 'c'])
9904         >>> s.describe()
9905         count     4
9906         unique    3
9907         top       a
9908         freq      2
9909         dtype: object
9910 
9911         Describing a timestamp ``Series``.
9912 
9913         >>> s = pd.Series([
9914         ...   np.datetime64("2000-01-01"),
9915         ...   np.datetime64("2010-01-01"),
9916         ...   np.datetime64("2010-01-01")
9917         ... ])
9918         >>> s.describe()
9919         count                      3
9920         mean     2006-09-01 08:00:00
9921         min      2000-01-01 00:00:00
9922         25%      2004-12-31 12:00:00
9923         50%      2010-01-01 00:00:00
9924         75%      2010-01-01 00:00:00
9925         max      2010-01-01 00:00:00
9926         dtype: object
9927 
9928         Describing a ``DataFrame``. By default only numeric fields
9929         are returned.
9930 
9931         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'categorical': pd.Categorical(['d','e','f']),
9932         ...                    'numeric': [1, 2, 3],
9933         ...                    'object': ['a', 'b', 'c']
9934         ...                   })
9935         >>> df.describe()
9936                numeric
9937         count      3.0
9938         mean       2.0
9939         std        1.0
9940         min        1.0
9941         25%        1.5
9942         50%        2.0
9943         75%        2.5
9944         max        3.0
9945 
9946         Describing all columns of a ``DataFrame`` regardless of data type.
9947 
9948         >>> df.describe(include='all')  # doctest: +SKIP
9949                categorical  numeric object
9950         count            3      3.0      3
9951         unique           3      NaN      3
9952         top              f      NaN      a
9953         freq             1      NaN      1
9954         mean           NaN      2.0    NaN
9955         std            NaN      1.0    NaN
9956         min            NaN      1.0    NaN
9957         25%            NaN      1.5    NaN
9958         50%            NaN      2.0    NaN
9959         75%            NaN      2.5    NaN
9960         max            NaN      3.0    NaN
9961 
9962         Describing a column from a ``DataFrame`` by accessing it as
9963         an attribute.
9964 
9965         >>> df.numeric.describe()
9966         count    3.0
9967         mean     2.0
9968         std      1.0
9969         min      1.0
9970         25%      1.5
9971         50%      2.0
9972         75%      2.5
9973         max      3.0
9974         Name: numeric, dtype: float64
9975 
9976         Including only numeric columns in a ``DataFrame`` description.
9977 
9978         >>> df.describe(include=[np.number])
9979                numeric
9980         count      3.0
9981         mean       2.0
9982         std        1.0
9983         min        1.0
9984         25%        1.5
9985         50%        2.0
9986         75%        2.5
9987         max        3.0
9988 
9989         Including only string columns in a ``DataFrame`` description.
9990 
9991         >>> df.describe(include=[np.object])  # doctest: +SKIP
9992                object
9993         count       3
9994         unique      3
9995         top         a
9996         freq        1
9997 
9998         Including only categorical columns from a ``DataFrame`` description.
9999 
10000         >>> df.describe(include=['category'])
10001                categorical
10002         count            3
10003         unique           3
10004         top              f
10005         freq             1
10006 
10007         Excluding numeric columns from a ``DataFrame`` description.
10008 
10009         >>> df.describe(exclude=[np.number])  # doctest: +SKIP
10010                categorical object
10011         count            3      3
10012         unique           3      3
10013         top              f      a
10014         freq             1      1
10015 
10016         Excluding object columns from a ``DataFrame`` description.
10017 
10018         >>> df.describe(exclude=[np.object])  # doctest: +SKIP
10019                categorical  numeric
10020         count            3      3.0
10021         unique           3      NaN
10022         top              f      NaN
10023         freq             1      NaN
10024         mean           NaN      2.0
10025         std            NaN      1.0
10026         min            NaN      1.0
10027         25%            NaN      1.5
10028         50%            NaN      2.0
10029         75%            NaN      2.5
10030         max            NaN      3.0
10031         """
10032         if self.ndim == 2 and self.columns.size == 0:
10033             raise ValueError("Cannot describe a DataFrame without columns")
10034 
10035         if percentiles is not None:
10036             # explicit conversion of `percentiles` to list
10037             percentiles = list(percentiles)
10038 
10039             # get them all to be in [0, 1]
10040             validate_percentile(percentiles)
10041 
10042             # median should always be included
10043             if 0.5 not in percentiles:
10044                 percentiles.append(0.5)
10045             percentiles = np.asarray(percentiles)
10046         else:
10047             percentiles = np.array([0.25, 0.5, 0.75])
10048 
10049         # sort and check for duplicates
10050         unique_pcts = np.unique(percentiles)
10051         if len(unique_pcts) < len(percentiles):
10052             raise ValueError("percentiles cannot contain duplicates")
10053         percentiles = unique_pcts
10054 
10055         formatted_percentiles = format_percentiles(percentiles)
10056 
10057         def describe_numeric_1d(series):
10058             stat_index = (
10059                 ["count", "mean", "std", "min"] + formatted_percentiles + ["max"]
10060             )
10061             d = (
10062                 [series.count(), series.mean(), series.std(), series.min()]
10063                 + series.quantile(percentiles).tolist()
10064                 + [series.max()]
10065             )
10066             return pd.Series(d, index=stat_index, name=series.name)
10067 
10068         def describe_categorical_1d(data):
10069             names = ["count", "unique"]
10070             objcounts = data.value_counts()
10071             count_unique = len(objcounts[objcounts != 0])
10072             result = [data.count(), count_unique]
10073             dtype = None
10074             if result[1] > 0:
10075                 top, freq = objcounts.index[0], objcounts.iloc[0]
10076                 names += ["top", "freq"]
10077                 result += [top, freq]
10078 
10079             # If the DataFrame is empty, set 'top' and 'freq' to None
10080             # to maintain output shape consistency
10081             else:
10082                 names += ["top", "freq"]
10083                 result += [np.nan, np.nan]
10084                 dtype = "object"
10085 
10086             return pd.Series(result, index=names, name=data.name, dtype=dtype)
10087 
10088         def describe_timestamp_1d(data):
10089             # GH-30164
10090             stat_index = ["count", "mean", "min"] + formatted_percentiles + ["max"]
10091             d = (
10092                 [data.count(), data.mean(), data.min()]
10093                 + data.quantile(percentiles).tolist()
10094                 + [data.max()]
10095             )
10096             return pd.Series(d, index=stat_index, name=data.name)
10097 
10098         def describe_1d(data):
10099             if is_bool_dtype(data.dtype):
10100                 return describe_categorical_1d(data)
10101             elif is_numeric_dtype(data):
10102                 return describe_numeric_1d(data)
10103             elif is_datetime64_any_dtype(data.dtype):
10104                 return describe_timestamp_1d(data)
10105             elif is_timedelta64_dtype(data.dtype):
10106                 return describe_numeric_1d(data)
10107             else:
10108                 return describe_categorical_1d(data)
10109 
10110         if self.ndim == 1:
10111             return describe_1d(self)
10112         elif (include is None) and (exclude is None):
10113             # when some numerics are found, keep only numerics
10114             data = self.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])
10115             if len(data.columns) == 0:
10116                 data = self
10117         elif include == "all":
10118             if exclude is not None:
10119                 msg = "exclude must be None when include is 'all'"
10120                 raise ValueError(msg)
10121             data = self
10122         else:
10123             data = self.select_dtypes(include=include, exclude=exclude)
10124 
10125         ldesc = [describe_1d(s) for _, s in data.items()]
10126         # set a convenient order for rows
10127         names: List[Label] = []
10128         ldesc_indexes = sorted((x.index for x in ldesc), key=len)
10129         for idxnames in ldesc_indexes:
10130             for name in idxnames:
10131                 if name not in names:
10132                     names.append(name)
10133 
10134         d = pd.concat([x.reindex(names, copy=False) for x in ldesc], axis=1, sort=False)
10135         d.columns = data.columns.copy()
10136         return d
10137 
10138     _shared_docs[
10139         "pct_change"
10140     ] = """
10141         Percentage change between the current and a prior element.
10142 
10143         Computes the percentage change from the immediately previous row by
10144         default. This is useful in comparing the percentage of change in a time
10145         series of elements.
10146 
10147         Parameters
10148         ----------
10149         periods : int, default 1
10150             Periods to shift for forming percent change.
10151         fill_method : str, default 'pad'
10152             How to handle NAs before computing percent changes.
10153         limit : int, default None
10154             The number of consecutive NAs to fill before stopping.
10155         freq : DateOffset, timedelta, or str, optional
10156             Increment to use from time series API (e.g. 'M' or BDay()).
10157         **kwargs
10158             Additional keyword arguments are passed into
10159             `DataFrame.shift` or `Series.shift`.
10160 
10161         Returns
10162         -------
10163         chg : Series or DataFrame
10164             The same type as the calling object.
10165 
10166         See Also
10167         --------
10168         Series.diff : Compute the difference of two elements in a Series.
10169         DataFrame.diff : Compute the difference of two elements in a DataFrame.
10170         Series.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods.
10171         DataFrame.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods.
10172 
10173         Examples
10174         --------
10175         **Series**
10176 
10177         >>> s = pd.Series([90, 91, 85])
10178         >>> s
10179         0    90
10180         1    91
10181         2    85
10182         dtype: int64
10183 
10184         >>> s.pct_change()
10185         0         NaN
10186         1    0.011111
10187         2   -0.065934
10188         dtype: float64
10189 
10190         >>> s.pct_change(periods=2)
10191         0         NaN
10192         1         NaN
10193         2   -0.055556
10194         dtype: float64
10195 
10196         See the percentage change in a Series where filling NAs with last
10197         valid observation forward to next valid.
10198 
10199         >>> s = pd.Series([90, 91, None, 85])
10200         >>> s
10201         0    90.0
10202         1    91.0
10203         2     NaN
10204         3    85.0
10205         dtype: float64
10206 
10207         >>> s.pct_change(fill_method='ffill')
10208         0         NaN
10209         1    0.011111
10210         2    0.000000
10211         3   -0.065934
10212         dtype: float64
10213 
10214         **DataFrame**
10215 
10216         Percentage change in French franc, Deutsche Mark, and Italian lira from
10217         1980-01-01 to 1980-03-01.
10218 
10219         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({
10220         ...     'FR': [4.0405, 4.0963, 4.3149],
10221         ...     'GR': [1.7246, 1.7482, 1.8519],
10222         ...     'IT': [804.74, 810.01, 860.13]},
10223         ...     index=['1980-01-01', '1980-02-01', '1980-03-01'])
10224         >>> df
10225                         FR      GR      IT
10226         1980-01-01  4.0405  1.7246  804.74
10227         1980-02-01  4.0963  1.7482  810.01
10228         1980-03-01  4.3149  1.8519  860.13
10229 
10230         >>> df.pct_change()
10231                           FR        GR        IT
10232         1980-01-01       NaN       NaN       NaN
10233         1980-02-01  0.013810  0.013684  0.006549
10234         1980-03-01  0.053365  0.059318  0.061876

10236         Percentage of change in GOOG and APPL stock volume. Shows computing
10237         the percentage change between columns.
10238 
10239         >>> df = pd.DataFrame({

10241         ...     '2015': [1500923, 40912316],

10252         APPL   NaN  0.337604  0.012002

10254 
10255     @Appender(_shared_docs["pct_change"] % _shared_doc_kwargs)
10256     def pct_change(
10257         self: FrameOrSeries,
10258         periods=1,
10259         fill_method="pad",
10260         limit=None,
10261         freq=None,
10262         **kwargs,
10263     ) -> FrameOrSeries:
10264         # TODO: Not sure if above is correct - need someone to confirm.
10265         axis = self._get_axis_number(kwargs.pop("axis", self._stat_axis_name))
10266         if fill_method is None:
10267             data = self
10268         else:
10269             _data = self.fillna(method=fill_method, axis=axis, limit=limit)
10270             assert _data is not None  # needed for mypy
10271             data = _data
10272 
10273         rs = data.div(data.shift(periods=periods, freq=freq, axis=axis, **kwargs)) - 1
10274         if freq is not None:
10275             # Shift method is implemented differently when freq is not None
10276             # We want to restore the original index
10277             rs = rs.loc[~rs.index.duplicated()]
10278             rs = rs.reindex_like(data)
10279         return rs
10280 
10281     def _agg_by_level(self, name, axis=0, level=0, skipna=True, **kwargs):
10282         if axis is None:
10283             raise ValueError("Must specify 'axis' when aggregating by level.")
10284         grouped = self.groupby(level=level, axis=axis, sort=False)
10285         if hasattr(grouped, name) and skipna:
10286             return getattr(grouped, name)(**kwargs)
10287         axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
10288         method = getattr(type(self), name)
10289         applyf = lambda x: method(x, axis=axis, skipna=skipna, **kwargs)
10290         return grouped.aggregate(applyf)

10500             "If you want the *index* of the maximum, use ``idxmax``. This is"
10501             "the equivalent of the ``numpy.ndarray`` method ``argmax``.",
10502             func=nanops.nanmax,
10503             see_also=_stat_func_see_also,
10504             examples=_max_examples,
10505         )
10506         cls.min = _make_stat_function(
10507             cls,
10508             "min",
10509             name1=name1,
10510             name2=name2,
10511             axis_descr=axis_descr,
10512             desc="Return the minimum of the values for the requested axis.\n\n"
10513             "If you want the *index* of the minimum, use ``idxmin``. This is"
10514             "the equivalent of the ``numpy.ndarray`` method ``argmin``.",
10515             func=nanops.nanmin,
10516             see_also=_stat_func_see_also,
10517             examples=_min_examples,
10518         )
10519 
10520     @classmethod
10521     def _add_series_or_dataframe_operations(cls):
10522         """
10523         Add the series or dataframe only operations to the cls; evaluate
10524         the doc strings again.
10525         """
10526         from pandas.core.window import EWM, Expanding, Rolling, Window
10527 
10528         @doc(Rolling)
10529         def rolling(
10530             self,
10531             window,
10532             min_periods=None,
10533             center=False,
10534             win_type=None,
10535             on=None,
10536             axis=0,
10537             closed=None,
10538         ):
10539             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
10540 
10541             if win_type is not None:
10542                 return Window(
10543                     self,
10544                     window=window,
10545                     min_periods=min_periods,
10546                     center=center,
10547                     win_type=win_type,
10548                     on=on,
10549                     axis=axis,
10550                     closed=closed,
10551                 )
10552 
10553             return Rolling(
10554                 self,
10555                 window=window,
10556                 min_periods=min_periods,
10557                 center=center,
10558                 win_type=win_type,
10559                 on=on,
10560                 axis=axis,
10561                 closed=closed,
10562             )
10563 
10564         cls.rolling = rolling
10565 
10566         @doc(Expanding)
10567         def expanding(self, min_periods=1, center=False, axis=0):
10568             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
10569             return Expanding(self, min_periods=min_periods, center=center, axis=axis)
10570 
10571         cls.expanding = expanding
10572 
10573         @doc(EWM)
10574         def ewm(
10575             self,
10576             com=None,
10577             span=None,
10578             halflife=None,
10579             alpha=None,
10580             min_periods=0,
10581             adjust=True,
10582             ignore_na=False,
10583             axis=0,
10584         ):
10585             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
10586             return EWM(
10587                 self,
10588                 com=com,
10589                 span=span,
10590                 halflife=halflife,
10591                 alpha=alpha,
10592                 min_periods=min_periods,
10593                 adjust=adjust,
10594                 ignore_na=ignore_na,
10595                 axis=axis,
10596             )
10597 
10598         cls.ewm = ewm
10599 
10600     @Appender(_shared_docs["transform"] % dict(axis="", **_shared_doc_kwargs))
10601     def transform(self, func, *args, **kwargs):
10602         result = self.agg(func, *args, **kwargs)
10603         if is_scalar(result) or len(result) != len(self):
10604             raise ValueError("transforms cannot produce aggregated results")
10605 
10606         return result

10626     def _find_valid_index(self, how: str):
10627         """
10628         Retrieves the index of the first valid value.
10629 
10630         Parameters
10631         ----------
10632         how : {'first', 'last'}
10633             Use this parameter to change between the first or last valid index.
10634 
10635         Returns
10636         -------
10637         idx_first_valid : type of index
10638         """
10639         idxpos = find_valid_index(self._values, how)
10640         if idxpos is None:
10641             return None
10642         return self.index[idxpos]
10643 
10644     @Appender(
10645         _shared_docs["valid_index"] % {"position": "first", "klass": "Series/DataFrame"}
10646     )
10647     def first_valid_index(self):
10648         return self._find_valid_index("first")

10657 def _doc_parms(cls):
10658     """Return a tuple of the doc parms."""
10659     axis_descr = (
10660         f"{{{', '.join(f'{a} ({i})' for i, a in enumerate(cls._AXIS_ORDERS))}}}"
10661     )
10662     name = cls._constructor_sliced.__name__ if cls._AXIS_LEN > 1 else "scalar"
10663     name2 = cls.__name__
10664     return axis_descr, name, name2

10781 _all_examples = """\
10782 Examples
10783 --------
10784 **Series**
10785 
10786 >>> pd.Series([True, True]).all()
10787 True
10788 >>> pd.Series([True, False]).all()
10789 False
10790 >>> pd.Series([]).all()
10791 True
10792 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).all()
10793 True
10794 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).all(skipna=False)
10795 True
10796 
10797 **DataFrames**
10798 
10799 Create a dataframe from a dictionary.
10800 
10801 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'col1': [True, True], 'col2': [True, False]})
10802 >>> df
10803    col1   col2
10804 0  True   True
10805 1  True  False
10806 
10807 Default behaviour checks if column-wise values all return True.
10808 
10809 >>> df.all()
10810 col1     True
10811 col2    False
10812 dtype: bool
10813 
10814 Specify ``axis='columns'`` to check if row-wise values all return True.
10815 
10816 >>> df.all(axis='columns')
10817 0     True
10818 1    False
10819 dtype: bool
10820 
10821 Or ``axis=None`` for whether every value is True.
10822 
10823 >>> df.all(axis=None)
10824 False
10825 """

10881 dtype: float64

10884

10886 0    2.0
10887 1    NaN
10888 2    2.0
10889 3   -1.0
10890 4   -1.0
10891 dtype: float64
10892 
10893 To include NA values in the operation, use ``skipna=False``
10894 
10895 >>> s.cummin(skipna=False)
10896 0    2.0
10897 1    NaN
10898 2    NaN
10899 3    NaN
10900 4    NaN
10901 dtype: float64
10902 
10903 **DataFrame**
10904 
10905 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[2.0, 1.0],
10906 ...                    [3.0, np.nan],
10907 ...                    [1.0, 0.0]],
10908 ...                    columns=list('AB'))
10909 >>> df
10910      A    B
10911 0  2.0  1.0
10912 1  3.0  NaN
10913 2  1.0  0.0
10914 
10915 By default, iterates over rows and finds the minimum
10916 in each column. This is equivalent to ``axis=None`` or ``axis='index'``.
10917 
10918 >>> df.cummin()
10919      A    B
10920 0  2.0  1.0
10921 1  2.0  NaN
10922 2  1.0  0.0
10923 
10924 To iterate over columns and find the minimum in each row,
10925 use ``axis=1``
10926 
10927 >>> df.cummin(axis=1)
10928      A    B
10929 0  2.0  1.0
10930 1  3.0  NaN
10931 2  1.0  0.0

11139 _any_desc = """\
11140 Return whether any element is True, potentially over an axis.
11141 
11142 Returns False unless there at least one element within a series or
11143 along a Dataframe axis that is True or equivalent (e.g. non-zero or
11144 non-empty)."""
11145 
11146 _any_examples = """\
11147 Examples
11148 --------
11149 **Series**
11150 
11151 For Series input, the output is a scalar indicating whether any element
11152 is True.
11153 
11154 >>> pd.Series([False, False]).any()
11155 False
11156 >>> pd.Series([True, False]).any()
11157 True
11158 >>> pd.Series([]).any()
11159 False
11160 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).any()
11161 False
11162 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).any(skipna=False)
11163 True
11164 
11165 **DataFrame**
11166 
11167 Whether each column contains at least one True element (the default).
11168 
11169 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2], "B": [0, 2], "C": [0, 0]})
11170 >>> df
11171    A  B  C
11172 0  1  0  0
11173 1  2  2  0
11174 
11175 >>> df.any()
11176 A     True
11177 B     True
11178 C    False
11179 dtype: bool
11180 
11181 Aggregating over the columns.
11182 
11183 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [True, False], "B": [1, 2]})
11184 >>> df
11185        A  B
11186 0   True  1
11187 1  False  2
11188 
11189 >>> df.any(axis='columns')
11190 0    True
11191 1    True
11192 dtype: bool
11193 
11194 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [True, False], "B": [1, 0]})
11195 >>> df
11196        A  B
11197 0   True  1
11198 1  False  0
11199 
11200 >>> df.any(axis='columns')
11201 0    True
11202 1    False
11203 dtype: bool
11204 
11205 Aggregating over the entire DataFrame with ``axis=None``.
11206 
11207 >>> df.any(axis=None)
11208 True
11209 
11210 `any` for an empty DataFrame is an empty Series.
11211 
11212 >>> pd.DataFrame([]).any()
11213 Series([], dtype: bool)
11214 """

11256 _sum_examples += """
11257 
11258 By default, the sum of an empty or all-NA Series is ``0``.
11259 
11260 >>> pd.Series([]).sum()  # min_count=0 is the default
11261 0.0
11262 
11263 This can be controlled with the ``min_count`` parameter. For example, if
11264 you'd like the sum of an empty series to be NaN, pass ``min_count=1``.
11265 
11266 >>> pd.Series([]).sum(min_count=1)
11267 nan
11268 
11269 Thanks to the ``skipna`` parameter, ``min_count`` handles all-NA and
11270 empty series identically.
11271 
11272 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).sum()
11273 0.0
11274 
11275 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).sum(min_count=1)
11276 nan"""

11287 
11288 See Also
11289 --------
11290 Series.sum : Return the sum.
11291 Series.min : Return the minimum.
11292 Series.max : Return the maximum.
11293 Series.idxmin : Return the index of the minimum.

11295 DataFrame.sum : Return the sum over the requested axis.

11300 
11301 _prod_examples = """
11302 
11303 Examples
11304 --------
11305 By default, the product of an empty or all-NA Series is ``1``
11306 
11307 >>> pd.Series([]).prod()
11308 1.0
11309 
11310 This can be controlled with the ``min_count`` parameter
11311 
11312 >>> pd.Series([]).prod(min_count=1)
11313 nan
11314 
11315 Thanks to the ``skipna`` parameter, ``min_count`` handles all-NA and
11316 empty series identically.
11317 
11318 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).prod()
11319 1.0
11320 
11321 >>> pd.Series([np.nan]).prod(min_count=1)
11322 nan"""
11323 
11324 _min_count_stub = """\
11325 min_count : int, default 0
11326     The required number of valid values to perform the operation. If fewer than
11327     ``min_count`` non-NA values are present the result will be NA.
11328 
11329     .. versionadded:: 0.22.0
11330 
11331        Added with the default being 0. This means the sum of an all-NA
11332        or empty Series is 0, and the product of an all-NA or empty
11333        Series is 1.
11334 """

11337 def _make_min_count_stat_function(
11338     cls,
11339     name: str,
11340     name1: str,
11341     name2: str,
11342     axis_descr: str,
11343     desc: str,
11344     func: Callable,
11345     see_also: str = "",
11346     examples: str = "",
11347 ) -> Callable:
11348     @Substitution(
11349         desc=desc,
11350         name1=name1,
11351         name2=name2,
11352         axis_descr=axis_descr,
11353         min_count=_min_count_stub,
11354         see_also=see_also,
11355         examples=examples,
11356     )
11357     @Appender(_num_doc)
11358     def stat_func(
11359         self,
11360         axis=None,
11361         skipna=None,
11362         level=None,
11363         numeric_only=None,
11364         min_count=0,
11365         **kwargs,
11366     ):
11367         if name == "sum":
11368             nv.validate_sum(tuple(), kwargs)
11369         elif name == "prod":
11370             nv.validate_prod(tuple(), kwargs)
11371         else:
11372             nv.validate_stat_func(tuple(), kwargs, fname=name)
11373         if skipna is None:
11374             skipna = True
11375         if axis is None:
11376             axis = self._stat_axis_number
11377         if level is not None:
11378             return self._agg_by_level(
11379                 name, axis=axis, level=level, skipna=skipna, min_count=min_count
11380             )
11381         return self._reduce(
11382             func,
11383             name=name,
11384             axis=axis,
11385             skipna=skipna,
11386             numeric_only=numeric_only,
11387             min_count=min_count,
11388         )
11389 
11390     return set_function_name(stat_func, name, cls)

11393 def _make_stat_function(
11394     cls,
11395     name: str,
11396     name1: str,
11397     name2: str,
11398     axis_descr: str,
11399     desc: str,
11400     func: Callable,
11401     see_also: str = "",
11402     examples: str = "",
11403 ) -> Callable:
11404     @Substitution(
11405         desc=desc,
11406         name1=name1,
11407         name2=name2,
11408         axis_descr=axis_descr,
11409         min_count="",
11410         see_also=see_also,
11411         examples=examples,
11412     )
11413     @Appender(_num_doc)
11414     def stat_func(
11415         self, axis=None, skipna=None, level=None, numeric_only=None, **kwargs
11416     ):
11417         if name == "median":
11418             nv.validate_median(tuple(), kwargs)
11419         else:
11420             nv.validate_stat_func(tuple(), kwargs, fname=name)
11421         if skipna is None:
11422             skipna = True
11423         if axis is None:
11424             axis = self._stat_axis_number
11425         if level is not None:
11426             return self._agg_by_level(name, axis=axis, level=level, skipna=skipna)
11427         return self._reduce(
11428             func, name=name, axis=axis, skipna=skipna, numeric_only=numeric_only
11429         )
11430 
11431     return set_function_name(stat_func, name, cls)

11458 def _make_cum_function(
11459     cls,
11460     name: str,
11461     name1: str,
11462     name2: str,
11463     axis_descr: str,
11464     desc: str,
11465     accum_func: Callable,
11466     accum_func_name: str,
11467     examples: str,
11468 ) -> Callable:
11469     @Substitution(
11470         desc=desc,
11471         name1=name1,
11472         name2=name2,
11473         axis_descr=axis_descr,
11474         accum_func_name=accum_func_name,
11475         examples=examples,
11476     )
11477     @Appender(_cnum_doc)
11478     def cum_func(self, axis=None, skipna=True, *args, **kwargs):
11479         skipna = nv.validate_cum_func_with_skipna(skipna, args, kwargs, name)
11480         if axis is None:
11481             axis = self._stat_axis_number
11482         else:
11483             axis = self._get_axis_number(axis)
11484 
11485         if axis == 1:
11486             return cum_func(self.T, axis=0, skipna=skipna, *args, **kwargs).T
11487 
11488         def block_accum_func(blk_values):
11489             values = blk_values.T if hasattr(blk_values, "T") else blk_values
11490 
11491             result = nanops.na_accum_func(values, accum_func, skipna=skipna)
11492 
11493             result = result.T if hasattr(result, "T") else result
11494             return result
11495 
11496         result = self._mgr.apply(block_accum_func)
11497 
11498         return self._constructor(result).__finalize__(self, method=name)
11499 
11500     return set_function_name(cum_func, name, cls)

11523     )
11524     @Appender(_bool_doc)

11526         nv.validate_logical_func(tuple(), kwargs, fname=name)

11533         return self._reduce(
11534             func,
11535             name=name,

11537             skipna=skipna,
11538             numeric_only=bool_only,
